<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Oscars-Wilder 1stLd-Writethru a0754 04-11 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oscars-Wilder, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0754,0417</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs acceptance quotes after 3rd pvs bgng
``Wilder, 81''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Film legend Billy Wilder, a six-time Oscar
winner for such films as ``The Lost Weekend'' and ``The
Apartment,'' on Monday night became the 25th recipient of the
Motion Picture Academy's Irving G. Thalberg Award.
   The award goes to ``a creative producer whose body of work
reflects a consistently high quality of motion picture
production.'' It is given only when the Academy of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences Board of Directors decides there is a deserving
recipient.
   Wilder, 81, has had a movie career of nearly 60 years, during
which he has been nominated for an Oscar 21 times.
   ``As I look back, I've lived a charmed life,'' Wilder said,
after being honored by the audience with a standing ovation.
   Wilder recounted how he had left Berlin to escape the Nazis, and
was granted a chance to stay in the United States by a consular
official in Mexicali, Mexico, who asked Wilder what he did for a
living. Upon hearing Wilder wrote movies, the official stamped his
passport and said, ``Write some good ones.
   ``That was 54 years ago, I've tried ever since,'' Wilder said.
   In 1961, he became the first person to win three Oscars at once
for producing, directing and co-writing on ``The Apartment,'' best
picture for 1960.
   Wilder's career began in Germany and continued after he fled the
Nazis and came to the United States in 1933. His mother,
grandmother and stepfather died at Auschwitz.
   When he arrived in Hollywood, he spoke fewer than 100 words of
English and took up residence in the ladies' room of the Chateau
Marmont Hotel.
   Wilder won Academy Awards for both directing and co-writing
``The Lost Weekend'' in 1945. He won a screenwriting award for
``Sunset Boulevard'' along with Charles Brackett and D.M. Marshman
Jr.
   The Thalberg award has been presented 28 times, sometimes more
than once to the same individual.
   Steven Spielberg received it last year. Darryl F. Zanuck won the
award three times and Hal B. Wallis twice, meaning it has gone to
25 people since it was established in 1937. Rules now prohibit a
person from receiving the award more than once.
   Thalberg was an MGM production chief who died at age 37 but left
a legacy of elevating the artistic quality of film with such movies
as ``The Good Earth'' and ``Romeo and Juliet.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
