<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CoalTheater     04-11 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coal Theater,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Theater Built By Coal Miners Opens As Fine Arts School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLLINSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When this old mining town was booming
with coal, men put aside their picks to construct a theater. Today,
the miners are few but the structure still stands _ now as a school
of performing arts.
   And as a proper salute to the people who worked underground in
Southern Illinois, organizers of the school have dedicated it to a
famous coal miner's daughter, country singer Loretta Lynn.
   ``We want to help promote local talent,'' said artistic director
Ilene Farrell. ``We want to benefit the community. That's what
we're here for, to benefit everyone in the arts.''
   The three-story building, named the Miners Live Theater and
completed in 1918 by members of United Mine Workers Local 264, was
used for labor meetings and vaudeville shows.
   The theater's past is intertwined with the region's coal-mining
history. According to literature about the building, the first mine
in this town of 20,000 residents, 15 miles east of St. Louis, was
established in 1857.
   The industry led to the town's growth ``and by 1886 a man could
walk underground through connecting tunnels between the mines from
one edge of the city limits to the other,'' literature says.
   ``Mining and Collinsville were almost synonymous terms.''
   The coal-mining industry slowly started to wane, however, and in
1969, Miners Live was sold to a private company, which turned it
into a movie house.
   Two years ago, Bloomer Amusement Co. closed the 700-seat theater
and it sat idle until February when Jean Spurlock reopened it and
decided to bring in live acts and launch a performing arts school
and production company.
   The building still needs plenty of renovation. The seats have
red strands of tape covering cracked vinyl upholstery. A walk up
the stairs to the balcony shows walls with peeling paint.
   Elevated box seats flank each side of the stage and an orchestra
pit is located in front.
   By starting the school and hiring big-name entertainers to
perform at the site, Ms. Farrell believes Miners Live will gain
recognition.
   ``My gut feeling is that it's doing well already, that the sky's
the limit,'' she said.
   Ms. Farrell said the fine arts school will feature instruction
in dance, theater, modeling, singing, music, and playwriting. She
has assembled a 25-member staff.
   So far, 50 students have signed up and classes could start this
month at the Loretta Lynn Artistic Art Center and School, she said.
   ``It's going to be a launching pad for some professional careers
_ hopefully,'' Ms. Farrell said.
   The town is glad to see the doors reopen. Ms. Lynn was on hand
April 1 for dedication ceremonies.
   ``It was part of Collinsville culture for so long,'' Ms.
Spurlock said. ``Most people think they have to go to Las Vegas, or
Los Angeles or New York. But like I said, there's nothing in the
Midwest to compare with what's gonna' be happening here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880411-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 0030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Ties Bjt   04-11 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Ties, Bjt,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tiespeak: The Way To A Man's Psyche</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clothes may make the man, but his tie can reveal
his innermost secrets.
   The color, pattern and style of a man's necktie all provide
clues to his personality and lifestyle, says the Guild of British
Tiemakers, representing 30 manufacturers of ``the British tie,''
that sartorial symbol of the Old Boy Network.
   ``As eyes are reputedly the mirrors of the soul, so ties are the
talisman of the image, a statement by the wearer of their
personality and individuality, an indication of their temperament
and mood, a symbol of the social set in which he does or wants to
belong, a guide to how the wearer sees himself or would like others
to see him,'' according to the guild's survey.
   To help tie wearers and watchers interpret some of the subtle
messages, the guild has issued a guide to ``tiespeak.''
   ``If you want to come across as a strong, confident extrovert
person with strong opinions, choose a brilliantly colored tie or
one with an exaggerated pattern or motif,'' it says.
   ``A man who wears a tie in a plain light color runs the danger
of being a professional Mr. Nice, someone who likes to amuse and
entertain, an arranger of matters rather than a doer.''
   The ``more glowing'' the color of a tie, the more
money-motivated the wearer is likely to be, the guide says. A plain
dark tie, on the other hand, indicates a secretive man who keeps
more than his tie close to his chest.
   The guide says a tie with light and dark stripes of equal width
is the mark of a fence-sitter.
   Wide, light stripes on a dark background suggest the wearer
thinks the best of people and accepts them at face value, while
pessimists generally go for wide, dark stripes on a light
background.
   Multicolored, multiwidth stripes indicate someone who'd love to
do something daring _ if only he dared.
   A striped tie also can blurt out which side of the Atlantic
Ocean a man hails from. American tie stripes run from the right
shoulder down toward the left, the opposite of those on a European
tie.
   A tie with dark spots on a light background indicates ``a
wheeler-dealer,'' while light spots on a dark background suggest
``a sheep in wolf's clothing,'' the guide says.
   ``Small, neat geometric patterns are taken to indicate a
planner, a man who likes to create order out of chaos, probably a
good administrator,'' it says.
   A small paisley pattern suggests an upholder of tradition, while
a large paisly print suggests a hedger of bets.
   Ties give away other secrets.
   In Britain, a man's personal history can be traced through the
ties in his closet, revealing his school, club and military
background.
   Every British school has its own design, usually striped with
the school colors, which every schoolboy wears as part of his
uniform.
   Upon graduation he moves up to an ``Old School Tie,''
identifying his alma mater. He also may collect a regimental tie,
with symbolic colors and crests.
   The colors of the Royal Military Academy's tie, for example,
represent the ingredients of gunpowder _ yellow for sulphur, blue
for saltpeter and black for carbon. The Royal Tank Corps tie
represents the brown mud, red blood and green fields of Flanders,
the World War I battlefield.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880411-0014 </DOCNO>
