<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 0032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0777 04-11 1273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0777,1,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson, Gore Conciliatory; Cuomo Still Draws Attention</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS new grafs 39-40 bgng: On Sunday ..., with Cuomo
elaborating on draft.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson and Sen. Albert Gore Jr. sounded
conciliatory notes Sunday as they campaigned for support in New
York's Democratic presidential primary, a contest in which the
active candidates often had to compete for attention with
non-candidate Mario Cuomo.
   Meanwhile, the front-runner in the contest, Gov. Michael Dukakis
of Massachusetts, took the day off to celebrate Greek Easter with
his family.
   Also taking a day off was Vice President George Bush, whose path
to the Republican presidential nomination is clear of serious
opposition. While GOP rival Pat Robertson remains in the race, the
former television evangelist has conceded he has no chance to
overcome Bush's long lead in the race.
   Gore and Jackson were interviewed on the CBS show ``Face the
Nation,'' and played down their differences, which have appeared
more heated as the New York campaign got under way.
   Jackson also said that if elected president he would not meet
again with Yasser Arafat, the leader of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   He said a meeting he had with Arafat several years ago was ``for
the sole purpose of challenging him to change his posture and move
toward a mutual recognition policy with Israel.''
   That meeting with Arafat has been a focus of criticism of
Jackson by Jewish leaders in New York.
   Gore campaigned in heavily Jewish neighborhoods in Brooklyn
Sunday and received the endorsement of state Assemblyman Dov
Hikind, who told the crowd, many of them wearing the traditional
black hats of the Hasidim: ``We want to understand when one of the
candidates has embraced Yasser Arafat.''
   At that, the crowd erupted into loud boos.
   Hikind described Gore as ``the only one who has had the courage
to criticize Jackson.'' He said that Dukakis supporters were
``telling us we should reward Dukakis for his silence.''
   In his brief remarks to the crowd, Gore steered clear of comment
about Jackson and told the crowd that in his years in Congress, ``I
have stood fast in support of Israel and a strong U.S.-Israeli
relationship.''
   Gore then took a walking tour for about 10 blocks down 13th
Avenue, a street lined with kosher food shops and a variety of
other small businesses.
   Mayor Edward Koch said earlier in the week that Jewish voters
and other supporters of Israel would ``have to be crazy'' to vote
for Jackson in the primary.
   Gore had made one of the strongest direct attacks of the
campaign on Jackson when he said recently that the nation was
looking for leadership not ``a preacher in the White House.''
   Jackson supporters bristled at the comment and called it racist.
   Asked if he agreed, Jackson said, ``That's not my basic
position. There are race-based questions; his is not a race-based
challenge and I accept it in that spirit, in part, because I
respect Al Gore quite a bit as a person.''
   When asked if he thought Gore was being unfair, Jackson also
demurred.
   ``No, I think Al Gore has too much character to be categorically
unfair,'' he replied.
   While, Gore said he had no intention of altering the aggressive
tone of his campaign, the Tennessee senator said he thought all the
candidates ``have grown'' during the long debate.
   As for his approach to the campaign, Gore said, ``I have no
plans to change my basic campaign posture at all.''
   Jackson spent Sunday morning preaching in the Abyssinian Church
in Harlem, where he delivered a sermon called ``A Letter to Dr.
Martin Luther King.'' He recounted the nation's progress since the
civil rights leader's assassination 20 years ago, and said much
remains to be done.
   He concluded quoting King's wish that all people would one day
join hands and and sing: ``Free at last...Thank God Almighty, we
are free at last.''
   Later, Jackson said he could not look up when he read the quote
because there is still ``a lot of pain and passion in it all.''
   ``All we can do is vow we will continue,'' he told reporters.
``It's not over.''
   Jackson had lunch at a soul food restaurant in Harlem, and
walked for several blocks through the neighborhood, hand in hand
with his wife Jacqueline. Residents called out to him and rushed up
to shake his hand. People called down from their windows, ``Win,
Jesse!'' and ``God bless you!'' as Jackson gave a thumbs-up sign.
   Security around Jackson was intense, with about 20 Secret
Service agents and New York City police officers escorting him
along the sidewalk, along with a phalanx of cameras. Limousines
from the motorcade drove alongside.
   Later, in affluent New Rochelle, Jackson called for racial unity.
   `Even lions and lambs ...don't want the forest set on fire,'' he
told a crowd in affluent New Rochelle. ``If lions and lambs can
find common ground, then blacks and Jews, Hispanics and Italians
can find common ground,'' he said to cheers from the largely black
audience.
   A young white man waved a sign that said ``Jews want peace with
Jesse Jackson.''
   The common ground in New York, as elsewhere in the nation,
Jackson said, lies in economnic issues and the desire to rid the
streets of drugs.
   Meanwhile, former President Richard M. Nixon, interviewed on the
NBC show, ``Meet the Press,'' commented on the New York campaign,
saying, ``Jackson has not been on the side of Jewish issues'' while
all the other candidates ``can't wait but line up for those issues
all the way down the line.''
   Nixon also said Jackson is ``appealing to those who are
restless, despite prosperity. And that is what George Bush must
overcome, and that's why I think it's going to be a close election
rather than a landslide.''
   The former president, driven from office by the Watergate
scandal, said that while he would describe Cuomo and Jackson as
``poets,'' Dukakis would better be compared to ``a word processor.''
   On the other hand, Nixon said of Dukakis, ``he's cool, he's
intelligent, he's tough, he's good in debates. He's going to be a
very formidable candidate.''
   Cuomo, the New York governor whom some Democrats have urged to
get into the presidential race, took the spotlight from the active
candidates on Saturday by announcing he would not endorse anyone
prior to the April 19 vote and calling efforts to draft him
``unproductive and unwise.''
   Did that end the possibility of drafting the governor?
   ``I've ruled it out,'' he said in a telephone call to The
Associated Press.
   But spokesman Gary Fryer said the governor meant that a draft
should not take place, but was not ruling out acceptance of one if
it did occur.
   On Sunday, however, Cuomo said ``I think it is absolutely a
reasonable interpretation to say that if a person says it's wrong,
it's counterproductive, it's unwise, it shouldn't be, then that
means he rejects a draft.''
   When asked if his remarks mean that he would not accept a draft,
Cuomo said, ``I think so.''
   Former New York Rep. Richard Ottinger said Sunday he will
suspend his organized effort to draft Cuomo after receiving a
letter from the governor requesting that he do so. He said,
however, that if it appears there will be no front-runner at the
Democratic convention, the effort would resume.
   ``It doesn't change anything,'' said Dukakis, responding to
Cuomo's latest comment.
   ``I'm going to win New York, I'm going to win Pennsylvania and
I'm going to win the nomination,'' said the Massachusetts governor
who had hoped to get Cuomo's backing before the primary.
</TEXT>
