<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Hungary-USShow     04-11 0127</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Hungary-US Show,0128</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Exhibit Draws 110,000 Visitors In Budapest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 18-day ``American Design'' exhibit
staged at the Museum of Arts and Crafts drew 110,000 people, the
highest number of spectators ever to attend a U.S. exhibit in
Hungary.
   The 250 artifacts presented were mostly everyday products
ranging from household appliances to child-care items, from
personal computers to farm tractors. A special unit dealt with
objects of ``the motorized way of life'' and ``office work today.''
   Exhibit manager Ursual Williams said the large turnout was due,
in part, to heavy media coverage of the American product show,
which closed Sunday.
   ``American Design'' will now travel to the cities of Miskolc in
northern Hungary and Kecskemet in central Hungary for 18-day stints
each.
</TEXT>
