<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--India-Bomb     04-11 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--India-Bomb,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Damages Base Of Nehru Statue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb believed planted by Tamil
extremists damaged the granite base of a statue of India's first
prime minister, Jawaharlal Nehru, in the southern Indian city of
Madras, the United News of India reported.
   No one was reported injured in the blast on Sunday, the news
agency said.
   There was no damage to the bronze statue of Nehru, unveiled by
his grandson, Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, in December 1987. But
chunks of granite were blown out of the base by the explosion.
   Police told the news agency they found two handbills signed by
the Tamil Liberation Army near the blast site. The group was linked
to a bomb blast on a train in the southern Indian state of Tamil
Nadu in March 1987 that killed at least 22 people and injured 150.
Madras is the capital of the state.
   Tamil speakers in southern India have long resisted efforts by
the government to broaden the use of Hindi, the dominant language
in the north.
</TEXT>
