<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 0111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HighDefinitionTV     04-11 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-High Definition TV,0761</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Tech Device Has Industry Excited, Nervous</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new age of television promising
sharper, brighter images on a larger, wider screen with sound as
clean as compact disc recordings is making America's TV broadcast
insdustry excited and nervous.
   This new technology called high definition TV, or HDTV, is the
biggest development in television since the introduction of color
and many American TV station owners are eager to explore its
potential. They also want to make sure they don't get left behind.
   They are watching nervously as competing American interests work
toward developing an HDTV transmission standard for U.S. markets
while the Japanese and Europeans move independently with their own
systems, neither of which is compatible with each other or with
existing U.S. TV sets.
   One of broadcasters' greatest fears is the probability that the
Japanese, who plan to offer HDTV in their own country in 1990, will
begin exporting to the United States HDTV receivers and video
cassette recorders. Such packages could cut over-the-air
broadcasters out of the video equation and threaten their survival.
   ``We don't know how much time it will take'' to develop a system
that can be used by over-the-air broadcasters, said Michael J.
Sherlock of NBC, which is developing a system that improves the TV
picture though not as significantly as HDTV. ``We don't know how
the audience will react, and we don't know how much time we have to
develop our own HDTV.''
   But one thing is certain, he said: ``We broadcasters will have
competition by technically superior systems.
   ``We're fooling ourselves if we don't think the people in the
video cassette, cable and movie industries are going to take
advantage of that,'' he warned in a panel discussion at the
National Association of Broadcasters convention, which began
Saturday and ends Tuesday.
   ``Broadcasters could be put out of business or severely hurt if
we take too long'' to meet the competition with an improved
picture, he said.
   HDTV is the most talked about development at this year's
convention. A room devoted to exhibits of the competing HDTV
systems being developed as well as the Japanese system has provided
most of the TV broadcasters here their first opportunity to see
high definition television.
   The Japanese have been working on HDTV for nearly 20 years, and
they are moving forward quickly. They plan to give a sneak preview
of their system with broadcasts of this summer's Seoul Olympics to
HDTV sets in about 50 big-city department stores throughout the
country.
   The quality of the picture on 35- and 50-inch HDTV screens is
noticeably better than on conventional TV sets. The colors are
brighter and the detail much greater. And because the
width-to-height ratio can be greater, the picture has the panoramic
appearance of a movie theater screen.
   The picture on a standard television set in the United States is
produced by a signal that scans more than 200,000 dots on 525
lines. The Japanese system has 1,125 scanning lines.
   The Japanese system, however, requires more than the space
allocated to TV channels on the electromagnetic spectrum. In Japan,
the HDTV system called Hi-Vision will be transmitted by satellite
to small rooftop antennas, avoiding the bandwidth problem that
would be faced by over-the-air broadcasting. But special HDTV
receivers will be needed to see the enhanced picture.
   A large part of the debate in the United States is whether a
system can be developed that can compress into the standard 6
megahertz TV channel all the electronic information required to
produce HDTV pictures, or whether additional channel space on
another band will be required.
   Some are advocating a transitional approach in which
broadcasters would move first to a system that requires no extra
bandwidth and is compatible with existing TV sets and produces an
improved picture though not as good as HDTV.
   Whichever system is ultimately agreed upon by the U.S. industry,
many technical questions must be answered and trade-offs examined.
Meantime, many TV station executives are nervous.
   ``If you're not scared by HDTV, then you don't understand the
problem,'' said LeBon G. Abercrombie, vice president and general
manager of KMPH-TV, Fresno, Calif.
   ``Within a few short years there are going to be high definition
systems out there for home use in some fashion,'' said Thomas R.
Craddock, an engineer at KKTV-TV in Colorado Springs, Colo.
``Broadcasters are most concerned about how that is going to erode
their audience.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
