<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 0130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Drugs Bjt   04-11 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Drugs, Bjt,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Questions Hit Home with Young Audience</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WYANDANCH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How many days a week do you practice
basketball, Jesse Jackson demanded of the young player prodded to
his feet in the packed high school auditorium.
   ``Four to six,'' was the reply.
   ``When you come home at night do you study for four hours? ...
Three hours? ... Two hours?'' Jackson asked.
   The other kids were giggling now, and eventually the boy
admitted to ``maybe'' one hour of studying, with radio on and
occasional calls to his girlfriend.
   That brought Jackson to one of his favorite lectures, on the
opportunities that await those who study hard, the importance of
pushing for all that life holds, of working to rise above
less-than-privileged beginnings.
   Included is a pointed anti-drug and anti-alcohol message that
Jackson has been hammering home for years to youngsters at schools
across the country.
   ``What does it matter if opportunity is there ... if you're to
drunk to stagger through the door?'' Jackson asked. ``What does it
matter if your classmate is black or white if you can't get along
with anybody?''
   The motivational talk is not part of Jackson's regular campaign
pitch, but talking to high school students is part of his campaign
schedule, as it has been a big part of his lecture tours in the
past.
   And fighting drugs is a big part of his campaign message. In
talking to the young people, he always includes a dramatic series
of questions:
   How many people here know someone who has died because of drugs?
Please stand. A smattering always stand up.
   How many know someone who is in jail because of drugs?
   This sometimes brings about half the audience to its feet.
   How many know someone who has tried drugs?
   Virtually the entire audience stands.
   And then Jackson asks, ``How many know someone who has
contemplated suicide?'' As many as half will stand.
   Jackson's call for action against drug use and trafficking gets
a more enthusiastic response than almost anything else he talks
about on the campaign trail.
   Lately the candidate has needled his Democratic opponents, Sen.
Albert Gore Jr. and Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, saying they
are following his leadership by making drugs a bigger part of their
own campaign messages.
   `We've never known a threat quite like drugs,'' he told some
4,000 people at Iona College in New Rochelle, N.Y., on Sunday. In
the old days, black people were threatened by the Ku Klux Klan who
came at night wearing hoods and carrying lynching ropes, he said.
   But now, ``We've lost more lives to dope than to the rope.''
   The audience cheered when Jackson added his punch line: ``Those
who push drugs don't wear hoods _ they are hoods.''
   His standard talk to the high school kids is about more than
just drugs _ it's about self-motivation and the chance to excel in
life.
   At Wyandanch High, he told the youths that they are good
athletes because, `You do well what you do much. There's nothing
wrong with your mind. There's something wrong with your time. ... I
challenge you to use your mind. I challenge you to study. Give your
mind a chance.
   ``As I travel around the country, the rising use of drugs and
babies making babies and suicide is undermining our opportunity,''
he said.
   He typically ends up leading a chant: ``Down with dope, up with
hope. Down with dope, up with hope.''
   The kids, chanting ``Jesse, Jesse,'' mobbed him Sunday as he
left the stage.
   ``He touched my hand,'' squealed Regina Ross, 17.
   What did she and her friend think of his talk?
   ``It was very inspirational,'' one of them said. Jackson had
zeroed in on the problems of their world, especially the ``down
with dope, up with hope,'' and the part about ``babies making
babies.''
   ``That's the problem right here in this school,'' said Regina.
</TEXT>
