<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     04-11 0819</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crops, Livestock Balance Seen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the effects of this year's continued
improvement in the farm economy may be a closer balance between the
crop and livestock sectors, says an Agriculture Department
economist.
   For some time USDA economists have been forecasting that 1988
net cash income of farmers may be in the range of $50 billion to
$55 billion. Last year, with a bulge in livestock profits, net cash
income rose to a record $57 billion _ the difference between gross
cash income and cash expenses.
   Gregory Hanson of the department's Economic Research Service
says 1988 crop receipts may rise 8 percent to 14 percent from last
year's $59 billion to a range of $64 billion to $67 billion.
   Livestock receipts, which were a record of $74 billion in 1987,
may decline to between $71 billion and $74 billion.
   ``While cattle receipts will be the second or third highest on
record, hog and dairy receipts may each fall nearly $1 billion,''
he said. ``Substantial increases in supplies could bring hog prices
down by one-sixth from last year, and poultry prices one-fourth
below two years ago.''
   Meanwhile, farm expenses will end their downward trend of the
last few years. Feed and fertilizer prices may rise 6 percent to 7
percent in 1988, translating into $2 billion of added costs.
Repairs, energy and labor could add another $1 billion, while
interest and livestock purchase may decline by about $1 billion.
   Hanson, writing in the April issue of Agricultural Outlook
magazine, said 1988 will bring ``continued improvement in the farm
sector's balance sheet.'' A slight strengthening of land prices and
a reduction in farm debt of $5 billion to $10 billion will boost
farmers' equity by $10 billion to $20 billion.
   ``The combination of higher crop prices, lower hog and poultry
prices, and higher feed costs is shifting profits from livestock to
crop producers,'' he said.
   Other impacts of higher crop prices, according to Hanson,
include:
   _The turnaround in declining land values coincided with a rise
in corn and soybean prices during the first six months of 1987.
   _With higher crop prices and the related strengthening in land
values, crop farmers have seen larger cash flows and a
stabilization of loan security, or collateral, provided by real
estate assets.
   ``All regions, including the economically hard-hit Delta and
Southern Plains, are likely to have less farm financial stress in
1988,'' he said. ``Roughly 60 percent of loan default problems of
commercial farmers were on primarily crop-producing farms at the
start of 1987.''
   _Capital expenditures are picking up as cash flows improve and
there is confidence in long-run profit potential. In 1988, capital
spending may increase by as much as $1 billion, with spending for
tractors and combines leading the list.
   _Government spending on crop supports are easing as commodity
prices increase. Direct government payments may decline 16 percent
to 20 percent this year to between $13 billion and $15 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Agriculture Department scientists are
being recognized this year for outstanding work during their
careers.
   Terry B. Kinney Jr., administrator of the department's
Agricultural Research Service, said the five will be inducted into
the agency's Science Hall of Fame at ceremonies on June 21 at the
U.S. National Arboretum in Washington.
   Kinney said that each ``has contributed significantly to
agricultural or nutritional progress worldwide and has an
international reputation for scientific excellence.''
   The honors program was begun in 1986 and, with the current
nominees, will include 13 USDA scientists.
   Kinney said the 1988 selections are:
   _Francis E. Clark, retired microbiologist, Soil and Plant
Nutrient Research Unit, Fort Collins, Colo.
   _Edgar E. Hartwig, research agronomist and former research
leader, Soybean Production Research Unit, Stoneville, Miss.
   _Ralph E. Hodgson, retired national program staff scientist for
dairy production, Beltsville, Md., now residing in Chapel Hill, N.C.
   _Hamish N. Munro, senior scientist, USDA Human Nutrition
Research Center on Aging, Tufts University, Boston, Mass.
   _Jose Vicente-Chandler, retired research leader and soil
scientist, Soil and Water Conservation Research Unit, Rio Piedras,
Puerto Rico.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Zealand consumers like U.S. peanuts, if
the price is right, says the Agriculture Department.
   The main competition is from Australia, India and China, which
provide peanuts for the ``table nut'' sector, the department said
in its April issue of Foreign Agriculture magazine. But U.S.
``splits'' are preferred by processors of peanut butter.
   U.S. peanuts are liked because they are mechanically harvested
and are bought on the basis of a well-understood grading system,
the report said. Some improvement has occurred as a result of the
rise of the New Zealand dollar against the U.S. dollar, but the
Australian dollar also has dropped sharply against the New Zealand
currency.
   Moreover, the report said, ``U.S. peanuts also face a 10 percent
tariff in New Zealand, while there is no duty on imports from
Australia, India and China.''
</TEXT>
