<DOCNO> AP880411-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 0201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FinanceMinisters     04-11 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Finance Ministers,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Finance Ministers from 151 Nations Meeting in US</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For a change, there's no aura of crisis
hanging over this week's meetings of finance officials from 151
nations, a welcome development given the doomsday scenarios which
sprang up following the stock market collapse last October.
   The delegates to the spring meeting of the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank will be wrestling with the
long-standing problems of Third World debt and huge trade
imbalances as preliminary discussions get underway today in
Washington.
   But six months ago, many economists were predicting that the
finance leaders would be facing the far more troubling prospect of
a global recession, triggered by the stock market plunge.
   Instead, the world economy is growing at a faster rate than
expected, inflation is remaining subdued and the stock markets in
the United States and other countries have regained much of the
ground lost last fall.
   For this reason, analysts aren't expecting any major policy
changes to come out of the meeting Wednesday between Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III and his counterparts from Japan, West
Germany, Britain, France, Italy and Canada.
   Baker, the mastermind behind some of the Reagan administration's
most successful economic initiatives, is likely to urge a
don't-rock-the-boat approach that will keep things on an even keel
through the November presidential election.
   In a speech last week, Baker boasted that ``significant
progress'' had been made by the United States and its allies in
promoting economic cooperation.
   ``The seven largest industrial nations in the free world now
have a coordination process firmly in place,'' he said.
   This will be the first meeting of the so-called Group of Seven
since last September. At that time, unity and international
economic cooperation were also the watchwords.
   But behind-the-scenes disagreements between the United States
and West Germany over interest rates became public soon after the
meeting, unnerving investors and, many believe, contributing to the
Oct. 19 stock market collapse.
   The market collapse served as a strong reminder to finance
leaders of the dangers in disharmony and on Dec. 22 they pledged to
support the dollar at its current levels. They then backed that
pledge up by intervening in currency markets, the process by which
governments buy and sell currencies to influence their value.
   Since early this year, the dollar has stabilized and the top
industrial countries are expected to pledge anew this week to
support that stability.
   Baker is also likely to push again for the other countries to
adopt his idea of using an index of commodity prices, including
gold, as one of indicators the countries use to measure the impact
of their policies.
   But some have been skeptical, wondering if the proposal might be
the first step to moving the world back to a gold standard for
currencies, something that was abandoned in 1973 when the current
floating exchange rates were implemented.
   Baker denies that, saying the commodity index would merely serve
as a useful measure of inflationary pressures.
   On Third World debt, the finance ministers are expected to
basically reaffirm existing strategies although they may adopt some
new approaches aimed at cutting the trillion-dollar debt burden.
   Barber Conable, president of the World Bank, has taken the
position that the burden on heavily indebted countries is becoming
unsustainable and such initiatives as the recent Mexican
debt-for-bonds swap are needed if the debt crisis is ever to be
resolved. In that case, Mexico offered to exchange debt held by
commerical banks in return for a reduced amount of Mexican bonds
which were backed by U.S. Treasury securities.
   For his part, Baker has also endorsed efforts to find new ways
of reducing the debt burden but he has opposed any broad
debt-relief plans involving the World Bank or the IMF, contending
they would be too costly and would represent a bailout for big
commercial banks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880411-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 0203EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StudentRadio     04-11 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Student Radio,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Princeton Students Run Nationally Syndicated Interview Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``American Focus'' radio show and the
college students who produce it are hardly household names, but the
guests heard on the program usually are.
   Jimmy Carter, Henry Fonda, Jerry Falwell, Joan Rivers, Carl
Sagan, David Letterman, Bob Hope, Walter Mondale, Julia Child,
David Rockefeller, Abba Eban, Dan Rather and Norman Mailer are
among the hundreds of luminaries who have agreed to sit behind the
mike.
   The show, one of the country's largest nationally syndicated
public affairs radio programs, is the work of 30 Princeton
University students who have virtually no formal radio training and
put the show together in their spare time.
   Even radio professionals are surprised when they learn the show
is just a student activity.
   ``It's very professionally done. I didn't know they were
students. They sounded like they have been in the field for quite
some time,'' said Sean Cort, public affairs coordinator for WRKS-FM
in New York City, which broadcasts the program.
   The weekly, half-hour show features one guest and three to four
student interviewers. It boasts a network of 270 stations,
including outlets in all of the nation's 50 largest radio markets.
   For the most part the show is broadcast either Sunday morning or
night, the time slots to which most public affairs programs are
relegated.
   The show is geared to adults, not college students. The program
is not even heard on college radio stations.
   ``For the most part our audience is not our peers. It's
primarily adults,'' said Richard Fitzgerald, a junior who's
executive producer.
   ``Rock stars ... we just don't think that's what our audience
will appreciate. When we do entertainers we go for the more
established entertainers.''
   Because a show may not be broadcast until three weeks after
taping, ``American Focus'' doesn't try to break news.
   It focuses on the guest's view of the news and ``a little bit
about the person, their lives and things that have led them into
what they are doing,'' said the show's current president, junior
Sofia Perez.
   But the show has made some headlines. Several years ago, actor
Richard Dreyfuss admitted while on ``American Focus'' that he had
used drugs. Dreyfuss also said he stopped using them after he was
charged with possessing narcotics following a traffic accident.
   A blown-up copy of a Los Angeles Times story crediting
``American Focus'' with the scoop hangs in the show's offices in a
creeky old house on the Princeton campus.
   ``Sometimes, the guests, if they know we are college students,
they won't put up as much as a front than if we were
professionals,'' Fitzpatrick said.
   The show was founded in 1974 by a local high school student who
pieced the initial programs together ``with scotch tape and
stuff,'' Fitzpatrick said.
   The first show, with a relatively anonymous New Jersey official
as the guest, could only be heard on a Trenton radio station. When
the student, Garth Ancier, now an executive at Fox Broadcasting,
was accepted to Princeton, he bought the show with him, initially
producing it out of his dormitory room.
   Today the show still doesn't receive direct financial support
from the university, but it now has commercial sponsors who help
pay its annual budget of $40,000 to $50,000. Money left over is put
back into the program because the enterprise is non-profit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
