<HEAD>McGovern: Dukakis' Win In Wisconsin Should Wrap Up Nomination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUKESHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential candidate George
McGovern says Michael Dukakis' win in the Wisconsin primary last
week will probably assure his receiving the Democratic presidential
nomination.
   McGovern, who lost to former President Richard M. Nixon in 1972,
said Dukakis' win over Jesse Jackson in the Wisconsin primary ``was
a turning point.''
   ``Dukakis came out of Wisconsin with a head of steam,'' the
former South Dakota senator said.
   McGovern talked about the current political campaign Saturday in
an interview before he addressed a conference on the Vietnam War.
   Dukakis finished with 48 percent of the popular vote in the
Wisconsin primary Tuesday, compared to Jackson with 28 percent and
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore with 17 percent.
   McGovern, 65, said he has not endorsed any candidate and
believes the nomination should go to the Democrat who enters the
national convention in July with the most delegates.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Time: Bush has ``No Grudges'' Against Rather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush says he has ``no
grudges'' against anchorman Dan Rather, with whom he verbally
sparred during a nationally televised interview, but he's passed up
lunch with columnist George Will because of ``personal attacks,''
according to Time Magazine.
   Bush, discussing his relationship with the media, told the
magazine in its current issue: ``I have nothing against Dan Rather.
He was nice to my kids. I called him up and said, `I've been
looking for an excuse to call you and say no grudges.'
   ``The same with many others who have criticized me. They are
coming from one place, I am coming from another. I understand
that,'' he said in the interview published Sunday.
   The nine-minute live exchange between Bush and Rather on the
``CBS Evening News'' on Jan. 25, spurred angry phone calls to CBS
affiliates across the country, as well as headlines and political
analysis of the fallout.
   Bush, however, doesn't get along with Will, according to Time.
   ``I draw the line at personal attacks,'' the vice president said.
   Will called him a ``lap dog'' and then asked him to lunch but
Bush said he passed on the invitation.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tuesday Caucuses Mark First Step in Missouri Delegate Selection
Process</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican and Democratic officials
alike expect Tuesday's caucuses in which both parties begin their
delegate selection process to be relatively quiet events that offer
no surprises.
   Tuesday night, party regulars are scheduled to attend Democratic
and Republican meetings to pick individuals to proceed to future
gatherings where delegates to the parties' national conventions in
Atlanta and New Orleans will be selected.
   Because Missouri had a presidential primary, the number of
delegates each presidential candidate will receive already has been
determined. So Tuesday night's caucuses will really be a matter of
just picking the individuals to represent the candidates.
   ``There's no reason to try to raid the caucuses,'' said Lt. Gov.
Harriett Woods, the Democrats' top elected official in Missouri.
   ``Everybody seems to be magnanimous,'' said Tony Feather,
executive director of the Missouri Republican Party. ``There's no
real animosity.''
   Tuesday night's mass meetings are the first of several steps
over the next two months that will determine which Missourians will
go to the conventions this summer where the two presidential
nominees will be picked.
</TEXT>
