<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel Bjt   04-11 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, Bjt,0713</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Settlers Reject Army Explanation Of Girl's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish settlers rejected an army report saying
an Israeli teen-ager was killed by a settler's gun and demanded
harsh punishment for a West Bank village where they claim the girl
was slain by Arabs.
   In another development, Palestinian leaders on Sunday called for
a commercial strike today in the occupied lands and demanded the
resignation of Arabs holding appointed or elected positions in the
territories.
   The occupied territories were quiet on Sunday. Arab reports said
troops closed shops and food markets in Gaza Strip, which opened
during morning hours.
   Since Palestinians began violent protests against Israeli rule
in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip in early December, 141
Arabs, one Israeli soldier and one Israeli civilian have been
killed.
   The Jewish settlers and right-wing legislators, including some
from Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's Likud bloc, on Sunday
condemned the army after its report on the death of the teen-ager
and demanded its chief of staff resign.
   They urged tough sanctions on Palestinian rioters, including the
expulsion of Arab stone-throwers, and called for the destruction of
every home in Beita, the West Bank village where 15-year-old Tirza
Porat was killed on Wednesday.
   Israel Television quoted the army report as saying Miss Porat
was accidentally killed by the M-16 rifle of Roman Al Dubi, a
settler-guard who ``panicked and opened fire in all directions''
during the clash with Arab rioters. Besides Miss Porat, two Arabs
died in the melee, and 15 people, including 13 Jewish teen-agers
and two Arabs, were wounded.
   Outraged settlers insisted Miss Porat was shot with a rifle by a
masked Arab and charged the Jewish teen-agers involved were not
properly questioned.
   The army said it has destroyed 13 houses belonging to inciters
of last week's clash and killed a 14-year-old Arab who tried to
avoid arrest. Israel's Supreme Court has barred the army from
destroying any more homes in Beita pending an appeal from a civil
rights group.
   The daily Maariv reported on Sunday that 150 villagers have been
detained, of whom 30 remained in custody.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin and the army chief of staff, Lt.
Gen. Dan Shomron, presented the army's version of the clash to the
Cabinet on Sunday.
   Rabin said an army autopsy showed Miss Porat apparently was shot
by a bullet from Al Dubi's rifle, Israel radio reported. Al Dubi
and another adult settler were guarding the Jewish teen-agers
during a hike.
   A senior army official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed the fatal bullet came from Al Dubi's weapon, but said the
army had not yet determined who fired the shot. The hikers said Al
Dubi only fired a single shot in the air while the group was inside
Beita.
   ``I looked up and saw an Arab man with a masked face shooting a
(rifle) from a rooftop,'' said Ariel Avivi, a hiker.
   Geulah Cohen, a legislator from the nationalistic Tehiya Party,
demanded that Shomron resign. ``I think he simply failed. He jumped
to conclusions and, acting as a judge, pointed an accusing finger
at the settlers,'' she said on Israel Television on Sunday.
   The TV quoted Likud's trade and industry minister, Ariel Sharon,
as telling the Cabinet that Arabs who attacked the youths should be
expelled, their homes destroyed and a new Jewish settlement
established nearby.
   Shamir's political rival, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres of the
Labor Party, defended the army. ``Cabinet ministers are not
investigators and the Cabinet is not a judge. This should be left
to competent authorities,'' Peres said.
   Shamir called for ``unity between all parts of the people ...
for the good of the people and, first of all, for the security of
the people.''
   A Palestinian leaflet distributed on Sunday in the occupied
lands praised Beita residents for ``responding twice as strongly to
wild settlers'' and called on Palestinians to make donations to
Beita on Wednesday.
   The leaflets repeated earlier calls for the resignation of Arab
officials in occupied territories and demanded that Palestinians
stop working in Jewish settlements. Another leaflet called for a
general strike today.
</TEXT>
