<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF-Hungary-Party,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Prominent Intellectuals Fired From Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four prominent intellectuals were
expelled from the Communist Party, apparently because they were
associated with the ``Democratic Forum,'' a loose group of mostly
non-conformist intellectuals, artists and professionals calling for
political change.
   The weekend edition of the party daily Nepszabadsag identified
the four as Zoltan Kiraly, a television journalist and member of
parliament; Zoltan Biro, senior staff member of the National
Library; Mihaly Bihari, a professor at the faculty of political and
legal science of Eotvoes Lorand University; and Laszlo Lengyel,
senior scientific staff member of a financial research institute.
   Nepszabadsag said the party's Central Control Commission
established that the four ``represented views on several
fundamental questions different from those upheld by party policy.''
   They were found guilty of ``voicing and spreading these views
for a prolonged time at different forums outside the party.''
   The ``Democratic Forum'' was set up at a meeting of 150
intellectuals at Lakitelek in southern Hungary on Sept. 27, 1987.
</TEXT>
