<HEAD>Officers Fined For Abuses In Military Reform Drive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military leaders have fined officers a total of $4
million in a new drive to end corruption and abuses of power that
are damaging Soviet military readiness, Pravda reported.
   The official Communist Party newspaper on Sunday quoted chief
military prosecutor Boris S. Popov as saying officials were trying
to stamp out evasion of military service, theft, damage of military
equipment and other crimes.
   Pravda said the military had not been exempt from the stagnation
and corruption that Mikhail S. Gorbachev is trying to stamp out of
Soviet society.
   Violations of laws and military regulations had become habitual
among some commanding officers and political officers, he said. The
fines were levied in the past two months against an unspecified
number of soldiers, Popov said.
   Some soldiers were found to be renting private apartments and
living outside barracks and stealing or damaging military property,
Pravda said. Soldiers who busy themselves with outside economic
activities have caused a ``great damage'' to Soviet military
preparedness, Pravda said.
</TEXT>
