<HEAD>Michael Jackson's Home Opened For Auction Guests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pop star Michael Jackson opened his estate to
bidders who purchased artwork and helped the reclusive singer raise
more than $2 million to benefit the South African Council of
Churches.
   Jackson was away on tour, but his brother Jermaine and family
patriarch Joseph Jackson were hosts of Sunday's auction. Actress
Whoopi Goldberg was auctioneer.
   In addition to the sale of a $1.2 million pearl to a buyer whose
name wasn't revealed, other jewelry, paintings, sculptures and furs
were sold, said auction spokeswoman Sabrina Horn.
   Miss Goldberg bought an oil painting by Grant Wood valued at
between $300,000 to $500,000, said Ms. Horn, who wouldn't disclose
how much the actress paid.
   It wasn't immediately known how much was raised by the auction,
but Ms. Horn said, ``It would be safe to say that millions of
dollars were raised.''
   More than 110 items were auctioned.
   Up to 300 people were treated to cocktails as a band and
magician entertained. Guests were allowed to tour the property,
while bidders bought artwork, including a Pablo Picasso oil
painting dated Feb. 27, 1969, and titled ``Buste d'Homme.''
   The dining room was the only portion of the home open to the
bidders, reporters and photographers.
   Lia Belli, head of the Adelphia Society and wife of attorney
Melvin Belli, arranged the auction with permission from Joseph
Jackson, Ms. Horn said.
   The money will go toward emergency housing, clothing and medical
supplies for displaced South African families.
