<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0811,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stock Prices Rally</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing figures; pickup 5th
pvs, `People are ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock market's key indicator surged to an all-time
high closing Monday in Tokyo, while the U.S. dollar gained ground
in trading against the Japanese yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Average of 225 selected
issues, which shed a modest 20.33 points Friday, gained 175.98
points, or 0.65 percent, finishing the day at 26,924.87.
   The dollar closed at 125.71 yen, up 0.53 yen from its close of
125.18 yen Friday. It had opened the day at 125.80 yen, and traded
between 125.68-125.83 yen.
   ``People are buying on an optimism based chiefly on the dollar's
movement,'' said Julian Jones, a broker at Vickers da Costa.
   He attributed the U.S. currency's positive trend to Wednesday's
anticipated meeting of monetary officials of the Group of Seven
major economic countries and Thursday's announcement of U.S. trade
figures for February.
   The bullish movement is expected to continue for the rest of the
day, Jones added.
   An exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo said the
dollar's firmness also reflected last Friday's close in New York,
when the dollar closed the week at 125.75 yen.
   ``Otherwise, many market participants are taking a wait-and-see
position prior to an announcement of U.S. trade figures for
February,'' he added, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
