<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     04-11 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A one-hour visit planned this week by
Sweden's royal couple has unleashed a wave of monarch mania in
Bridgeton.
   Every lamppost in town has Swedish and American flags, a pizza
parlor printed special T-shirts for the occasion and inmates were
rushing to finish a Swedish farmstead museum in the middle of an
abandoned baseball field.
   ``It's going to be tremendous. Bridgeton hasn't had this much
excitement in a long time,'' said Reginald Scott, the owner of Big
John's Pizza.
   In honor of the royal visit, Scott printed up commemorative Big
John T-shirts for some of the 10,000 visitors expected to join King
Carl XVI Gustaf and Queen Silvia on Thursday.
   ``That's the closest we'll come to Swedish pizza,'' he said with
a laugh.
   The royal couple plan to start a day of touring in New Jersey in
Bridgeton, where they'll dedicate a log-cabin museum commemorating
the historic 1638 landing that led to the Swedish settlement of the
Delaware Valley.
   Bridgeton normally is not steeped in Scandinavian tradition but
the visit kicks off a four-day Swedish cultural tribute that
includes dancing, crafts and other events.
   The visit here is scheduled to last only 60 minutes and will
cost about $300,000 in public and private funds, city recreation
director Bob Rose said.
   But nobody seems to mind the short stop.
   ``It's more than that. It's a whole weekend but the visit is the
highlight,'' Rose said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal to turn former federal prison
Alcatraz Island into a casino crapped out in a newspaper survey of
San Francisco residents.
   ``I hate to sound so Californian, but it's just not good
karma,'' said, one of those surveyed, Kathleen Kelly, 30. ``It is
just a dumb idea.''
   The proposal, an advisory measure on the June 7 ballot, was
opposed by a margin of 57 percent to 35 percent of the 600 people
participating in the poll by the San Francisco Chronicle, the
newspaper reported today.
   Supervisors who placed Proposition N on the ballot say a casino
could generate millions of dollars for the debt-plagued city.
Several hurdles would have to be cleared first _ the city would
have to acquire the land from the state, the state constitution
would have to be changed to allow casino gambling, and numerous
capital improvements would have to be made.
   Alcatraz, known as The Rock, now is a popular attraction for
tourists who want to take a peek at the former home of gangster Al
Capone and other incorrigibles.
   Putting a casino on Alcatraz ``would be like violating Mount
Rushmore or Ellis Island,'' said Saundra Neal, a legal secretary
who moved here from New York 18 months ago. ``I think it is very
beautiful. It's peaceful.''
   ``The idea of putting some kind of casino blight in the middle
of the bay is really repulsive,'' said Jerry Weiss. ``Flashing neon
just seems like a stupid idea for the bay.''
</TEXT>
