<HEAD>Guardian Angels Picket Dennis Hopper's Home to Protest `Colors'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gang Sweep</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Guardian Angels picketed film director
Dennis Hopper's home to protest his new movie ``Colors,'' which the
anti-crime group called a recruitment film for gangs nationwide.
   ``It starts with a drive-by killing and ends with the killing of
an L.A. cop. I don't think that's the kind of message that needs to
get out in this country,'' Guardian Angels leader Curtis Sliwa said
Sunday.
   The self-styled crime fighters, who picketed actor Sean Penn's
home in Malibu on Saturday, set up symbolic coffins outside
Hopper's Venice home and chanted ``Kids will die with pain; Dennis
Hopper in the hall of shame.''
   The movie, which stars Penn and Robert Duvall as police
officers, is a drama set amid the gang wars of Los Angeles. Hopper
wrote and directed ``Colors.''
   Police reported no problems during the weekend demonstration,
which also included protesters lying on the ground to simulate a
murder scene.
   The Guardian Angels want Orion Pictures to either halt
distribution of the film or use some of its profits to support
community organizations that combat gang violence, said Sliwa.
   It wasn't known if Hopper was home during the protest. Sliwa
said some people were seen entering the house.
   Neither Hopper, nor Orion officials could be reached for comment
Sunday about the protest by telephone. Hopper has said previously
he was surprised by objections to the movie.
   Gangs were blamed for nearly 400 killings last year in Los
Angeles County, and were the target of two unprecedented citywide
police sweeps this weekend.
