<HEAD>`War of Cities' Resumes After Three-Day Lull</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said it fired two missiles into
Tehran and another into Isfahan today, and Iran said 16 civilians
were killed.
   The reported attacks broke a three-day lull in the ``war of the
cities.''
   The Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Cyprus, said the missiles
were fired after a lull that allowed Iranians to vote in Friday's
parliamentary elections.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency, which confirmed one strike
on each of the cities and reported the civilian deaths, also said a
mosque, a hospital and homes were damaged. IRNA also was monitored
in Cyprus.
   The Iranian news agency quoted an unidentified military
spokesman as saying Iran's forces would retaliate and ``raze to the
ground the dens of mischief in Baghdad and elsewhere in Iraq.''
   Today's reports described the 117th and 118th missile attack on
Tehran and the 17th on Isfahan since Iraq began launching the
long-range missiles into Iranian cities for the first time on Feb.
29.
   IRNA quoted an unidentified spokesman as saying Iraqi warplanes
raided an Iranian village near the border city of Marivan on
Sunday. The spokesman said the renewed Iraqi attacks were proof
that Iraq needed ``a good punishment.''
   Iraq and Iran have been at war since September 1980.
</TEXT>
