<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GlobalForum     04-11 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Global Forum,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Pull Out Of Conference Over Dalai Lama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China, expressing displeasure at the
attendance of the Dalai Lama, pulled out of an international
meeting of religious leaders and lawmakers discussing global
problems, the organizers said.
   ``We worked hard to get the Chinese here because we are
discussing issues of great concern to them, like population
growth,'' said the Rev. James Parks Morton, a co-chairman of the
Global Conference of Spiritual and Parliamentary Leaders on Human
Survival.
   Morton, dean of the Episcopal Cathedral of St. John the Divine
in New York, said the leaders of the world's most populous nation
had earlier shown a willingness to attend the five-day conference,
which was to open today.
   ``But although we had no formal complaint from the Chinese
government about the attendance of the Dalai Lama, we did get a
letter from one of their bigwigs saying they were not coming
because he was here,'' Morton said.
   Akio Matsumura, a Japanese living in New York who organized the
conference in the university city of Oxford, visited Beijing to
invite the Chinese.
   ``We are disappointed that they aren't coming, but we will
communicate closely with them with a view to involving them in our
future activities,'' Morton said in an interview.
   The Dalai Lama, the religious and civil leader of Tibet before
the 1950 Chinese Communist takeover, fled to India in 1959.
   China recently said the Dalai Lama could return to China
provided he accepts Chinese rule in Tibet. He said he will not
accept a Chinese offer to return but was willing to negotiate with
China.
   China maintains it has held sovereignty over Tibet since the
13th century. Tibetan independence advocates say the remote
Himalayan region enjoyed de facto independence for most of that
time.
   On March 5, China arrested 200 people in an independence protest
in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa, the fourth against Chinese rule
there in five months. On Oct. 1, thousands of Tibetans led by
Buddhist monks stormed and set fire to a police station in Lhasa.
At least 14 people died.
   Morton said the Dalai Lama was attending the conference in
London ``as a pre-eminent theologian known worldwide for his
commitment to world peace and universal human causes.''
   On Tuesday, the Dalai Lama will address the conference on the
universal human condition.
   About 200 people from at least 60 countries are attending the
conference, including Buddhist, Christian, Hindu, Moslem and Jewish
leaders.
   The meeting will discuss how participants will work together on
the threat of nuclear war, terrorism and urban violence, population
control, poverty, pollution, conservation and education.
   Matsumura, a family planning expert, said the main financial
sponsors were Shingo Nomura, a Japanese real estate developer, who
put up $500,000, and three other benefactors who contributed
$300,000 each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
