<1ST_LINE>u i PM-AfghanFighting     04-11 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghan Fighting,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insurgents Attack City, 13 Reported Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Afghanistan-Plane, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem insurgents attacked the northwestern Afghan
city of Maimaneh with rockets and artillery, killing 13 people and
causing serious damage, the Tass news agency said today.
   The attack was on the same city from which a Soviet-built
Antonov-26 plane took off for Mazar Sharif, 145 miles to the east,
on Sunday. Official Kabul Radio said the plane was shot down by
rebels, killing all 29 people aboard.
   ``Oppositionists brought down rocket and artillery fire on the
town of Maimaneh, killing 13 people, among them women and children,
wounding four people and inflicting considerable destruction upon
the town,'' Tass said.
   It did not say when the attack occurred, or provide any more
information. Maimaneh is located 90 miles south of the Soviet
border.
   Tass also reported that government forces had discovered a rebel
arms cache including recoilless rifles, grenade launchers, small
arms and ammunition in Helmand province. It said a group of
insurgents had been routed by government forces in Balkh province,
and that eight of them had been taken prisoner.
   The fighting took place as Pakistan and Afghanistan were
preparing to sign a U.N.-sponsored agreement in Geneva to end the
Afghan conflict. Pakistan shelters millions of Afghans who have
fled the fighting, and many Afghan guerrilla groups have bases in
Pakistan.
   Soviet soldiers entered Afghanistan in December 1979, replaced
one pro-Soviet government with another, and remained to fight the
Moslem insurgents.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has said the estimated
115,000 Soviet soldiers will begin leaving on May 15 if an
agreement is signed soon in Geneva.
   The agreements call for all Soviet soldiers to be out of
Afghanistan in nine months.
</TEXT>
