<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpyHotLine 1stLd-Writethru a0498 04-11 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spy Hot Line, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0498,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hot Line Aims To Bring Spies In From The Cold</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to reflect that hot line started one year ago.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FORT MEADE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A toll-free spy hotline that urges
soldiers to report suspicious activity and colleagues who receive
phone calls from people with foreign accents has fielded more than
20,000 calls, an official said.
   But William Dwyer, a civilian Army employee who for the past
year has run the nationwide hotline from a windowless room at Forte
Meade, says it has not led to any celebrated arrests.
   ``I know for a fact that there are investigations ongoing,''
Dwyer said, adding that the calls have sparked several espionage
probes by the military and the FBI. ``I have heard we have provided
significant leads.''
   Although the hot line, 1-800-CALL-SPY, is designed for Army
personnel across the country, most callers are civilians, Dwyer
said.
   About 1 percent of the inquiries have provided worthwhile
espionage or security-related tips, which are passed on to federal
investigators ranging from U.S. Army intelligence to the FBI, he
said.
   ``It's been effective,'' said Lt. Col. John Ooley, a spokesman
for the U.S. Army Intelligence and Security Command in Arlington,
Va.
   ``The hot line, like any hot line, is an excellent resource for
people to report this type of activity,'' FBI spokesman William
Carter said.
   Fliers advertising the hot line urge soldiers to watch for
colleagues who receive calls from ``someone with a foreign accent''
or ``brag about ... `James Bond'-type activities.'' Other telltale
spy signs are ``a lot of unexplained money'' or odd requests ``for
a manual, document or plan.''
   The warnings might seem a bit melodramatic, Dwyer admitted.
``Sound stupid? Yeah,'' he said. ``But these are actual cases.''
   The American Civil Liberties Union says it has concerns about
the possibility of abuse.
   ``It's inviting mischief,'' said Jerry Berman, chief legislative
counsel with the ACLU in Washington, D.C. ``The allegations can
have very serious consequences for someone.''
   Dwyer conceded that the program might appear troublesome.
   ``Some people look at this and say, `My God! Big Brother,''' he
said. ``That is the furthest thing from our minds.''
   Any information received over the phone is checked by several
supervisors before it is sent to federal investigators, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
