<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MastersNewspage     04-11 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Masters Newspage,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandy Lyle Wins Golf's Masters Title</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandy Lyle captured the 52nd Masters title
by one stroke with a 12-foot putt set up by a dramatic extrication
from a bunker on the last hole.
   Lyle, a Scotsman who won the 1985 British Open, became the first
British subject to ever win the Masters tournament. His score for
Sunday's round was a 1-under-par 71 for a tournament total of 281,
seven shots under par.
   Mark Calcavecchia, who was a caddy as recently as three years
ago, finished second with a 2-under-par 70 in the bright, warm
sunshine. He had a 282 total.
   Craig Stadler, the 1982 Masters winner, once had a share of the
lead, but bogied the 16th hole and finished third at 283. Another
former champion, Ben Crenshaw, followed at 284 with a 72. Jack
Nicklaus, the only six-time winner of the Masters, was at 292 after
a 72, putting him in a tie for 20th place.
   Lyle had to come out of a yawning fairway bunker on the 18th
hole of the Augusta National Golf Club course.
   ``I thought it was over,'' he said. ``That bunker has a steep
face and I didn't think I could get the ball over the lip onto the
green.''
   His ball hit beyond the cup and backed up toward the hole while
spectators howled. Lyle, who had blown a two-shot lead earlier in
the day, then made the birdie putt to win the title.
   In addition to the famed green winner's jacket, Lyle collected
$183,800 from the total purse of $1 million.
</TEXT>
