<HEAD>No Celeb Oscar Party at Polly Bergen's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even though the ceremony is in Los Angeles you
just CAN'T stay home, but how do you avoid mixing with the hoi
polloi?
   For the last nine years celebs stuck in the Big Apple could pick
up a little Oscar glamour by watching the ceremonies on television
while rubbing famous elbows at Polly Bergen's Park Avenue digs.
   But this year Ms. Bergen has just finished a television movie
and is preparing to act in several pilots, so she herself is in Los
Angeles.
   So there's no giant New York soiree for the likes of Helen
Gurley Brown, Gay Talese, Nora Ephron, Barbara Walters and even
Paul Newman.
   Well, not quite. Ms. Walters is inviting a few friends over to
watch her hourlong yak with a couple of actors right before the
Oscars, but it is not an official Oscar party.
   ``I'm not going to give the Polly party,'' Ms. Walters said.
   Ms. Bergen says the party _ for up to 240 people _ has been
going on for so many years that some may not know she's not
throwing it.
   ``I've been getting long distance calls form people who feel
stranded,'' she said. ``It's possible that some people will show up
on the doorstep, poor dears, and never even realize that there is
not party this year.''
   Ms. Bergen herself is going to the dime-a-celebrity party thrown
annually in L.A. by literary agent Irving (Swifty) Lazar.
