<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Oscars-ETPoll     04-11 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oscars-ET Poll,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Entertainment Tonight' Telephone Poll Picks Oscar Winners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If it were up to the viewers of
``Entertainment Tonight,'' Cher and Robin Williams would be winners
at tonight's Academy Awards ceremonies.
   They were picked for the best actress and best actor Oscars for
their roles in ``Moonstruck'' and ``Good Morning Vietnam.''
   ``Fatal Attraction,'' the thriller about an affair turned
murderous was chosen best picture by 40 percent of the viewers who
phoned in their favorites to a special 900 prefix number.
   Cher, who portrayed an Italian widow smitten by her fiance's
brother in ``Moonstruck,'' received 51 percent of the votes.
``Moonstruck'' took 36 percent of the vote and second place in the
best movie category.
   Glenn Close, the vengeful other woman in ``Fatal Attraction,''
was second with 24 percent, Meryl Streep, the alcoholic in
``Ironweed,'' had 12 percent of the vote and TV news producer Holly
Hunter in ``Broadcast News'' had 10 percent. Sally Kirkland, who
starred as an aging beauty in ``Anna,'' garnered just 3 percent.
   In the best actor category, Robin Williams took 58 percent and
first place for his portrayal of a wartime disc jockey in ``Good
Morning Vietnam,'' while Michael Douglas, the ruthless entrepreneur
in ``Wall Street,'' garnered 25 percent of the ``Entertainment
Tonight'' poll.
   Jack Nicholson, also a drunk in ``Ironweed,'' had 8 percent;
William Hurt, the brainless but charming ``Broadcast News''
anchorman got 6 percent while Marcello Mastroianni netted 3 percent
for his performance in ``Dark Eyes.''
   ``The Last Emperor'' took 13 percent of the vote and third place
for best movie, while ``Broadcast News'' had 7 percent and ``Hope
and Glory'' 4 percent.
</TEXT>
