<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 0848EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CucumberAlert     04-11 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cucumber Alert,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cucumbers Contaminated With Illegal Use Of Pesticide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A two-state public-health alert for
pesticide-contaminated cucumbers is in effect in Washington and
Oregon following illness in two Seattle-area families.
   The cucumbers, contaminated with aldicarb, were distributed by
wholesalers to grocers in those two states and possibly northern
California and Idaho, said Roger Lowell, district director for the
U.S. Food and Drug Administration in Seattle.
   Symptoms of the infected cucumbers include nausea, vomiting and
diarrhea within one hour of eating, usually within 30 minutes,
Lowell said Sunday. Other symptoms can include blurred vision,
excessive sweating and muscle twitching.
   Lowell said officials were unaware of any permanent health
damage, adding that the symptoms pass quickly, like influenza. In
fact, he said, many people in the area who thought they had the flu
in the last week may have actually been suffering from the
pesticide.
   Both cucumber-related illnesses were in the Seattle area, said
Frank Mendizabal of the Department of Social and Health Services.
The health alerts in Oregon and Washington took effect Saturday,
although no illnesses were reported in Oregon.
   The cucumbers are European style, 12 to 18 inches long and about
1{ inches in diameter with pointed ends. They are wrapped in clear,
unlabeled plastic, Lowell said.
   Any skinny cucumbers without labels are considered suspect, said
Lowell, but those with a brand-name label showing they were grown
elsewhere are considered safe.
   The cucumbers were grown in hothouses in northern California by
Barnard Hydroponic of Redding and distributed by Blue Anchor, Inc.,
of Sacramento, Lowell said.
   Bruce Barnard, an owner of Barnard Hydroponic, refused to
comment in a Sunday telephone interview from his home in Redding,
Calif., saying he wanted to talk with FDA officials first.
   Aldicarb is used to treat soil before crops are grown and is
used mostly for non-food crops, including cotton. Use of the
pesticide on growing food products is illegal, Lowell said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
