<1ST_LINE>u i PM-WorldCourt-US 1stLd-Writethru a0482 04-11 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-World Court-US, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Court Hearings Open In PLO Mission Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with arguments</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations today accused
the Reagan administration of violating a U.N. treaty by trying to
close the PLO Mission in New York.
   The United Nations has asked the World Court for an opinion on
whether the U.S. government must accept arbitration in the dispute,
which emanates from anti-terrorist legislation signed by President
Reagan last December.
   That law, which classifies the Palestine Liberation Organization
as a terrorist group and bars it from operating on U.S. territory,
led the United States to order the closing of the PLO Mission to
the United Nations, a maneuver condemned by all U.N. member nations
except the United States and Israel.
   ``The (U.N.) secretary-general has the strong desire to avoid
any confrontation with the host country,'' a U.N.
undersecretary-general, Carl-August Fleischhauer of West Germany,
told the World Court today.
   But he stressed that the United Nations ``urges the court to
declare that indeed there is an obligation to the United States''
to submit the dispute to independent arbitration.
   Fleischhauer's remarks came during a 90-minute World Court
hearing. Neither the United States nor the PLO was officially
represented at the session.
   In a recent letter to the World Court, John Shad, U.S.
ambassador to the Netherlands, said his government does not
``believe arbitration would be appropriate'' because the case is
now before a U.S. court.
   The PLO is unable to plead its case here because only nation
states and U.N. bodies are entitled to appear before the World
Court.
   The World Court, officially known as the International Court of
Justice, is the U.N.'s 15-member judicial branch. It has no
enforcement powers and depends on voluntary adherence to its
rulings.
   In the case now under consideration, the United Nations claims
the United States is required to accept arbitration in the matter
under a 1947 accord between the world body and the Truman
administration.
   Under that pact, known as the Headquarters Agreement, disputes
between the U.S. government and the United Nations arising from the
U.N. presence in the United States must be settled by arbitration.
   The accord calls for a three-member arbitration panel, made up
of one member appointed by the U.N. secretary-general, one
appointed by the U.S. government, and one chosen by mutual consent.
   Although the accord does not specifically mention missions, the
United Nations maintains its rules concerning the unhindered
functioning of diplomats accredited to its headquarters in New York
also apply to the missions of member nations and organizations with
observer status.
   The PLO was granted non-voting observer status at the United
Nations in 1974. It has maintained an office in Manhattan since
then.
   Several weeks ago, the U.S. Justice Department filed suit in
U.S. District Court in New York after the PLO refused to close its
office there. The PLO was expected to respond in the U.S. case
today, and the United Nations was expected to file a brief
supporting the PLO position.
   The U.S. boycott of the World Court proceedings marks the second
time in four years that the Reagan administration has refused to
take part in one of its cases.
   The U.S. government claimed the court had no authority to handle
a complaint against it filed in 1984 by Nicaragua and boycotted the
last 17 months of the proceedings in that case. The World Court
ultimately ruled in favor of Nicaragua, and ordered the United
States to halt its support for the Contra rebels fighting
Nicaragua's Sandinista government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880411-0070 </DOCNO>
