<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Hijack 1stLd-Writethru   04-11 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hijack, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0841,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shiite Extremists Threaten To Kill Hostages If Plane Stormed In
Cyprus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5 grafs for last 7 grafs pvs to UPDATES with Hezbollah
saying it wasn't involved in hijacking and terming Higgins' capture
an arrest. Edits to trim. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American and French hostages in Lebanon
will be killed if security forces storm a hijacked Kuwaiti jet in
Cyprus, a pro-Iranian group said in a statement.
   ``To the families of the hostages, we declare that we shall
execute the Western captives in Lebanon if the plane and holy
warrior (hijackers) aboard is subjected to any military
foolhardiness,'' the statement by the Shiite Moslem group Islamic
Jihad said.
   The threat was accompanied by photographs of two hostages,
journalists Terry A. Anderson, an American, and Jean-Paul Kauffmann
of France.
   Anderson, 40, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated
Press, is the longest held of the 22 foreigners missing after being
kidnapped in Lebanon. He was abducted March 16, 1985, in west
Beirut.
   Kauffmann, 43, was kidnapped May 22, 1985.
   The typed, Arabic-language statement was delivered Sunday to the
Reuters news agency in west Beirut.
   It declared full support for the hijackers' demand in Cyprus for
the release of 17 convicted pro-Iranian terrorists, all but one of
them Shiites, imprisoned in Kuwait for bombing the U.S. and French
embassies in December 1983. Kuwait has refused to free them.
   The statement said the 17 were jailed for ``confronting the
centers of international arrogance in our Islamic homeland along
with regimes that sold themselves cheaply to the superpowers and
their interests in the region.''
   Islamic Jihad claims to hold three Frenchmen and another
American, Thomas Sutherland, 55, of Fort Collins, Colo. He was
kidnapped June 9, 1985.
   Sutherland was acting dean of agriculture at the American
University of Beirut.
   Islamic Jihad has said the two other Frenchmen its men kidnapped
are Marcel Fontaine, 47, vice consul at the French Embassy,
abducted March 22, 1985, and Marcel Carton, 64, the embassy's
protocol officer, who was kidnapped in a separate attack the same
day.
   Today, a spokesman for Hezbollah, or Party of God, said his
group was ``not involved in any way'' in the hijacking. Chief
spokesman Sheik Ibrahim el-Amin, speaking to reporters in west
Beirut, declined to say if his group supports the hijackers' demand
for release of prisoners in Kuwait.
   Hezbollah is believed to be an umbrella organization for the
Shiite extremist factions holding many of the foreign hostages in
Lebanon. Hezbollah has never claimed responsibility for kidnapping
a foreigner.
   El-Amin also said U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins was
``not kidnapped but detained.''
   Higgins, 43, of Danville, Ky., was serving with a U.N.
peacekeeping force in south Lebanon when he was kidnapped near Tyre
on Feb. 17.
   El-Amin denied his group had been involved in Higgins' capture,
which has been claimed by the Organization of the Oppressed on
Earth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
