<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WastedRenovation     04-11 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wasted Renovation,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Base Plans To Demolish Building It Just Renovated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCOTT AIR FORCE BASE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scott Air Force Base officials
are planning to knock down a recently renovated building and make a
parking lot, despite workers' complaints that the Air Force is
wasting money.
   Workers and the president of the union representing civilian
employees at Scott criticized the Air Force for sinking $161,000
into a building they planned to demolish.
   But 1st Lt. Jerry Lobb, a base spokesman, said Building 1522 was
renovated earlier this year to improve working conditions because a
specific date to tear down the building had not yet been set.
   The building is near a $19 million Air Force Communications
Command facility that is under construction and targeted for
completion in June 1989, said Staff Sgt. Jerry Anderson, another
base spokesman.
   Lobb said Building 1522, now used as office space, would be
razed at some point to provide room for parking space for the new
command center.
   Carl Denton, president of Local R7-23 of the National
Association of Government Employees, said union officials
questioned the need for the renovation during meetings with base
management to discuss money-saving measures.
   ``There's nothing you can do if they've already spent money.
Once it's spent, it's gone, so we concentrated on things that could
be avoided. But (this kind of project) is what we said was work
that was not necessary,'' Denton said.
</TEXT>
