<DOCNO> AP880411-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 0933EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AlcoholConsumption     04-11 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alcohol Consumption,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People Drinking Less, But Character Of The Change Unclear.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People seem to be drinking less, and they worry
about alcohol more, but health researchers disagree about what it
means.
   ``Overall, there's a clear trend in the direction of
moderation,'' said Jay Winsten, director of the Center for Health
Communication at the Harvard School of Public Health.
   ``In terms of social mores, the public message used to be that
it's cool to get smashed. Now, it's dumb to get drunk.''
   The cutback in consumption grows in part from recent court
rulings in some states recognizing host liability for drunken
guests, he told The Boston Globe.
   ``Legal deterrence is a major factor in the moderation, but I
think it goes beyond that,'' he said. ``There is just much more
informal social pressure not to drink as much.''
   But Dr. Henry Wechsler, associate executive director of the
Medical Foundation in Boston, said the move to curb excess involves
a limited part of society.
   ``I still think we have a six-pack syndrome out there in much of
our society, and the data is there to support it,'' he said.
``Alcohol consumption has dropped, but not markedly and young
people are drinking as much as ever.''
   Massachusetts legislator Rep. Suzanne Bump filed legislation
last week to put warning labels on alcoholic beverage containers in
the state.
   ``The bottom line is that alcohol is still the nation's drug of
choice and a major health problem, especially among young people,''
she said.
   A recent Gallup Poll showed that the number of adults who
believe that alcohol is a problem in their homes has doubled since
1974 to 24 percent.
   In 1980, per person consumption was 2.5 gallons of liquor, 2.6
gallons of wine and 30.7 gallons of beer. In 1985, liquor use
dropped to 2.2 gallons, beer eased off to 29.6 gallons, but wine
consumption rose to 2.9 gallons.
   Eddie Burke, co-owner of Doyle's, an Irish pub in Boston, said
the bar now sells five cases of nonalcoholic beer weekly, while
three years ago there were no takers.
   ``People are just drinking less, although they're drinking more
of the quality stuff,'' Burke said, adding that his bartenders now
shut off patrons more quickly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
