<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ScoutmasterAttacked     04-11 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scoutmaster Attacked,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Boy Scout Attacks Scoutmaster Over 12-year Merit Badge
Grudge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE SILVER BOROUGH, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 25-year-old former Boy
Scout allegedly attacked his old scoutmaster with a knife after a
chance meeting brought back memories of a 12-year-old grudge over a
merit badge, police said.
   John F. Wilbert was held on $110,000 bail in the assault on
Harold W. Scott Jr., 55, police said.
   Wilbert told authorities that Scott had kept him waiting too
long when he went to his home as an eighth-grader to work on a
merit badge project.
   Wilbert, a Navy veteran, did not see Scott again until he passed
him on the street two weeks ago, said Little Silver police Capt.
Thomas F. Bruno.
   Scott says he doesn't remember Wilbert, who grew up here and now
lives a few miles away in Long Branch, but Bruno said the chance
encounter prompted ``flashbacks'' for Wilbert.
   On Thursday night, Wilbert rang Scott's door bell, Bruno said.
When Scott answered, Wilbert slashed him about the head and upper
body, Bruno alleged.
   Scott, who retired in January after 21 years as a scoutmaster,
bit Wilbert, wrestled the knife away, ran back into the house and
called police, Bruno said.
   Wilbert was caught while he headed to his car parked nearby,
Bruno said. He was charged with attempted murder and, because
police said they found tools in Wilbert's car like those that would
be used in a burglary, he also was charged with burglary.
   Scott was hospitalized briefly for treatment of multiple
lacerations.
</TEXT>
