<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrizeCats     04-11 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prize Cats,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cat Lover Makes Prize Winners Of Skid Row Felines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Karin Jackson has a knack for taking the lemons of
the cat world and turning out lemonade.
   Her latest victory came Sunday when a blue-spotted tabby named
Amy was given the 9-Lives Morris Award after being judged the best
household cat at Denver's Campaign Tails spring cat show.
   In fact, four of Jackson's six contestants swept the household
competition at the show, sponsored by the Foot of the Rockies Cat
Club Inc.
   Cages for Amy, Chip, Koko and Little Miss Muffet were covered
with so many red, white and blue ribbons that some had to be moved
so spectators could see the prize-winning felines.
   ``I'm doing very well, without boasting,'' said Jackson, who
said she is known as a ``cat lady'' back home in Salt Lake City.
   Jackson, a native of Germany, fell in love with cats shortly
after she came to the United States in 1961. Now she drives her
cats in a station wagon to competitions around the West.
   Purebred cats are judged on precise calculations of color, build
and hair length, Jackson said. Household pets are judged on health,
cleanlines, color and personality.
   Jackson fondly recalls Pedro, a stray dropped off in June 1979.
By April 1980, Pedro was named the best household cat in all of
North America, she said.
   Amy was abandoned with her siblings at Jackson's home when she
was 7 weeks old.
   Now, at 8 months, she's a prize-winner.
   ``She was so outgoing,'' Jackson said. ``A sweetheart. Easy to
handle. It shows that with proper care, good food _ no junk food _
medical attention ... and lots of love, you can make a throw-away,
dirty, neglected, undernourished cat a show cat.''
</TEXT>
