<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama-Noriega     04-11 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Noriega,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panamanian Leader Says He'd Rather Be Somewhere Else</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
today was quoted as saying he would really rather be somewhere
else, but that he was fighting an American attempt to control
Panama.
   ``Ah yes,'' Noriega was quoted as telling the Paris newspaper Le
Monde in an interview published today. ``I would like to be
somewhere else.'' He did not say where.
   Although Noriega is ready to leave Panama, the newspaper said,
he is not ready to be pushed out.
   ``Foreigners have trouble understanding our mentality,'' Noriega
was quoted as saying. ``It is a struggle that we have been waging
for a long time against the American presence here. It is not a
personal fight, but that of a people and a nation. It is the
destiny of a country that is at stake.''
   Le Monde said Noriega is convinced that President Reagan, who
always opposed the 1977 treaties turning over the Panama Canal to
Panama, wants to reclaim the canal.
   ``The attitude of the United States is very suspect,'' the
general was quoted as saying. ``We began to have problems with it
from the moment we denounced violations of the treaties, when we
defended an independent, Third World, non-aligned policy on the
international scene, and above all when we refused to participate
in a military intervention in Nicaragua to overthrow the Sandinista
regime.''
   He said Washington ``wants to rewrite history, cancel the
treaties by imposing a government controlled by them and reversing
social achievements.''
   Asked if his departure would not put an end to the crisis and
ease the suffering of the Panamanian people, Noriega said: ``I
refuse to answer that question,'' he said. ``If the people are
suffering, it is because of the United States, not me.''
   He brushed aside questions about his role in the drug trade.
   ``The problem is not here,'' he said. ``It is in the United
States. The United States is the consumer country. It is there that
the drugs are paid for. There are drug-producing countries and
there are consumer countries. The other countries, like Panama, are
passage routes.''
   The general agreed that Panama's liberal financial laws make it
easy for drug transactions, but he said ``the money was not
invested here ... therefore you cannot say that the laundering of
this drug money is done here. We were only a step in the process
controlled by the United States.''
   He said the United States was behind making Panama a banking
center, ``and it is they who have decided to dismantle it.''
</TEXT>
