<1ST_LINE>d a PM-Obit-Citrin     04-11 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Citrin,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Only Non-Family Executor Of Henry Ford II's Estate, 59</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin E. Citrin, a close friend of Henry
Ford II and the only non-family executor of Ford's estate, has died
of a self-inflicted gunshot at the age of 59, police said.
   Citrin's body was found Saturday at a motel in Romulus, west of
Detroit, police and Wayne County Medical Examiner Werner Spitz
said. The Bloomfield Hills businessman and Jewish community leader
checked into the motel Thursday.
   Police and Citrin's brother, Toby, offered no reasons for the
death.
   Citrin was an executor of Henry Ford II's estate along with
Ford's widow, Kathy DuRoss Ford, and Ford's son, Edsel Ford II, who
declined comment. Edsel Ford has served as family spokesman since
his father's death in September.
   In addition to family oil interests, in 1984, Citrin and his
brother founded Ways and Means, a company that supplies health care
products for the elderly and handicapped. Citrin was a child polio
victim and needed crutches to walk.
   Survivors include Citrin's mother, Matilda Citrin; his wife,
Myra; two daughters, two sons and a grandson.
</TEXT>
