<1ST_LINE>r i PM-CentAmerica-Soviet     04-11 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CentAmerica-Soviet,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Says Won't Send Arms to Central America if U.S. Agrees To
Same</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OLDEMAR RAMIREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev said in a
letter to President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica that the Soviet
government was prepared to stop sending arms to Central America if
the United States agreed to do the same.
   In the letter, the Soviet Communist Party general secretary also
said he had proposed to the United States to embargo all arms
shipments to the region, except for firearms for police forces.
   The Soviet Union is a major arms supplier to Nicaragua's
Sandinista government.
   Reports that the Soviet Union was sending arms to leftist
Salvadoran and Guatemalan guerrillas were ``totally unfounded,''
said the letter, which was made public Saturday by Arias' press
office.
   Gorbachev said his government was conducting its relations with
Central America's governments in accordance with the regional peace
plan authored by Arias and signed by the five Central American
presidents on Aug. 7.
   That plan calls for an end to outside assistance for
insurgencies in the region, cease-fires in Nicaragua, El Salvador,
and Guatemala, and talks aimed at establishing democratic elections
in the region.
   ``The Soviet Union is ready to assume, on a reciprocal basis
with the United States, the obligation to respect and rigorously
comply with the accords relative to conditions of security, the
control and limitation of arms,'' the letter said.
   Gorbachev was responding to a letter Arias sent on March 7
asking the Soviet leader to suspend arms shipments to the region.
   Arias has urged Gorbachev and President Reagan to include
Central America as a topic in their next summit meeting, scheduled
for May.
   Gorbachev said the two superpowers had yet to agree to stop
sending arms because ``the United States neither pursues nor wants
to hear talk of any reduction in U.S. arms shipments to Honduras
and El Salvador.''
   The Honduran and Salvadoran governments are the Reagan
administration's principal allies in Central America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
