<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SuspectEscape     04-11 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Suspect Escape,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspect Escapes When Guards Leave Keys in Van</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused in the torture-murder of
a nurse was still at large today after he drove off in a prisoner
van when his guards went into a convenience store and left the keys
behind.
   Police used helicopters and dogs to search for Richard Lacy
Letner Jr., 27, after the Sunday escape.
   ``He should be considered extremely dangerous,'' said police
Sgt. Jim Nelson of Visalia, Calif. Letner was being taken from Iowa
to California to stand trial for the March 1 strangulation and
stabbing of Ivon Portbriant, Nelson said.
   Letner and eight other prisoners were in a van owned by
Interstate Extraditions of Bloomington, Ill., a private company
that uses former law officers to transport 3,000 prisoners across
the nation each year.
   Jim Kuzek, a spokesman for Interstate Extraditions, said the van
went to Texas to pick-up more prisoners, and was en route to Silver
City, N.M., before going to California. The
   The driver and another guard left the keys in the van when they
stopped at the convenience store.
   After kicking out a rear window, Letner got into the driver's
seat and drove the van about a block before using other keys to
unlock his handcuffs and shackles. He then abandoned the van and
fled on foot, said San Antonio police spokeswoman Sandy Perez.
   None of the other prisoners left the van, she said.
   Ms. Portbriant was found dead in her apartment with a telephone
cord wrapped around her neck, Nelson said. ``She had been stabbed
several times. She was tortured and then murdered.''
   Letner and another suspect were found in Ms. Portbriant's car
that night. The car was impounded but police let the men go free
before they learned of the murder. Both men were arrested in
Council Bluffs, Iowa, Nelson said.
   Kuzek of Interstate Extraditions said the guards violated
company policy by leaving the keys in the ignition. Together, the
guards have a total of 20 years of law enforcement experience, he
said.
</TEXT>
