<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Knights 1stLd-Writethru a0545 04-11 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Knights, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0545,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Briton Descended from Stuarts Picked to Lead Catholic Order</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS formal title in 11th graf pvs ``Andrew
Willoughby...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A descendant of Britain's royal Stuart family was
elected leader of the Knights of Malta, an ancient Roman Catholic
charitable order, it was announced today.
   Fra Andrew Bertie was voted grand master at a secret conclave of
36 electors Friday at the group's villa in Rome. His election makes
him the highest-ranking layman in the Catholic church.
   The order, founded with a pilgrims' hospice in 11th century
Jerusalem, has the status of an independent state. It maintains
diplomatic relations with 50 nations.
   Its 10,000 members, led by Italy with 2,800 and the United
States with 2,500, operate about 200 hospitals and first-aid
centers in 90 countries, especially in the Third World and war
zones.
   The announcement of Bertie's election was delayed for approval
by Pope John Paul II.
   Bertie was one of 22 eligible candidates at the conclave. The
electors from the group's Council Complete of State voted by secret
ballot, and no tally was announced.
   Other council members are presidents of the order's worldwide
associations, including New York financier J. Peter Grace.
   Bertie, 58, is the knights' 78th grand master, or supreme
leader. He succeeds Fra Angelo de Mojana di Cologna, an 82-year-old
Italian who died Jan. 18 after 25 years as grand master.
   Officially known as the Sovereign Military Order of the Hospital
of St. John of Jerusalem, of Rhodes and of Malta, the group only
selects as grand master people who have followed vows of poverty,
obedience and chastity. They must also have 200 years of nobility
on both parents' sides.
   Elected for life, the grand master carries the title of prince
and ``most eminent highness.'' The position is equal in rank to a
cardinal.
   Andrew Willoughby Ninian Bertie of the Earls of Lindsey and
Abingdon _ his full title _ was born in London on May 15, 1929,
according to the order's statement.
   His father, James, worked as foreign exchange dealer at the
stock exchange there.
   His mother, Lady Jean Crichton-Stuart, was a descendant of the
Stuarts, the ruling family of Scotland from 1371-1603 and of
England and Scotland from 1603-1714, with an 11-year interruption
in the 17th century. Bertie's aunt on his mother's side was married
to the brother of Sir Winston Churchill.
   As a youth, Bertie studied at a Benedectine boarding school in
Ampleforth. He earned a degree in modern history at Christ Church
College of Oxford.
   For more than 20 years, he taught French, Spanish and Russian at
a Benedictine school in Worth in southern England.
   He joined the knights in 1956 and took his vows his 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
