<DOCNO> AP880411-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchnickTrial     04-11 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Schnick Trial,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Begins In Multiple Slayings Of Family</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA BRYSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSHFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began with tight security
today at the trial of a southwest Missouri dairy farmer accused of
killing seven members of his family in a fall shooting spree.
   James E. Schnick, 36, of nearby Elkland, faces seven counts of
first-degree murder in the deaths of his wife and her brother and
his family on Sept. 25.
   Immediately after the killings, police had speculated that one
of the victims, a 14-year-old boy, was responsible.
   Highway Patrol officers helped Webster County deputies search
the courtroom and inspect each spectator with a metal detector
before proceedings began.
   Sheriff Eugene Fraker said the security measures were taken as a
precaution and not because of any threats.
   Schnick sat quietly between his two attorneys. His hands were
clenched tightly but unshackled. He began to cry quietly when the
judge read the charges against him to the potential jurors.
   More than 100 prospective jurors were scheduled to be
interviewed today.
   The courthouse is a short drive from the scene of the slayings
at two family dairy farms in the tiny community of Elkland.
   Proceedings are likely to center on what prosecutor Donald
Cheever says is Schnick's confession.
   According to statements made in a pre-trial hearing in February,
Schnick implicated himself Oct. 5 at Missouri State Highway Patrol
troop headquarters in Springfield, where, as the only witness in
the slayings, he had been taken to undergo a lie detector test.
   Schnick's attorneys, county public defender James McNabb and
special state public defender Susan Chapman, had attempted to have
Schnick's statements suppressed. They said the statements were
unfairly obtained by a Webster County sheriff's deputy who
exploited both his friendship with Schnick and the suspect's
fragile mental and physical condition.
   Circuit Judge John Parrish ruled that the confession was
admissable.
   Schnick is accused of shooting his wife Julie, 30; her brother
Steve Buckner, 35; Buckner's wife Jeannette, 36; and the Buckner's
four children: Kirk, 14; Dennis, 8; Timmy, 6; and Michael, 2. The
Schnicks' two young children were not injured.
   Authorities initially speculated that Kirk was responsible.
Schnick, who suffered minor wounds that morning, told officers that
he and his family had been attacked by an unknown intruder.
   Kirk was found with the gun used in the killings in his right
hand, but authorities later discovered he was left-handed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
