<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StudentProtest     04-11 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Student Protest,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>About 400 Rally At Denison; Blacks Boycott Classes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRANVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black students boycotted classes today at
Denison University to protest what they call lenient treatment of
white students involved in a racial incident, and about 400
students and faculty members attended a rally.
   University spokesman Stewart Dyke said the rally was peaceful
and included a speech by university trustee Clifford Tyree, who
said he would recommend the institution adopt a policy of immediate
suspension from school for racial harassment.
   ``They're really using it as an educational opportunity to
address the issues and incidents of racism that they've seen on the
increase,'' Dyke said of the rally. ``They're putting it into the
context of the new racism on campuses these days.''
   The protest resulted from an incident last week. Two students
accused of verbally harassing Aaron Laramore, a black senior from
Toledo who is head resident at the private school's Huffman Hall
dormitory, were suspended for one semester Friday by the University
Judicial Board. A third white student was found innocent.
   About 80 of 2,100 undergraduates at the school in a suburb of
Columbus are black, Dyke said.
   The white students, who lived in a room adjacent to Laramore's,
testified that they were having a private conversation early on the
morning of April 1. But the Black Student Union claimed the racial
slurs were aimed at Laramore.
   Dyke refused to identify the students, citing Denison's privacy
policy.
   The Black Student Union said it was ``profoundly disappointed at
the shortsighted, insensitive and totally unsatisfactory decision
by the board.''
   Steve Gaskill, a sophomore and member of the Black Student
Union, said the group met before the hearing and agreed not to
accept any punshisment less than a year-long suspension for the
students found guilty.
   ``I don't expect an end,'' he said regarding the protest. ``I do
expect an impact on the students to end apathy about racism on
campus.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
