<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Finland-Rabies     04-11 0123</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Finland-Rabies,0128</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Finland Leashes Cats, Dogs to Control Rabies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Monday ordered all cats
and dogs leashed in order to stop an outbreak of rabies.
   The Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry imposed the order after
a fox and dog died of rabies in the southeastern corner of Finland.
Officials believe the rabies came from the Soviet Union, which
shares a nearby border.
   Authorities also asked hunters in the area to concentrate on
killing foxes, raccoons and badgers, as well as stray dogs and cats.
   Household pets can come down with the viral disease through
contact with infected animals. People can be infected with rabies
through animal bites.
   There were no reports of human cases in the outbreak.
</TEXT>
