<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Reed-Taxes     04-11 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reed-Taxes,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Movie Critic Rex Reed In Police Court For Attempted State Tax
Evasion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Movie critic Rex Reed pleaded guilty today
to attempted state tax evasion charges in a dispute he blamed on a
former accountant's advice.
   In an agreement with the state Attorney General's office, Reed
already had paid approximately $20,000 to the state Department of
Taxation and Finance to cover deliquent taxes, penalties and
interest.
   `It's ironic that this would happen on Academy Awards day,'' he
said outside the court, adding that he didn't believe he would be
able to get a flight to Los Angeles in time for the awards.
   ``I'm going to miss seeing Cher's navel,'' he said. Cher was his
pick for best actress in the film ``Moonstruck.''
   Appearing in City Police Court, Reed, 49, entered a guilty plea
on two misdemeanor counts of attempted tax evasion for failing to
file state returns in 1984 and 1985 while employed as a columnist
for the New York Post. He was fined $2,000.
   The Tax Department found that the Post paid Reed as an
independent contractor for 1984 and 1985, ``therefore he was
earning income from a New York state employer, but had not filed
the New York state returns,'' said Nancy Connell, a spokeswoman for
the Attorney General's office.
   Reed told reporters that since he lives in Connecticut he should
have filed nonresident tax forms but said an accountant he no
longer retains told him that wasn't necessary.
   State tax officials said Reed's primary address is New York City.
   Reed was a columnist for the Daily News in New York City for 12
years, then worked for the Post from 1982 until last year. He
currently appears on the syndicated television series ``At The
Movies.''
</TEXT>
