<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CrackRaid 1stLd-Writethru a0492 04-11 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crack Raid, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Raid Moved Up In Time For TV Documentary, Officials Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf and 8th graf pvs, ``About 60 xxx, to update
arrest total to 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Murder Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLES TOWN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police raid on suspected drug
dealers was conducted weeks ahead of schedule because a network
television crew planned to show the suspects in a nationally
televised documentary, officials said.
   The weekend sting resulted in 29 arrests, but one West Virginia
state trooper suffered a gunshot wound and two others were injured
in a traffic accident.
   The alleged dealings near a shopping center were covered in just
25 seconds of Sunday night's hourlong ABC-TV documentary titled
``Drugs: A Plague Upon the Land.''
   U.S. Attorney William Kolibash, who originally was concerned
that if the suspects saw themselves on TV they would flee, said
after the show aired that the influence probably would have been
minimal.
   ``These people were so blatant that they probably would have
been back out there within a week,'' Kolibash said.
   Saturday's raid focused on runners peddling crack cocaine
shipped in from Miami, and Washington, D.C., by Jamaican dealers,
Kolibash said.
   The suspects were using the rural county to cater to out-of-town
buyers who ``didn't want to have to worry about the dangers'' of
city crime, he said. The county is less than an hour's drive from
suburban Washington.
   About 60 state and federal agents Saturday afternoon began
serving arrest warrants on 40 people accused of distributing crack.
A total of 29 arrests have been made, authorities said today, and
more are pending.
   A national magazine article several weeks ago detailed a
Jamaican drug connection to Jefferson County, and a television crew
arrived shortly thereafter.
   Kolibash said he offered to let the reporters do their work from
unmarked police vehicles, but also asked that their pictures not be
aired until the suspects were arrested.
   ``We were kind of concerned that if some of those people saw
themselves on television, they would disappear,'' Kolibash said.
   ABC News officials didn't hold off, however, and scheduled the
special show for Sunday night, Kolibash said.
   ABC News spokeswoman Joyce Kravitz denied that the network was
responsible for speeding up the drug arrests.
   ``My understanding is that they offered to move the date,'' she
said. ``They volunteered to do that. It wasn't anything we asked
for.''
</TEXT>
