<HEAD>With PM-Pakistan-Blasts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Navy Bomb-Disposal Team Sent to Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A five-man bomb disposal team from the Navy
has been sent to Islamabad, Pakistan, in the wake of Sunday's
massive blast at an ammunition depot, the Pentagon said today.
   Lt. Col. Keith Schneider, a Pentagon spokesman, said the team
was flown from an aircraft carrier battle group operating in the
northern Arabian Sea on Sunday at the request of the U.S.
ambassador.
   Schneider said the government of Pakistan had made no request
for assistance. The explosives experts will be on call ``in the
event that unexploded ordnance is found in U.S. compounds,'' the
spokesman said.
   ``This was a prudent precautionary measure,'' he added. ``They
were sent at the request of the American ambassador to render any
assistance required by the U.S. country team (in Pakistan).''
   The Sunday explosion sent projectiles into populated areas in
and around Pakistan's capital, killing at least 93 people and
wounding more than 1,000.
