<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Mecca     04-11 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Mecca,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khomeini Says Protest in Mecca is Religious Duty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini said Monday
that 150,000 Iranian pilgrims would travel to Mecca this year and
stage demonstrations against the United States and Israel.
   These intentions had been announced earlier this year by other
Iranian officials but it was the first time that Iran's 87-year-old
spiritual leader has referred to them.
   Saudi Arabia has said it will cut the number of pilgrims
traveling to the holy city this year but has not announced any
figures.
   Last year 402 pilgrims, including 275 Iranians, were killed in
riots that began with a rally against ``pagans'' in the holy city
in Saudi Arabia during the hajj, or pilgrimage.
   Saudi officials said many pilgrims were trampled to death in a
stampede or killed in subsequent street brawls that followed the
demonstration. Iran claimed police mowed down the pilgrims with
machine guns.
   After the violence last summer, Iran called for the overthrow of
the ruling family in Saudi Arabia, saying it was unfit to have
custody of Mecca and Medina, holy places of Islam.
   ``This year 150,000 pilgrims will participate in hajj rituals
and the pilgrims will do their duty, which is disowning the
infidels, America and Israel,'' Khomeini was quoted as saying by
Tehran radio, which was monitored in Nicosia.
   ``It is not possible for our pilgrims to take part in the hajj
and not demonstrate against world arrogance,'' Khomeini said.
``Basically, disowning the infidels is one of the political duties
of pilgrims, and without it the hajj would not be the hajj.''
</TEXT>
