<NOTE>For release at 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Hollings Receives Public Broadcasting Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Ernest F. Hollings received public
television's highest honor Monday for being ``a longtime champion
of public broadcasting.''
   Hollings, D-S.C., was to be presented with the 1988 Ralph Lowell
Award during a meeting Monday night of the Corporation for Public
Broadcasting, a private, non-profit corporation that develops
non-commercial radio and television services.
   When he was governor of South Carolina from 1959 to 1963,
Hollings was instrumental in creating the public TV system in his
state. Last year, together with Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, he
proposed a trust fund to create a permanent financial base for
public broadcasting.
