<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Baker-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0524 04-11 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baker-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0524,560</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 13 grafs new; picking up 2nd graf pvs, ``We worry</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's spokesman acknowledged
today that U.S. steps inentded to force Panamanian strongman Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega from power have seriously damaged that
nation's financial system, but expressed optimism Panama's economy
will recover.
   ``We don't think it is irreparable harm, but it is serious
harm,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters.
   He was queried about concerns expressed by leading Panamanians
that the past several weeks of financial turmoil triggered by U.S.
attempts to pressure Noriega to step down have caused permanent
damage to the country's once-flourishing financial system.
   Fitzwater contended that the U.S. steps, which included freezing
Panamanian assets in the United States, have been effective, even
though Noriega has not yet stepped down. The spokesman also
contended that the U.S. government has not intended to harm the
general population.
   ``They (the sanctions) were designed to strangle the financial
system,'' Fitzwater said.
   Noriega is under indictment in Florida for alleged drug
trafficking and U.S. officials have insisted that he relinquish
power and leave the country.
   In an effort to increase pressure on Noriega, Reagan on Friday
invoked the International Emergency Economic Powers Act for the
first time since invoking it against Libya two years ago. That
action banned all trade with Libya.
   The law prohibits payments _ including taxes _ by Americans and
U.S. corporations to the Panamanian government. One administration
official estimated last week that roughly 40 to 50 subsidiaries of
U.S. corporations would be affected.
   Fitzwater defended the steps as attempting ``to deny Noriega ...
money that could be used to perpetuate his stay in power.''
   ``We have tried to design those sanctions to affect the banking
and financial system of the country and not the general economy ...
and tried to minimize damage to the general public and general
economy while at the same time attacking the points of power that
constitute the base for Noriega staying in there,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``There is serious damage being done, in terms of the financial
system, but we think the banking system will be able to recover,''
he added.
   Earlier, Treasury Secretary James Baker said he's optimistic
that the new economic sanctions will force Noriega from power
without permanently damaging the economy.
   ``We worry about the Panamanian economy because what we've tried
to do is take action that would not hurt the Panamanian people,''
Baker said in an interview on the NBC-TV ``Today'' program.
   ``We've tried to take action directed toward getting Noriega to
step down,'' added Baker.
   Asked if the administration is considering even sterner moves to
force Noriega from power, Baker said he believes the new sanctions
``will be effective.''
   ``I think for the time being this is what should be done and
we're optimistic about the results,'' said the Treasury secretary.
   Panamanian assets in U.S. banks have been frozen since March,
when Reagan requested the Federal Reserve take the action after
deposed Panamanian President Eric Arturo Delvalle obtained an
injunction from a federal court in Miami.
   Reagan's executive order on Friday stopped short of a full
economic embargo on Panama, but violators can be prosecuted for
non-compliance with administration policy for the first time since
U.S.-Panama relations began to sour. Violators can be sentenced to
up to 10 years in prison and $50,000 in fines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
