<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Benton 1stLd-Writethru a0479 04-11 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Benton, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singer of `Rainy Night in Georgia' Dies at 56</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with two grafs to CORRECT cause of death</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brook Benton, whose stylish touch with pop
ballads led to hit songs in three decades, including ``Rainy Night
in Georgia,'' has died. He was 56.
   Benton died Saturday at Mary Immaculate Hospital. His managers
said today that he died of bacterial meningitis.
   His elegant baritone, backed by sweeping string arrangements,
was especially popular in the late 1950s and early 1960s. In 1959
alone he had four top 20 hits: ``It's Just a Matter of Time,'' `So
Many Ways,'' ``Endlessly'' and ``Thank You Pretty Baby.''
   Benton, who wrote many of his songs, sang several duets with
Dinah Washington, two of which, ``Baby (You've Got What it Takes)''
and ``A Rockin' Good Way,'' were hits.
   His biggest hit, however, came with ``Rainy Night in Georgia,''
a mournful tune that reached No. 4 on the Billboard pop chart in
1970.
   Benton, born Benjamin Peay in Lugoff, S.C., began singing at an
early age in the Methodist church choir in nearby Camden, where his
father was choir master. He started his career as a gospel singer.
   In recent years, he limited his performances to occasional
nightclub appearances, which concentrated on his hits, among them
``The Boll Weevil Song,'' ``Think Twice,'' ``Revenge,'' ``Frankie
and Johnny'' and ``For My Baby.''
   ``It was Benton's own idea to combine gospel intensity with lush
pop arrangements,'' according to the ``Rolling Stone Record
Guide,'' which described his singing as ``smooth and smoky.''
   ``From rock to ballads to blues, Benton never drops his easy
elegance, yet the swirling strings don't obscure his emotional
intensity,'' said the record guide.
   Benton, who lived in New York, is survived by his wife, Mary;
five children, and his mother, Maddie Peay of Lugoff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
