<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gelli     04-11 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gelli,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian Financier Released From Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARMA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A financier alleged to be the mastermind of
some of the biggest political and financial scandals in postwar
Italy was released from prison Monday because of a serious heart
condition.
   Licio Gelli was extradited from Switzerland less than two months
ago to face charges of fraudulent bankruptcy in the 1982 collapse
of Banco Ambrosiano.
   His release on ``provisional liberty'' was granted by Milan
judges Antonio Pizzi and Renato Brichetti.
   The frail, 68-year-old financier who once was Italy's
most-wanted fugitive left the jail in this north Italian city with
his son, Maurizio.
   Lawyers said Gelli, former head of Italy's outlawed P-2 masonic
lodge, will be hospitalized after a few days of rest at home.
   Gelli had fled Italy in 1981, ahead of a police raid on his
villa which uncovered links between the P-2 lodge and a ring of
right-wing terrorism.
   He was arrested in Switzerland in 1983 for entering the country
with false documents, but escaped from prison after a few months.
   Afer four years in hiding, Gelli surrendered to a Swiss
magistrate in September. He was extradited to Italy on Feb. 17.
   The major scandal involving Gelli was the $1.2 billion collapse
of the Vatican-linked Banco Ambrosiano in 1982.
   Gelli was a close associate of Roberto Calvi, the head of Banco
Ambrosiano who was known as ``God's banker'' because of his links
with the Vatican. Calvi was found hanged in London a few months
after his bank collapse.
   Gelli, held in a maximum-security cell, decided last week to
suspend all medical treatment to press his demand for provisional
liberty.
</TEXT>
