<DOCNO> AP880411-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1341EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PennCase     04-11 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Penn Case,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Attorney General Won't File Charges Against Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state attorney general's office today said
it would not file charges against San Diego police officers accused
of perjury or excessive force in connection with a case that raised
allegations of racism and brutality.
   A report issued today concludes an eight-month investigation
into the case involving Sagon Penn, a black who was acquitted in
the killing of one white police officer and the wounding of another.
   Penn claimed he was defending himself against a racially
motivated attack when he grabbed one of the officer's guns and
opened fire in the March 31, 1985, incident. Thomas Riggs was
killed and Donovan Jacobs and civilian observer Sarah Pina-Ruiz
were wounded.
   The state attorney general's investigation arose out allegations
made by Judge J. Morgan Lester, who presided over Penn's second
trial. The judge's public remarks came shortly after Penn was
acquitted in the retrial that ended July 16, 1987.
   Morgan said police officers lied on the witness stand and
suggested that Riggs and Jacobs engaged in ``nightstick justice,''
provoking the struggle that ensued after a traffic stop.
   State Attorney John Van de Kamp said there was insufficient
evidence to support successful prosecution. He also said Penn had
made it clear he didn't want any charges filed against Jacobs.
   Penn was at first reluctant to be interviewed by state
investigators, who interviewed him March 12 only after an immunity
agreement was worked out.
   During the questioning, Penn was unresponsive to many questions
and drifted off into other subjects such as religion and
philosophy, Van de Kamp said.
   Describing Penn as a troubled man, Van de Kamp said he didn't
think Penn would have made a credible witness and that his
testimony would have been crucial to a successful prosecution.
   The perjury allegations stemmed from testimony given by several
San Diego police officers regarding the police investigation and
Jacobs' character, which was described by the defense as bigoted.
   Van de Kamp said that criminal perjury requires a very high
standard of proof. He said the prosecution has to prove that a
witness knowingly gave false testimony in regard to a central issue
of the case.
   ``After careful investigation of eight incidents of possible
perjury, our lawyers concluded that there was either no evidence or
insufficient evidence to meet that very high standard,'' the
attorney general said.
   Another key issue was the possible use of excessive force. Van
de Kamp said there was substantial evidence that officers used
excessive force at the beginning and at the end of the
confrontation.
   But he said there was no evidence to sustain a charge of battery
against Riggs.
   ``As to Agent Jacobs, the decision was much more difficult. The
most consistent accounts from eyewitnesses suggest that Jacobs did
use excessive force, both at the beginning of the incident and
after Penn was on the ground.''
   But because there were conflicting accounts among eyewitnesses,
without coherent testimony from Penn, the state couldn't sustain a
battery charge against Jacobs, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
