<HEAD>US Backs Cypriot Stand on Hijackers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration expressed firm
support Monday for the refusal by Cypriot officials to comply with
a demand by the hijackers of a Kuwait Airways jet that the aircraft
be refueled.
   Department spokesman Charles Redman also said the United States
supports Kuwait's decision not to abide by the hijackers' demand
for the release of 17 convicted terrorists in that country.
   ``The hijackers are murderers trying to free other convicted
murderers,'' Redman said. ``They must be punished. ''
   He added that the United States is ``appalled at the
cold-blooded murder of two innocent hostages'' aboard the aircraft.
   The second victim, killed on Monday, was identified as a
``Kuwaiti officer.'' He was thrown out of the plane onto the tarmac
at the airport in Larnaca.
   Redman also dismissed as ``cynical'' a threat by the Islamic
Jihad in Beirut to kill the hostages they are holding if any harm
comes to the hijackers.
   ``We continue to hold the kidnapers in Lebanon fully responsible
for the safety and well being of all the hostages there,'' he said.
