<1ST_LINE>r w PM-OffshoreSales     04-11 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Offshore Sales,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interior Department Postpones Offerings of Offshore Oil and Gas
Leases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A heavy workload has forced the Interior
Department to postpone seven planned offerings of offshore oil and
gas leases in 1989, 1990 and 1991, the department said today.
   Four are in federal waters off Alaska, two off California and
one off the mid-Atlantic states.
   The Alaska postponements are in the Navarin Basin, from January
1989 to December 1989; the Norton Basin, from December 1989 to
September 1991; the North Aleutian Basin, from May 1990 to October
1990; and the Navarin Basin, from September 1991 to June 1992.
   The two California postponements, announced last week by members
of that state's congressional delegation, are off Southern
California, from September 1989 to January 1990; and off Central
California, from November 1990 to March 1991.
   The Atlantic offering postponed from October 1989 to December
1989 is for waters from roughly the Rhode Island-Massachusetts
border to a bit south of Cape Hatteras, N.C.
   ``Staff problems and work overloads,'' was how Marcia
Heimberger, spokeswoman for the department's Minerals Management
Service, described the reasons for the changes.
   The California postponements were made necessary by a heavy
volume of comments for a lease offering off northern California
scheduled for next February, she said.
   The new schedule shows 34 remaining offerings under the
five-year drilling plan adopted last July, reflecting the dropping
of the June 1992 offering off the eastern coast of Florida under an
agreement with the state announced in March.
</TEXT>
