<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Lebanon     04-11 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Lebanon,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Stages Unusual Cross-Border Drug Raid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli police and soldiers swept into southern
Lebanon and arrested dozens of drug traffickers suspected of
smuggling heroin and hashish into Israel, police said Monday.
   The unusual raid Sunday night was aimed at checking a growing
cross-border drug trade and narcotics addiction in Israel's
self-proclaimed security zone in Lebanon, the officials said.
   Lebanese sources said more than 100 Israeli police with dogs
detained 65 drug traffickers in three villages north of the border,
Bint Jbeil, Klaia and Marjayoun, and confiscated nearly nine pounds
of heroin and cocaine and 110 pounds of hashish.
   An Israeli police spokeswoman, Edna Ziegelshifer, said the
action was to ``keep drug merchants away from Israel and followed
several attempts by traffickers to smuggle drugs accross the
border.''
   She said the troops seized ``different kinds of weapons and a
large quantity of drugs including heroin and hashish,'' but
declined to elaborate.
   Haim Ariev, Israel's liaison officer in south Lebanon, told the
Christian-owned Voice of the South radio station the action also
came in response to local complaints of growing addiction to drugs
smuggled mostly from Lebanon's Syrian-controlled Bekaa Valley.
   Israel established the so-called security zone, a six- to
10-mile-wide area north of the border, after withdrawing most of
its occupation troops from Lebanon in 1985.
</TEXT>
