<1ST_LINE>r p AM-TexasRunoffs     04-11 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texas Runoffs,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman, Rich Businessman Seek Texas GOP Senate Nomination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Beau Boulter battles Houston
businessman Wes Gilbreath on Tuesday in a primary runoff for the
Republican nomination to challenge Democratic Sen. Lloyd Bentsen.
   Gilbreath, who has spent about $1 million of his own money in
the race, was the top candidate in the March 8, four-man GOP
primary with 37 percent of the vote. Boulter got 30 percent and
later picked up endorsements from the candidates who ran third and
fourth. The runoff was required because no candidate received a
majority.
   Boulter, 46, also has been endorsed by a majority of Texas
Republican leaders.
   Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., campaigned Monday for Boulter in several
Texas cities. Boulter, a two-term congressman from Amarillo, backed
Kemp's failed bid for the Republican presidential nomination.
   The presidential race and Gilbreath's money were the featured
issues in the campaign. Gilbreath, 59, a first-time office seeker,
said Boulter's support of Kemp would hurt Texas if Vice President
George Bush becomes president.
   Boulter said Gilbreath supported former television evangelist
Pat Robertson's unsuccessful bid for the GOP presidential
nomination. Gilbreath has declined to say for whom he voted in
Texas' Super Tuesday Republican presidential primary.
   The Boulter campaign spent about $250,000 and complained about
Gilbreath's deep pockets.
   ``I don't think it's healthy to try to buy a nomination with
your own money,'' Boulter said.
   Bentsen, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, breezed to
renomination in March over a little-known San Antonio professor.
The incumbent has said he does not care which Republican he faces
in his November bid for a fourth term in the U.S. Senate.
</TEXT>
