<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-US     04-11 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-US,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Vietnam to Discuss Amerasians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Vietnamese officials will hold
immigration talks this week and likely discuss Washington's plan to
accept within two years all children remaining in Vietnam that were
fathered by American servicemen, a U.S. official said Monday.
   Ross Petzing, spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok, said
the negotiations also will cover additional Vietnamese immigration
to the United States. Since 1980, 64,000 Vietnamese have gone to
the United States.
   In January, Hanoi agreed in principle to Washington's offer to
resettle within two years the estimated 8,000-12,000 Amerasians and
up to 22,000 close relatives remaining in Vietnam. The United
States has said the children suffer prejudice in Vietnam, which
American troops left in 1973.
   Bruce Beardsley, head of the embassy's refugee office in
Bangkok, will join the talks in Hanoi on Wednesday, Petzing said.
   ``A prime focus of the talks with Hanoi will be the Amerasian
program, and consequently ... the two-year program is likely to be
discussed,'' Petzing said.
   The proposal is based on recent legislation that reclassfied
Amerasians as immigrants rather than refugees, a change likely to
hasten resettlement.
   Since 1980, the United States has accepted more than 4,000
Amerasians under a U.N.-sponsored program. Vietnam suspended its
participation from January 1986 until September 1987, when the
United States agreed to streamline procedures.
   Vietnam's Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach said Thursday that
the Americans were ``lazy'' in taking the children and he would
like them to go even quicker than two years.
   ``We have told them they can take them all tomorrow,'' he said.
   The resettlement program was established in 1980 as an
alternative to the flight of refugees in boats.
   Petzing said in the latest round of interviews, U.S. officials
had screened about 1,000 Amerasians and relatives, and 1,000 other
Vietnamese.
</TEXT>
