<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Paton     04-11 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paton,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paton Goes Home; Cancer `Spreading Fast'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author Alan Paton, critically ill
with throat cancer, was released from a hospital Monday to spend
his final days at home, his wife said.
   Paton, 85, was hospitalized last week and underwent surgery
April 5 to allow him to swallow solids despite a tumor in his
esophagus. The operation was unsuccessful and a second operation
was ruled out.
   His wife, Anne, said the cancer was spreading fast and the
family decided to have him spend his final days at home.
   ``I am sure he is the happier for it,'' she said.
   Mrs. Paton said over the weekend that her husband had less than
a week to live.
   Paton is best known for his 1948 novel, ``Cry, The Beloved
Country,'' often cited as the most compelling story of South
Africa's apartheid system of racial segregation.
   Paton's last book, ``Journey Continued,'' a sequel to his
autobiography, ``Towards the Mountain,'' is to be published this
month. His publishers had planned a party which Paton was to attend.
   He said in November that ``Journey Continued'' would be his last
book.
   In addition to writing, Paton was a long-time anti-apartheid
political activist.
</TEXT>
