<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Strike     04-11 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Strike,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilots, Flight Engineers Strike Domestic Airline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pilots and flight engineers of Air Inter, the
largest French domestic airline, began a three-day strike Monday,
but company officials said most flights went off as scheduled.
   The strike is one in a series to protest Air Inter's decision to
fly the new Airbus A320 aircraft with only two cockpit crew members
instead of three. The first A320 is scheduled to go into service
with Air Inter in June on the Paris-Grenoble line.
   The personnel have conducted a series of strikes since Feb. 16,
but until Monday had limited the action to the morning hours, from
midnight until 8 a.m., and exempting Saturdays, Sundays and
holidays.
   According to Air Inter, 80 percent of the flights went off
because it used non-striking crews and leased planes from other
companies.
   Since the company made its decision in November 1985 to fly its
A320s with only pilot and co-pilot, the personnel have claimed that
it would be unsafe. Under that system, the flight engineer's
navigating equipment is installed in front of the pilot and
co-pilot.
   The A320 was conceived and certified for flight by a two-member
crew. The smaller crew also means lower operating costs.
   Union members on Monday denounced the lack of negotiations
between the union and the company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
