<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Panama     04-11 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Sees Panamanian Economy Bouncing Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. attempts to topple Panamanian strongman
Manuel Antonio Noriega have caused ``serious damage'' to Panama's
economy, but it will bounce back, President Reagan's chief
spokesman predicted Monday.
   Marlin Fitzwater said U.S.-imposed sanctions ``were designed to
strangle the financial system'' of the Central American nation but
not harm the general population.
   The spokesman was asked to respond to assertions by leading
Panamanians that the past weeks of financial turmoil have crippled
the country's once-flourishing economic system, perhaps forever.
   Panama, which uses the U.S. dollar as its currency, had become
known as a stable and reliable banking center in both North and
South America.
   But the financial system has been nearly paralyzed since March,
when the United States froze $50 million in Panamanian government
funds in American banks. The U.S. step followed Noriega's ouster of
President Eric Arturo Devalle, who is still recognized by the
administration as Panama's president.
   In an effort to increase pressure on Noriega, Reagan last Friday
invoked the International Emergency Economic Powers Act. The law
prohibits payments _ including taxes _ by Americans and U.S.
corporations to the Panamanian government. One administration
official estimated last week that roughly 40 to 50 subsidiaries of
U.S. corporations would be affected.
   The taxes are to be paid to an account opened for deposed
President Delvalle.
   Fitzwater defended the steps as attempting ``to deny Noriega ...
money that could be used to perpetuate his stay in power.''
   ``We have tried to design those sanctions to affect the banking
and financial system of the country and not the general economy ...
and tried to minimize damage to the general public and general
economy while at the same time attacking the points of power that
constitute the base for Noriega staying in there,'' he said.
   ``We don't think it is irreparable harm ... there is serious
damage being done, in terms of the financial system, but we think
the banking system will be able to recover,'' he added.
   Fitzwater contended that the U.S. steps have been effective,
even though Noriega has not yet stepped down.
   Noriega heads Panama's 15,000-member Defense Forces and is the
power behind the civilian government.
   In February, two federal grand juries in Florida indicted
Noriega on drug-trafficking charges. The United States imposed
economic sanctions on Panama after Noriega rejected Washington's
demands that he resign and leave the country.
   Reagan's executive order on Friday stopped short of a full
economic embargo on Panama, but violators can be prosecuted for
non-compliance with administration policy for the first time since
U.S.-Panama relations began to sour. Violators can be sentenced to
up to 10 years in prison and $50,000 in fines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
