<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EatonvilleSurvival     04-11 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eatonville Survival,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Fear Five-lane Road Will Crush Town's Heritage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EATONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan to expand a two-lane road to five
lanes has sparked fears that it would destroy the residential
heritage of the nation's first incorporated black community.
   Residents of the 100-year-old community are worried that the
county's plan would threaten the city's history. The Association to
Preserve the Eatonville Community and two private citizens joined
in a class-action suit in March against Orange County.
   The group opposes a 1.3-mile highway which would replace a
two-lane road through the two-square-mile town's commercial and
civic center. The road also would cut through a neighborhood in
nearby Maitland.
   ``I don't think they're paying proper attention to what
Eatonville and Maitland have done to preserve the residential
nature of our cities,'' said Germaine Marvel, a member of the
preservation group.
   ``This is Eatonville's main street. This is where the schools,
the grocery stores, the churches in this little town are located,''
he said.
   John Kingman Keating, an attorney for the group, said the
lawsuit is novel because it says the public need for roads is
outweighed by the greater need to preserve a historically unique
town and to balance transportation improvements with existing
neighborhoods.
   County commissioners say central Florida is growing so rapidly
that something must be done to prevent future traffic jams. They
also think the road could help Eatonville.
   ``It could move commercial interests and increase thair tax
base,'' aid Tom Dorman, chairman of the board of commissioners.
   But most residents don't want the road.
   ``Everyone knows this is a community-busting road,'' said N.Y.
Nathiri, who heads the association against the road-widening.
``You'll have a nonexistent or nonfunctioning black community.''
</TEXT>
