<1ST_LINE>r w AM-OffshoreSales     04-11 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Offshore Sales,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hodel Says He Erred in Excluding Some Areas From Offshore Drilling
Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If he had to handle offshore oil and gas sales
all over again, he'd do it differently by starting with all
possible areas up for leasing, Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel
told an industry audience Monday.
   ``I would recommend to my successor when he puts together the
next five-year (drilling) plan, that he ought not to exclude areas
from the plan as I did,'' Hodel told a convention of the National
Ocean Industries Association.
   The association represents oil companies operating offshore and
their suppliers.
   Plans drawn up by former Secretaries James Watt in the Reagan
administration and Cecil Andrus under President Carter did not rule
out any offshore areas from the start, relying on procedural steps
at later stages to drop unsuitable areas.
   Hodel noted that in drawing up the current plan, which took
effect last July, he excluded several environmentally sensitive
areas off the California coast such as Big Sur in the hope of
``eliminating arguments over areas not seriously part of anyone's
future drilling objectives.''
   ``But, instead, what I accomplished was what a friend of mine
calls `pre-emptive capitulation,''' Hodel said.
   ``My current view, based upon this experience, is that there
must be some quid pro quo _ such as that provided by Florida
Governor Bob Martinez in our recent negotiations on the Florida
Outer Continental Shelf.''
   Martinez and Hodel agreed last month that areas off the Florida
keys would not be offered for leasing under the current plan,
something Martinez and many Florida environmentalists wanted and
something that was easy for Hodel to grant because there is
believed to be little oil or gas there.
   In exchange, Martinez agreed to drop out of a multi-state legal
challenge to the five-year drilling plan, and not to oppose the
offer of certain tracts off the Florida Panhandle.
   The Florida sale was omitted from a revised schedule of 34
offerings that saw seven lease auctions delayed several months in
1989, 1990 and 1991 because of the pressure of work _ four in
Alaska, one off the mid-Atlantic states and two off California, the
department's Minerals Management Service said Monday.
</TEXT>
