<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Grandmother'sWalk     04-11 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grandmother's Walk,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ohio Grandmother Completes 500-Mile Hike For Abused Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Ohio grandmother hiking to awaken the
American people to the plight of abused and neglected children
completed her 500-mile, three-week trek Monday in the nation's
capital.
   Wearing shorts, a T-shirt and jogging shoes, a smiling Mary
Helen Wallace of suburban Cincinnati strode briskly up to the foot
of the U.S. Capitol, triggering cheers from supporters who had
gathered to welcome her.
   ``Let me catch my breath, everybody,'' Ms. Wallace said. ``It
was hard. It was full of blisters and joint pain and back pain and
sunburn and windburn and cars trying to run me down...''
   However, Ms. Wallace, spokeswoman for a group called Rights of
Our Children, said she does not regret making the journey.
   ``I have made this walk to awaken the American people,'' she
said. ``If everyone will just look and see the pain and the
destruction that's happening to America's children, they will
search their hearts and do something about it.''
   Ms. Wallace refused to disclose her age, but said she has a
10-year-old grandson. She left Cincinnati on March 21 and hiked
through Ohio, West Virginia and Virginia before reaching Washington.
   She said she has been ``powerwalking'' for about four years and
averaged about 23 miles a day during her trip.
   ``I'm so exhausted that I don't sleep,'' she said. ``I get about
four hours' of sleep a night.''
   Betty Kuehner, of Cincinnati, followed Ms. Wallace in a car
during the first part of the journey and maintained contact with
her throughout the trip.
   She said Ms. Wallace stayed overnight in the homes or campers of
friends and that there were a few ``campout situations.'' Ms.
Kuehner said her friend walked virtually the entire way, taking
rides only for a few miles on stretches of dangerous highway.
   Ms. Wallace said the most frightening part of the trip occurred
in West Virginia when she was forced to hug the side of a mountain
to avoid being struck by a semitrailer carrying a wide-load cargo.
   ``I dug my toes literally into the side of the culvert against
the stone ... and prayed,'' Ms. Wallace recalled. ``I felt the whiz
of it go across my back.''
   She said she was disappointed she was not able to meet with
President Reagan but that she hopes her walk will spawn legislation
to better protect children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
