<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--ShipwreckSale     04-11 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Shipwreck Sale,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auction Set for Shipwreck Treasure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bounty from two shipwrecks discovered by
treasure hunter Mel Fisher, including a 5{-foot-long solid gold
chain, will be sold in June, Christie's auction house said Monday.
   The gold, silver and emeralds from the sunken, 17th century
Spanish galleons Nuestra Senora de Atocha and Santa Margarita were
uncovered west of the Florida Keys in a 17-year treasure hunt.
Fisher's team salvaged more than 300,000 pieces of cargo and
wreckage, including 57 tons of gold and silver.
   The gold chain has a presale estimate of $200,000 to $250,000.
Also being auctioned June 14 are a coral and gold rosary estimated
at $250,000, a silver-gilt wine cup, $150,000 to $250,000, and a
silver-gilt rose water dish, $80,000 to $120,000. There also are
four astrolabes, rare navigational instruments used by 17th century
mariners, estimated at $50,000 to $80,000 apiece.
   Fisher's company, Treasure Salvors Inc., was liquidated so the
proceeds can be divided among its stockholders.
</TEXT>
