<DOCNO> AP880411-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1452EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Longshore-AFL-CIO     04-11 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Longshore-AFL-CIO,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ILWU Considering Affiliation With AFL-CIO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After nearly 40 years on their own, members of
the International Longshoremen's and Warehousemen's Union will vote
this week on whether to join the AFL-CIO.
   About 350 delegates of the West Coast dockworkers' union will
vote at the ILWU international convention in Vancouver, British
Columbia, on the possible affiliation.
   In the late 1940s, the ILWU was tossed out of the Committee for
Industrial Organizations, a forerunner of the CIO, for alleged
communist domination. The CIO merged with the AFL in 1955.
   ``I think it's going to pass without any problems,'' said John
Bukoskey, the international's representative for Washington, Oregon
and Alaska. ``But I think there will also be quite a bit of debate.
After all, we were asked to leave.''
   He said that rejoining the federation would improve the ILWU's
bargaining power and its ability to lobby for national legislation.
   ILWU President Jimmy Herman and AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland
have agreed in principle to the reaffiliation, said Danny Beagle,
spokesman for the San Francisco-based ILWU.
   The 24,000-member union was formed in 1937 when it broke with
the New York-based International Longshoremen's Association. Harry
Bridges led the ILWU from 1934 until 1977.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
