<DOCNO> AP880411-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1456EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Budget     04-11 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Budget,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Shows Support for Budget Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate showed support Monday for a $1.1
trillion fiscal 1989 budget built to comply with deficit-reduction
promises while increasing spending for the AIDS fight, the space
program and education.
   The spending plan cleared an initial parliamentary hurdle 83-0,
and debate began at the earliest date in years. Although the law
allows 50 hours of debate time, a final vote was considered
possible by Tuesday.
   The smoothness of the process didn't stop an undercurrent of
concern and frustration that the election-year plan wasn't doing
enough about the deficit.
   ``We're running just a few steps in front of the avalanche of
death,'' said Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., chairman of the Senate
Budget Committee. But given current political constraints, he said,
the best the Congress could do was ``make sure that next year's
burden grows no larger.''
   The estimated deficit of $136 billion would meet the mandate of
the Gramm-Rudman budget-balancing law. But it represents only a
modest reduction in red ink from the $146.7 billion predicted for
the current fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30.
   Congress will have to ``do much better in the years to come,''
said Chiles, who is retiring after this year.
   Chiles and Sen. Pete V. Domenici of New Mexico, the budget
committee's senior Republican, drafted the budget in compliance
with last fall's deficit agreement between congressional leaders
and President Reagan.
   The pact set overall spending guidelines and took away what is
usually the biggest point of contention _ the balance between
domestic and military spending.
   Under the agreement, the Senate budget proposes for the Pentagon
to spend $294.0 billion next year. Domestic agencies would spend
$169.2 billion, while foreign aid would total $16.1 billion.
   The agreement also pre-determined that no new taxes would be
included in the budget plan, beyond the $14 billion in new taxes
enacted last December.
   The Senate, as the House did in adopting its budget last month,
was using the administration's optimistic assumptions about the
nation's economy. The non-partisan Congressional Budget Office
predicts a deficit some $35 billion above the Gramm-Rudman target.
   Within the overall guidelines of last fall's agreement, the
Senate proposal re-arranges some domestic priorities that Reagan
proposed when he submitted his budget in February.
   While many domestic agencies will face belt-tightening to absorb
inflationary costs, the budget rejects the president's call for
eliminating several domestic development and mass-transit programs.
   It also rejects his request for tightening up in the Medicare
system. The deficit-reduction agreement did not cover Social
Security or most other benefit programs and none of this year's
budget plans has envisioned cuts in those areas.
   The House and Senate budgets, like Reagan's proposal, call for
big spending increases on the space program, research on AIDS,
education and air traffic safety.
   The Senate plan also endorses Reagan's plan to give a 4.3
percent pay hike to the military and only 2 percent for civilian
federal workers. The House voted a 3 percent across-the-board raise.
   The Senate and House must settle on a single budget resolution
before it becomes final. The budget resolution is a guideline for
Congress' fiscal legislation, and it does not require the
president's signature.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
