<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gore     04-11 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Against Palestinian State, But Sees Possibility of Autonomy
Tryout</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. said Monday that he is not
in favor of a Palestinian state but that some sort of temporary
autonomy could be tested on the West Bank.
   ``I support the Camp David formula, which points us toward a
period of limited autonomy, during which Israel and the
Palestinians would be able to judge what autonomy is like in
practice,'' Gore said. ``Now the exact formula must be arrived at
by the parties themselves.''
   Those parties include Israel, Jordan, the Palestinians ``and
perhaps Syria,'' Gore told reporters during a question-and-answer
session in the board room at the New York Stock Exchange.
   Whatever happens, Gore said, ``it's unthinkable to have an
armed, military, hostile presence so close'' to Israel's borders.
   ``I think that the eventual formula has to involve assurances
that Israel's security will not incur an additional threat,'' said
the Democratic presidential aspirant from Tennessee.
   Gore was in town campaigning for the delegate-rich April 19 New
York primary. Two hundred fifty-five delegates are at stake for the
three remaining Democrats: Gore, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
and Jesse Jackson. Gore is far behind the other two in the delegate
count.
   Before talking to reporters, Gore addressed leaders from the
securities industry in the stock exchange board room.
   During a wide-ranging session with reporters later, Gore said
that he was glad Jackson seemed to distance himself from the
Palestine Liberation Organization and that he always thought Gov.
Mario Cuomo was not a candidate for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
   On Sunday, Jackson said that if he were elected president he
would not meet with PLO leader Yasser Arafat. Gore had criticized
Jackson for being too close to the PLO, and was asked by reporters
Monday if he took credit for what he termed ``a very useful
statement'' from Jackson.
   ``No, I'm not taking credit for that. He deserves credit for
it,'' Gore said. ``But by raising the issues openly instead of just
behind the scenes I think it makes it a healthy process and creates
opportunities for questions and answers that break new ground.''
   The Tennessee senator added that ``I think that one of the
purposes that can be served by drawing contrasts in a primary
campaign is by making it possible for candidates to more clearly
... elaborate their positions. I know I have grown during this
campaign. I know the other candidates have.''
   Also during the weekend, Cuomo said the correct interpretation
of statements he has made is that he wouldn't accept a nomination
draft if one were offered at the Democratic convention next July.
   ``He has encouraged people to look favorably at all the active
candidates,'' Gore said. ``I never thought he was a candidate
because he told me he wasn't a candidate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
