<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TurtleDredging     04-11 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turtle Dredging,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Endangered Sea Turtles Get Special Treatment Off Cape Canaveral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the need to keep the entrance
channel to Cape Canaveral free for submarine passage, the federal
government is taking the slow route in dredging the waterway in
order to protect endangered sea turtles.
   Federal officials have hired a team of University of Florida
zoologists to study turtle populations at different times of the
year to guide future channel dredging, said Karen Bjorndal,
director of the Archie Carr Center for Sea Turtle Research at the
university.
   The U.S. National Marine Fisheries Service told the Army Corps
of Engineers to use only the safest dredging method to avoid
harming the turtles, she said.
   The Corps would like to use hopper dredging, which sucks up
sediment with a tremendous hydraulic force, Ms. Bjorndal said
Monday.
   ``The problem is that the sea turtles get sucked up too and torn
into pieces,'' she said.
   The alternative is clam-shell dredging, in which a large bucket
slowly scoops up sediment.
   ``While our work is basic research, it has a great effect on
potential management and conservation decisions,'' said Alan
Bolten, one of the researchers who catch, tag, measure and
determine the species and sex of each turtle. The turtles are
returned to the water within 30 minutes of their capture.
   ``A two-day study doesn't give you enough information because of
the dynamics of sea turtle distribution,'' Bolten said. ``A number
of years of data need to be collected for a bigger picture.''
   The team did one survey of the channel last month and plans
return trips in May and September.
</TEXT>
