<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Reed     04-11 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Reed,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Movie Critic Rex Reed Pleads Guilty To Attempted State Income Tax
Evasion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Movie critic Rex Reed pleaded guilty Monday
to two counts of attempting to evade the state's income tax in a
dispute he blamed on faulty advice from an accountant.
   Appearing in City Police Court, Reed, 49, entered a guilty plea
on the two misdemeanor counts that stemmed from his failing to file
state returns in 1984 and 1985 while he was a columnist for the New
York Post.
   He was fined $2,000 and must pay $50 in court costs.
   Reed had already paid approximately $20,000 in delinquent taxes,
penalties and interest to the state Department of Taxation and
Finance.
   ``It's ironic that this would happen on Academy Awards day,'' he
said afterward, adding that he would miss attending the ceremony in
person because he couldn't get a flight to Los Angeles from Albany
in time, and would have to settle for watching it on television.
   ``I'll miss Cher's navel,'' he quipped.
   The Tax Department found that the Post paid Reed as an
independent contractor for 1984 and 1985, ``therefore he was
earning income from a New York state employer, but had not filed
the New York state returns,'' said Nancy Connell, a spokeswoman for
the state attorney general's office.
   Reed said he could have avoided the $2,000 fine if he were to
prove that he was a Connecticut resident during 1984 and 1985, but
he didn't want to face the prolonged legal battle. Reed said it was
easier for him to ``give them their pound of flesh for two thousand
bucks.''
   Tax officials said Reed's primary address was New York City.
   Reed, who currently appears on the television show ``At The
Movies,'' worked as a columnist for the Post from 1982 until last
year. He was also a columnist for the Daily News for 12 years
before writing for the Post.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
