<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1510EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan 3rdLd-Writethru a0612 04-11 0858</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0612,850</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 7-10, Shultz told reporters, to include Shultz
comments.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, hailing the ``valiant
struggle of the Afghan people,'' announced today that he will send
Secretary of State George Shultz to Geneva to sign the accord
ending the Soviet occupation of Afghanistan.
   ``I believe the United States can now join the Soviet Union as a
guarantor of the Geneva instruments,'' Reagan said of the accord,
which opens the way for the pullout of the 115,000-man Red Army and
a return of millions of Afghan refugees to Afghanistan.
   Reagan said the proposed pact ``would provide for the complete
withdrawal of Soviet occupation forces from that country.''
   Shultz is to represent the United States at the signing
ceremony, which is expected to be held Thursday.
   ``This development would not have been possible had it not been
for the valiant struggle of the Afghan people to rid their country
of foreign occupation,'' Reagan said, adding, ``We take great pride
in having assisted the Afghan people in this triumph and they can
count on our continued support.''
   Reagan also lauded Pakistan for its role as a home to millions
of Afghan refugees during the period of Soviet domination of
Afghanistan.
   Shultz told reporters after Reagan's announcement that beginning
May 15, the Soviet Union is to begin withdrawing its 115,000 troops
from Afghanistan, with 50 percent of the forces removed over a
three-month period. All remaining Soviet forces are to be out by
Feb. 15, 1989.
   He said Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze has promised
to complete the withdrawal by the end of the year, ahead of the
deadline. He said the United States will ``push for that and expect
that.''
   While hailing the agreement, Shultz said, ``The withdrawal of
Soviet troops is obviously not the end of the matter.''
Negotiations will continue for the establishment of an interim
government. ``We know it's not easy, it will be hard,'' Shultz said.
   Underscoring Reagan's pledge of continued aid for the
U.S.-backed rebels, Shultz said, ``We have stood by the Afghan
people during this 8{ years and we're prepared to stand by them in
the coming months to help Afghans return home and begin rebuild
their lives and their country.''
   Shultz's Geneva trip gives him another chance to meet with
Shevardnadze before talks in Moscow next week to continue
preparations for the superpower summit meeting in the Soviet
capital beginning May 29.
   Prior to the announcement, Shultz reported to Reagan on his
Middle East talks last week with Arab and Israeli leaders, which
failed to produce a breakthrough to negotiations. But Shultz vowed
to find the time to return and to continue his effort.
   Setting the tone for the coming summit in Moscow with Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev, Reagan said Sunday he looks forward to
the signing of an agreement providing for the withdrawal of Red
Army forces from Afghanistan.
   ``If that accord is complied with, and Soviets withdraw
irrevocably from that long-suffering country, this will be a great
victory for its heroic people,'' he said at a broadcasters'
convention in Las Vegas, Nev. ``It will also be a major
contribution to the improvement of East-West relations.''
   However, Reagan said the Russian economy remains in trouble and
he doesn't know how the Soviet Union will be able to compete in a
changing world marked by new technologies.
   `` ...Nations will have to grant to their scientists complete
freedom of inquiry; to their businessmen and entrepreneurs, freedom
to invest, to risk, to create new products and with them new
markets,'' Reagan said.
   ``The Soviets and their clients must open their countries to
ever-wider freedoms. Or they will see their economies _ indeed
their whole way of life _ fall further behind,'' he said.
   Reagan made only a passing reference to the agreement reached in
Geneva for the pullout of the Soviets' 115,000 troops from
Afghanistan.
   ``We're very optimistic, but nothing has been signed yet,''
Reagan told reporters.
   The agreement is to be signed Thursday.
   The president's top aides continued planning for the Moscow
summit while Reagan and his wife, Nancy, vacationed the past 10
days at their mountaintop ranch near Santa Barbara, Calif. They
returned to Washington on Sunday.
   The May 29-June 2 summit with Gorbachev is seen by many as the
likely capstone to the Reagan presidency, with Reagan spending much
of the rest of the year on the 1988 political campaign trail.
   Reagan noted that the summit will come almost a year after he
flew to West Berlin to demand that the Soviets destroy the Berlin
Wall.
   ``As I challenged him in Berlin before the Washington
(superpower) summit, I challenge Mr. Gorbachev here today, before
the summit in Moscow, to tear down this other wall, this grim,
invisible wall of oppression,'' he said.
   Reagan said that while headway has been made on emigration,
people-to-people exchanges between Americans and Russians and his
own access to Soviet television, much more needs to be done.
   Reagan also called on Gorbachev to work for more openness in the
Soviet Union and the Warsaw Pact countries for Western authors,
journalists and broadcasters.
</TEXT>
