<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1520EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Afghan     04-11 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghan,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Condemns Guerrilla Attack on Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet television on Monday condemned Afghan
guerrillas for shooting down a Soviet-built passenger jet with 29
people aboard after announcements that a negotiated end to the
10-year-old Afghan war is near.
   The national news program ``Vremya'' showed wreckage strewn over
a valley near the Afghan city of Maimaneh, about 90 miles south of
the Soviet border.
   A Tass news agency commentary blamed the attack on the leaders
of the ``Peshawar Seven,'' the main guerrilla organization based in
Pakistan. It accused the leaders of prolonging the bloodshed at a
time when Afghans were inspired by recent news from Geneva that the
fighting will cease and 115,000 Soviet soldiers will go home.
   An Afghan air force colonel told Soviet TV that a U.S. Stinger
missile had been used to down the plane carrying both government
soldiers and civilians.
   ``This act is especially cynical because it was committed when
all Afghan people were inspired by the joint Soviet-Afghan
statement by Mikhail Gorbachev and Najib,'' said the colonel,
identified only as Zahir, referring to Thursday's announcement by
the Soviet and Afghan leaders that all obstacles had been removed
to the signing of a peace accord.
   Tass said guerrilla alliance leader Gulbuddin Hekmeyar vowed to
carry on the armed fight, and that the insurgents had ``already
shot down several civilian planes and the number of those killed
amounted to almost 200.'' It was not clear over how long a period
of time the casualties were inflicted.
   ``The leaders of the insurgents are unwilling to listen to the
voice of reason and to join the settlement process,'' Tass said,
referring to Najib's call for insurgents to lay down their arms and
join his government.
   Pakistan and Afghanistan have announced agreement on a package
of measures to end the war in Afghanistan between Najib's army,
backed by about 115,000 Soviet soldiers, and guerrilla forces based
in Pakistan and armed primarily by the United States.
   The negotiated peace plan is to be signed on Thursday in Geneva,
where indirect talks moderated by U.N. representative Diego
Cordovez have been under way since 1983.
   Under the Geneva plan, Soviet troops will begin leaving
Afghanistan on May 15 and at least half will be out within three
months. The remainder would be obligated to leave Afghanistan
within 10 months of the start of the pullout, but Soviet officials
have indicated they plan to have their soldiers home by the end of
this year.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979.
   The United States and the Soviet Union are expected to act as
guarantors of the Geneva agreement under a plan worked out behind
the scenes that would ensure ``symmetry'' in continued aid to the
warring sides.
   Afghan negotiators had insisted on an end to U.S. weapons
deliveries to the guerrillas once the Soviet pullout began, but
American observers at the Geneva talks refused to abide by it
unless the Kremlin stopped arming Najib's troops.
   Soviet officials deemed the U.S. demand an infringement of its
right to enter into bilateral agreements with a sovereign neighbor
and initially refused the ``symmetry'' plan.
   But diplomatic and official sources have reported in recent days
that Moscow and Washington have worked out an agreement ensuring a
balance in aid or a moratorium on arms shipments to the warring
sides.
   Earlier Monday, Tass reported that insurgents attacked Maimaneh,
killing 13 people and causing serious damage.
</TEXT>
