<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says ``I'm a Good Friend of Israel''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THORNWOOD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush suggested
Monday that American Jews should vote for him rather than a
Democrat because ``I'm a good friend of Israel.''
   Bush made the comment as he spoke to reporters during a tour of
an IBM office here during a day of low-key campaigning.
   The vice president, now running virtually unopposed for the
Republican presidential nomination, was asked to comment on remarks
by New York Mayor Edward Koch that New York Jews should not vote
for Democrat Jesse Jackson in the state's April 19 primary.
   ``Listen, we've got enough problems on our own side to get into
the Democratic nominating process,'' Bush said.
   ``Ed Koch is entitled to his opinion. Each candidate is entitled
to run on his own record. There is no point in my fine-tuning Ed
Koch's comments,'' Bush said.
   He said Jews should consider voting for him. ``I think everyone
shold vote for me. Besides that, I'm a good friend of Israel.''
   Bush toured an IBM high-tech training center here, was shown how
computers can be used in designing and manufacturing products, and
spoke to a group of IBM employes.
   IBM officials said that Bush had requested the tour. In his
speech to employees, Bush talked of the importance of training and
education in keeping U.S. industry competitive _ one of his
favorite campaign themes.
   Earlier in the day, he told a noon crowd in a shopping mall in
nearby White Plains that he was ready to face whichever candidate
Democrats select to oppose him.
   ``We don't have all the excitement that exists on the Democratic
side of the aisle, but we have a lot more unity and fewer
problems,'' he said.
   Bush was also to attend a fund-raiser in Greenwich, Conn., and
to spend the night in Schenectady, N.Y., on the first leg of his
three-day campaign swing.
</TEXT>
