<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Blasts     04-11 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Blasts,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Disposal Experts Begin Clearing Projectiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCHEHEREZADE FARAMARZI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Pakistani bomb disposal
experts Monday began defusing thousands of deadly missiles and
grenades strewn around the capital after an explosion at an
ammunition dump killed 93 people and injured 1,100.
   Security forces and rescue teams also searched flattened
buildings for hundreds of people still unaccounted for after
Sunday's blast.
   President Mohammad Zia Ul-haq, who cut short a visit to Kuwait,
called the explosion an ``extraordinary accident.''
   Zia refused to speculate on the cause of the fire which ignited
the ammunition dump explosion at Ojeri camp between the twin cities
of Islamabad and Rawalpindi.
   Commenting on reports that some of the ordnance was earmarked
for Moslem guerrillas in Afghanistan and that some empty casings
bore Chinese labels, Zia said: ``It's nothing but speculation _ a
high measure of speculation.''
   Witnesses saw burning trucks Sunday near the depot bearing
Afghan license plates. Pakistan is a conduit for foreign military
supplies and other aid to the Afghan insurgents fighting the
communist government in Kabul backed by an estimated 115,000 Soviet
troops.
   Zia, who disclosed the number of dead and injured, received
messages of sympathy from various heads of state, including a
message from Afghan President Najib.
   ``I wish to convey our deepest condolences to the families who
suffered from this tragic incident and to all people of the
republic of Pakistan,'' Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad, quoted
Najib's message as saying.
   Streets in the two cities were littered with an estimated 6,500
unexploded anti-tank mortars, rockets, rocket-propelled grenades
and other devices.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Kent Obee said the embassy had offered
the Pakistani government help in finding and clearing the weapons.
   A four-man American explosives expert team arrived Sunday night
from the U.S. Task Force in northern Arabian Sea.
   Obee said the team would also clear ammunition that fell in 10
to 12 residences of U.S. Embassy employees. There were no injuries
or major damage, he added.
   He said the team began its work Monday and will continue as long
as needed. He stressed that the Americans would not investigate the
blast.
   Zia said seven Pakistani soldiers were killed and 32 injured in
the explosion. On Monday, he toured the areas around the blast site
and visited hospitals to talk with the wounded.
   Police and army patrolled the streets and some people began
repairing their houses.
   Pakistan radio and neighborhood mosques appealed for missing
people.
   Prime Minister Mohammad Khan Junejo said the injured and the
families of the bereaved will be compensated and ordered an enquiry
into the cause of the explosion.
   He also said all ammunition depots situated within populated
areas will be shifted to safer and isolated places.
   Some Western embassies said they received anonymous telephone
calls warning of a terrorist bombing shortly before the depot blew
up at about 10 a.m.
   Obee said the U.S. Embassy did not receive such a call.
   Shortly before the explosion, a small group of Moslem
fundamentalists were preparing to march toward the U.S. Embassy to
protest against Israeli action against the Palestinian uprising in
the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   In India, two people were killed and at least 100 others injured
Monday when police clashed with mobs of students who tried to close
shops in northern Kashmir state to show sympathy for the victims of
the weekend explosion.
   The United News of India reported that the injured included 70
policemen.
   India and Pakistan have fought three wars, two of them over
Kashmir. Some of the Moslems, who predominate in Kashmir state,
want to unite with Pakistan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
