<DOCNO> AP880411-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1602EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WorldCourt     04-11 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Court,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Court Hears Flap Over PLO's New York Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American judge on the
International Court of Justice said Monday the United Nations
should step aside in its dispute with the Reagan administration
over the PLO's U.N. office in New York.
   A U.N. official argued before the world court that the United
States is ducking its international responsibility by trying to
close the PLO mission.
   The diplomatic tug-of-war stems from anti-terrorist legislation
signed by President Reagan in December. The law classifies the
Palestine Liberation Organization as a terrorist group and bars it
from operating on U.S. territory.
   U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese III has tried to use the law
to close the 14-year-old mission with U.N. observer status.
   In Monday's 90-minute session of the world court, American Judge
Stephen M. Schwebel challenged a U.N. claim that the Reagan
administration moves constitute an immediate threat to the PLO's
presence in New York.
   He said the United States has said it would wait for a ruling
from a U.S. District judge in New York, and he said the United
Nations should do the same. The U.S. Justice Deparment has asked
the judge to rule in favor of the closure in a case initially
brought by the PLO.
   The United Nations has asked the world court to issue an opinion
against such a closure, which has been denounced by all U.N.
members but Israel and the United States. The United Nations says
the dispute should be arbitrated by a special, three-member panel.
   The world court, the U.N.'s judicial arm, lacks legal powers to
enforce its decisions and can only issue advisory opinions.
   U.N. Undersecretary-General Carl-August Fleischhauer of West
Germany said Monday that the American move to close the PLO office
violates a 1947 agreement between the international organization
and the Truman administration.
   The United Nations says that accord, which guarantees the
unimpeded functioning of diplomats accredited to U.N. headquarters,
also applies to missions with observer status.
   The PLO was granted permanent observer status at the United
Nations in 1974 and has maintained an office near U.N. headquarters
in Manhattan ever since.
   In a brief released by the court Monday, the United Nations
stated ``the question at issue goes far beyond the particular
dispute and has far-reaching consequences for the ... discharge of
the responsibilities of the United Nations in the world at large.''
   The court asked Fleischhauer, the U.N.'s undersecretary-general
for legal affairs, to respond in writing to its queries later this
week. Fleischhauer told reporters Monday he expected a decision by
the end of May.
   There were no representatives of either the Reagan
administration or the PLO at the world court on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880411-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1603EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Airlines-Smoking     04-11 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airlines-Smoking,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Smoking Ban Covers Any Flight Over Two Hours</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The airline smoking ban that goes into effect
April 23 on commercial aircraft will apply to any flight scheduled
for two hours or less even if delays cause the flight to take
longer, the Federal Aviation Administration said Monday.
   Congress required the smoking ban on short flights in
legislation last year. The FAA issued its final rules on the
prohibition Monday, although the general outline of the new
restrictions has been known for months.
   Airlines since the first of the year have complied with a state
law in California and banned smoking on flights within the state.
   The law enacted by Congress last year prohibits smoking on any
flight of two hours or less on jet aircraft as well as smaller
commuter planes. Charter flights and those involving travel clubs
are exempt from the rules.
   The FAA, clarifying details of the restrictions, said Monday
that the length of the flight shall be determined by the elapsed
time shown for the flight in the Official Airline Guide. Should a
flight be delayed so it takes longer than two hours, the ban still
is in effect, the FAA said.
   The ban also will apply to each segment of a flight. For example
a flight that has three legs of 90 minutes, 90 minutes and 2{ hours
would require that smoking be prohibited in the first two segments
and allowed in the final segment, according to the FAA.
   According to the rules, flight attendants must remind passengers
of the smoking ban during pre-flight briefings.
   A passenger who violates the ban would face a civil fine of up
to $1,000 per offense. Any passenger who tampers with a smoke
detector in an aircraft lavatory and tries to smoke could face a
fine of up to $2,000.
</TEXT>
