<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GlobalForum     04-11 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Global Forum,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conference Opens, Archbishop Warns About Environmental Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie
told a gathering of the world's religious leaders and lawmakers on
Monday that environmental and political problems have imperiled the
Earth.
   ``We are confronted by problems which transcend national and
credal boundaries, which are urgent and potentially terminal, and
which require not less than a global solution,'' the archbishop
told the conference, which is debating global problems.
   ``We live in a world society which desperately seeks some
measure of world community in order to survive,'' said Runcie, the
spiritual head of the state Church of England and leader of 70
million Anglicans worldwide.
   In an apparent reference to the plight of hostages in the
hijacked Kuwaiti airliner in Cyprus, Runcie said one crisis that
had to be solved was the ``terrorism which fouls and feeds on
global communciation.''
   Runcie took part in the opening of the five-day Global
Conference of Spiritual and Parliamentary Leaders on Human Survival.
   Earlier Monday, the organizers said China pulled out of the
meeting, expressing displeasure at the attendance of the Dalai
Lama, the spiritual and temporal leader of Tibetan Buddhism.
   The conference is a gathering of the leaders of the world's
major religions and elected lawmakers and is aimed at putting their
influence to work on solving dilemmas such as over-population and
poverty.
   In a message of good wishes to the conference, Indian's Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi said, ``Those who guide the destinies of
spiritual affairs and those who forge the destinies of nations must
share the same vision for the betterment of humanity.''
   About the pulling out of the Chinese, the Very Rev. James Parks
Morton, a co-chairman of the conference, said: ``We worked hard to
get the Chinese here because we are discussing issues of great
concern to them, like population growth.''
   Morton, dean of the Episcopal Cathedral of St. John the Divine
in New York City, said the leaders of the world's most populous
nation had earlier shown a willingness to attend the conference.
   ``But although we had no formal complaint from the Chinese
government about the attendance of the Dalai Lama, we did get a
letter from one of their bigwigs saying they were not coming
because he was here,'' Morton said.
   The Dalai Lama fled to exile in India in 1959 after China
invaded his country and has criticized China's policies in Tibet.
   The Dalai Lama is one of a dozen main speakers at the
conference. On Tuesday he will address the conference on the
universal human condition. He will not attend other sessions of the
gathering, which ends Friday.
   About 200 people from 60 countries in East and West, including
the Communist bloc, are attending the conference, with the five
main religions of Buddhism, Christianity, Hinduism, Islam and
Judaism strongly represented.
   The meeting, apparently the first such religious-political
gathering, will discuss how the participants will work together to
influence crucial issues, which also include terrorism, urban
violence, pollution, conservation and education.
</TEXT>
