<DOCNO> AP880411-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1600EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WesternDrought Bjt   04-11 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Western Drought, Bjt,0761</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Low Water Pits Farmers, Utilities Against Fishermen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. CRUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers, utilities and fish and game
officials will be fighting over limited water supplies this summer
as a major drought parches the West.
   ``That's the big concern, the juggling act with water,'' said
Mick Jennings, a fish biologist for the Oregon Department of Fish
and Wildlife in Central Point. ``There are so many interests in
water, what might be best for one interest may not be best for
another interest.''
   The Bonneville Power Administration quit selling power to
California last fall to make up for a drop in electricity produced
by hydroelectric dams on the Columbia River system.
   But the big victims of the drought will be farmers, ranchers and
fish, said Wally Gibson of the Northwest Power Planning Council.
``The problem is severe on the fish and irrigation side, not the
power side.''
   In California, San Joaquin County already has declared a drought
after noting snowpack and reservoir levels were approaching the
lows that preceded the drought of 1976-77.
   ``We've had a critical premature die-off of range land, and lots
of water districts are cutting back on farm water allotments,''
said Ron Baldwin, coordinator of the San Joaquin County Office of
Emergency Services.
   The snowpack in California averages 35 percent of normal,
forcing some ranchers to sell cattle and appeal for federal grain
subsidies as pastures dry up.
   ``It's scary. It's really scary,'' said Billy Marr, head of the
Tuolumne County Water System, in the Sierra Nevada, which is
considering rationing.
   The West isn't alone. In the Southeast, Georgia, Alabama and
South Carolina are facing their fourth serious drought in eight
years, with some reservoirs at lower levels than they were at this
point in the drought years of 1981, 1986 and 1987, officials said
earlier this month.
   ``If we don't get a dramatic increase in rainfall, we'll be
looking at water restrictions this summer,'' said David Word, chief
of water resource management for the Georgia Department of Natural
Resources.
   In Oregon, snowpack and rainfall figures range from near-normal
in the northwestern part of the state to 36 percent of normal in
the south.
   Ranchers in southeastern Oregon are trucking water to their
cattle as water holes dry up, said Jay Carr, an Oregon State
University Extension agent in Lakeview.
   Irrigation water will be in short supply for orchards, hopyards,
vineyards and livestock around Yakima, Wash., on the drier eastern
slopes of the Cascades.
   In Seattle, however, unusually heavy rain and snow in March
relieved fears of a second year of rationing. Reservoirs are up to
94 percent of normal.
   The outlook is grim in the region's forests, which were heavily
scarred by fires last summer.
   Southern Oregon's Siskiyou National Forest, where 110,000 acres
burned, already has started its fire season.
   ``Drought conditions don't guarantee a bad season,'' said Tim
Keith, who oversees southwest Oregon for the state Department of
Forestry. ``But they certainly elevate the potential.''
   Timber companies worked feverishly over the winter and spring to
stockpile logs.
   ``Companies are concerned that we'll have another serious fire
season and they'll be locked out of the woods again,'' said Ron
Johnson, timber staff coordinator for the U.S. Forest Service
regional office in Portland. Last summer, officials limited logging
in high danger areas of Oregon.
   The Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife is particularly
worried about a disease called furunculosis killing off thousands
of chinook salmon on their spawning run up southern Oregon's Rogue
River.
   Low flows mean warmer water, which promote the growth of the
bacteria, said Jennings. Low water also makes it tougher for fish
to swim up rapids and falls, bottling them up in crowded pools
where the bacteria is more readily spread.
   Starting Friday, the Corps is to flush immense volumes of water
down the Columbia and Snake rivers to help young salmon smolts
migrate to the ocean. It also plans to use trucks and barges to
carry many smolts around dams, where they can be killed by
hydroelectric turbines or spillway torrents.
   The Northwest Power Planning Council is facing the prospect of
less hydroelectricity from the dams on the Columbia.
   ``If we have to buy hydropower from Canada or if we have to fire
up the coal plants in Oregon, which are far more expensive than our
hydropower, we are likely to see some rate increases,'' said
council spokeswoman Dulcy Mahar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
