<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Ambassadors     04-11 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Ambassadors,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Names Cutler To Second Term as Saudi Ambassador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House formally announced on Monday
that President Reagan intends to return Walter Leon Cutler to the
post of U.S. Ambassador to Saudi Arabia.
   If he is confirmed, it will be Cutler's second term as
ambassador. Cutler, who had served as the U.S. representative in
Riyadh from 1984 to 1987, will replace Hume Horan in the position.
   Earlier this month, State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley
announced Horan was being reassigned after only six months on the
job.
   At that time, a State Department official who spoke on condition
of anonymity said Horan had a ``personality conflict'' with King
Fahd.
   Saudi and American officials denied a report that the Saudi
government had asked Horan be replaced. A U.S. official also denied
that Horan's reassignment was related to a U.S.-Saudi dispute over
that country's acquisition of missiles from China.
   In separate announcements, the White House said Reagan intends
to nominate Paul Taylor as ambassador to the Dominican Republic.
   Taylor, who has been deputy assistant secretary of state for
inter-American affairs since 1985, would succeed Lowell Kilday, the
White House said.
   Reagan also intends to nominate Rush Walker Taylor Jr. to be
ambassador to the Republic of Togo. Taylor, who has been serving as
the temporary charge d-Affaires in Guinea-Bissau since 1986, will
succeed David Korn, the White House said.
</TEXT>
