<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChildCare     04-11 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Care,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Advocates Push Universal Child Care In Mass.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ambitious plan to make Massachusetts the first
state to guarantee affordable child care for every child under 14
was unveiled Monday, although its sponsor said he didn't know how
it would be funded.
   ``We are in the midst of a child-care crisis,'' said state Rep.
David B. Cohen, co-chairman of a special child-care commission.
``It is a crisis which affects our children, our families and our
economy.''
   Cohen, chief sponsor of the bill to create a cabinet-level
Executive Office of Child Care to oversee and expand current
child-care services, said three out of five Massachusetts children
need child care because both their parents work or they have a
single parent who works.
   Currently, the state is providing services to about 80,000
children at an annual cost of $110 million, primarily through
subsidies to the poor, he said.
   But Cohen said conservative estimates point to another 80,000
children whose families cannot find child-care services and 80,000
more whose parents can't find services at a price they can afford.
   ``This crisis will only grow in the future,'' Cohen, joined by
other child care advocates, told a statehouse news conference.
   Cohen's bill doesn't say exactly how or when the state will meet
these needs.
   The measure would create a 21-member, gubernatorially appointed
advisory commission to counsel the child care secretary on how to
accomplish the mandate.
   He said the proposal could double or triple current state
spending on child-care programs, but added, ``The only thing that
will be more expensive is not providing universal child care.
Without it, we may find that our economic boom will go bust.''
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis' administration has taken no position on
the proposal, which now goes before the Legislature's Human
Services Committee.
   Asked what the administration's initial reaction was, Cohen
said, ``Well, they broke out in a rash.'' But he said the
administration hasn't dismissed the idea.
</TEXT>
