<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SuspectEscape     04-11 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Suspect Escape,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Hunt Escaped Murder Suspect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police searched Monday for a murder
suspect who drove off in a prisoner transport van after his guards
went into a convenience store and left the keys in the ignition.
   Richard Lacy Letner Jr., charged in the torture-murder of nurse
Ivon Pontbriant of Visalia, Calif., kicked out a passenger-door
window in the back of the van and drove away in handcuffs Sunday
afternoon, said San Antonio police spokeswoman Sandy Perez.
   Letner, 27, drove about a block before using the keys to unlock
his shackles and then fleeing on foot. The suspect, who was
captured in Iowa and was being returned to California, was one of
nine prisoners in the van.
   Interstate Extraditions of Bloomington, Ill., was transporting
the men across the country. The private firm uses former law
enforcement officers to ferry 3,000 prisoners a year.
   ``I would certainly consider him very dangerous in light of the
escape and because the information from the (murder) case alludes
to that,'' Visalia police Sgt. John Gomes said of Letner.
   Jim Kuczek, chief executive officer of Interstate Extraditions,
said the prisoner van was en route to Silver City, N.M., before
going on to California, but came to Texas to make four more
prisoner pickup stops in Beeville and Lubbock.
   He declined to say if the two guards, with more than 20 years
combined law enforcement experience between them, would be
disciplined.
   ``Our procedures indicate that one of the officers should be
with the vehicle at all times and that the keys should not be left
in the vehicle,'' Kuczek said. ``They (officers) were saying that
they were hot and needed air and the prisoners wanted the air
conditioner to be left on.
   ``Letner must have been quite an acrobat. We have never had an
escape like that,'' he added.
   Shortly after the guards went into the store, Letner kicked out
a rear window and managed to drive the van about a block. He then
used other keys on the ring to unlock his handcuffs and shackles,
before abandoning the van, authorities said.
   None of the other prisoners left the van.
   Helicopters and dogs were used to search for Letner on Sunday,
Perez said, and an all-points bulletin was issued with Letner's
description.
   Ms. Pontbriant's body was found March 2 in her apartment with a
telephone cord wrapped around her neck and several stab wounds,
authorities said.
   Earlier that morning, Letner and another suspect, Christopher
Tobin, 26, had been found in the woman's car, but officials did not
know about the killing, Gomes said.
   About 20 hours later, authorities learned about the slaying and
linked Letner and Tobin to the killing, Gomes said.
   The suspects were arrested March 29 in Council Bluffs, Iowa,
Gomes said.
   Two Visalia police officers went to Iowa to pickup the
prisoners, but because of restrictions allowing only one prisoner
per flight, only Tobin was returned to Visalia, Gomes said.
</TEXT>
