<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1711EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SwedenExibit     04-11 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden Exibit,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swedish Monarchs Preview Exhibit, Mark 350th Anniversary Of Colony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Carl Gustaf XIV and Queen Silvia of
Sweden posed Monday in front of an oil painting of their family as
they toured an exhibition of masterpieces from the Gripsholm Castle.
   The royal couple previewed the 60-piece exhibit at the National
Portrait Gallery in advance of the formal opening Wednesday. Their
family portrait, painted by John-Erik Franzen in 1985, is one of
the 4,000 works at Gripsholm Castle which is Sweden's national
portrait museum.
   The king and queen arrived in Washington on Sunday to
participate in events around the country marking the 350th
anniversary of the first Swedish colony in America. From here they
will travel Wednesday to Wilmington, Del., the site of the first
colony, which was subsequently captured by the Dutch and then the
British.
   The king toured the National Air and Space Museum, and the
monarchs hosted a reception at the Swedish ambassador's residence.
They also were scheduled to dine at the White House with President
Reagan and his wife Nancy.
   Reporters were given a preview of another exhibit marking the
350th anniversary, this one at the National Gallery. The royal
couple will be on hand for the formal opening on Tuesday of the
decorative art show ``Sweden: A Royal Treasury 1550-1700.''
   Among the exhibits are the Swedish crown jewels, a selection of
armor and weapons, the wedding costume of Gustavus Adolphus and the
elaborate velvet gown worn by 4-year-old Charles XI when he became
king.
   These are among 100 objects, never before shown in the United
States, which will be on display in the gallery's East Building
until Sept. 5. Then they will go to the Institute of Arts at
Minneapolis, Minn., where many immigrants from Sweden settled. They
will be on view there from Oct. 9 to Jan. 1, 1989..
   ``The baroque period in Sweden is largely unfamiliar to the
American public, and we expect this exhibition to open up a
fascinating area of European history to this country,'' J. Carter
Brown, director of the National Gallery said.
   The exhibit has been supported by contributions from the Boeing
Company, the Federation of Swedish Industries and the Swedish
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
