<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1716EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RadioWriters     04-11 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Radio Writers,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writers Bellow And Terkel Talk To Radio Audience In Kiev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authors Saul Bellow and Studs Terkel talked
Monday about a familiar topic, writers and writing, but to an
unfamiliar audience _ a big chunk of their listeners will tune in
on radios in the Soviet Union.
   The topic was ``glasnost''_ the new policy of openness promoted
by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev _ and how writers might help
foster greater understanding between their two countries.
   The program, originating live on public radio WBEZ in Chicago
with panelists commenting by telephone from Kiev, was recorded for
broadcast sometime later this week in that city in the Soviet
Ukraine.
   ``I think we can say the Cold War days have basically had it,''
said Terkel, the Chicago-based author and interviewer known for
such books as ``Working'' and ``The Good War.''
   ``I'm happy to say that a recent poll ... revealed that the
American people think drugs is the biggest fear and not communism.
It shows there is more curiosity than antipathy when the Soviet
Union is mentioned today,'' he said.
   Panelists in Kiev and Chicago lauded the more tolerant attitude
towards art and artists in the Soviet Union.
   But Alexi Gubenko, chief correspondent for Radio Kiev, opened
the 75-minute program with an apology to Bellow, the Nobel and
Pulitzer Prize-winning novelist whose works have not been ranslated
into Russian.
   ``I can say the ice has already melted in many ways ... Yet, it
is very sad that such distinguished writers as Mr. Bellow are not
available at this time,'' Gubenko said.
   ``I met Mr. Gorbachev at the White House recently,'' Bellow
said, ``but I didn't get a chance to ask him about it.''
   On a more serious note, Bellow noted that proposed cultural
exchanges of the past had promised more than they'd delivered. The
author of ``The Adventures of Augie March,'' and most recently,
``More Die of Heartbreak,'' added he hoped ``that wouldn't be the
case with glasnost.''
   Soviet writer and critic Ivan Drach said from Kiev that the
profusion of literary journals in Kiev alone, and the freedom to
publish works that had been banned for years, suggested glasnost
would lead to fundamental changes in Soviet life.
   `Indeed, we said too many sweet words about our past reality,''
Drach said through a translator. ``The problems have been raised,
the problems are many, but at last they are being discussed.''
</TEXT>
