<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MacDowellMedal     04-11 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MacDowell Medal,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>William Styron To Receive MacDowell Medal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PETERBORO, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Styron has been named the
recipient of the 1988 Edward MacDowell Medal for his lifetime
achievements as a writer, a spokeswoman for the MacDowell Colony
for artists said Monday.
   Styron is being recognized for his novels, articles and essays,
including the 1967 book ``The Confessions of Nat Turner,'' which
won a Pulitzer Prize, and ``Sophie's Choice,'' which won the
American Book Award in 1980.
   ``We will honor William Styron for his contribution to American
literature and for his unique insight and vision of the American
novel,'' said Mary Carswell, the colony's executive director.
   ``Through his works, he has helped us understand man's
limitations. He has taught us lessons about the human condition,
about how to survive, about right and wrong.''
   Styron was chosen by a committee of seven American literary
figures. It was chaired by John Updike, a former MacDowell
medalist, and included Michael Blumenthal, Brendan Gill, Elizabeth
Hardwick, Norman Mailer, Elizabeth Sifton and Robert Taylor.
   Updike will present the medal to Styron and writer George
Plimpton also will speak at a ceremony Aug. 21 at the MacDowell
Colony, a retreat for artists founded in 1907 by composer Edward
MacDowell and his wife, Marian.
   Styron is the 29th recipient of the MacDowell Medal. Past
medalists include writers Thornton Wilder, Eudora Welty and Lillian
Hellman; composers Aaron Copland, Leonard Bernstein and William
Schuman; and visual artists Georgia O'Keeffe, Willem de Kooning and
Louise Nevelson.
</TEXT>
