<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1740EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CollegeGiving     04-11 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-College Giving,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Private Gifts To Colleges Surge To Record $8.5 Billion In 1986-87</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private gifts to the nation's colleges and
universities rose a record $1.1 billion to $8.5 billion in 1986-87,
boosted by a sharp increase in alumni contributions, according to
an annual survey.
   For the second straight year, Stanford University was the most
successful fund-raiser with $198.5 million, topping Harvard
University which raised $178 million.
   The 1986-87 survey results gathered by the Council for Aid to
Education were projected from data reported by 1,174 colleges and
universities which together account for about 85 percent of all
private giving to higher education.
   Council president John R. Haire said several factors explain the
unusual rise in contributions. The percentage of the population
with four years or more of college doubled since 1970, meaning more
people were in a position to give.
   Colleges were more aggressive in making their case for
donations, Haire added. And the stock market was still booming in
1986-87.
   Among the survey findings:
   _Support from all sources reached $8.5 billion, up 14.9 percent
from the $7.4 billion raised in 1985-86.
   _Alumni donations showed the largest year-to-year increase, up
28.5 percent to $2.34 billion.
   Among other donor groups, non-alumni individuals contributed
$2.06 billion, up 16 percent; corporations gave $1.8 billion, up
$6.9 percent; foundations gave $1.5 billion, up 11 percent;
religious organizations donated $204 million, a 3.3 percent
decrease, and contributions from other sources rose 6.6 percent to
$552 million.
   _Following Stanford and Harvard, other top fund-raisers were
Cornell University, $149.7 million; Yale University, $120.1
million; University of Minnesota, $116.3 million; Washington
University (St. Louis), $110.4 million; Columbia University, $104.6
million; Massachusetts Institute of Technology, $101.4 million;
Johns Hopkins University, $92.6 million; and the University of
Southern California, $91.2 million.
</TEXT>
