<HEAD>Prank Forces Dukakis Campaign to Unplug Its Toll-Free Number</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An apparent prank has forced the presidential
campaign of Gov. Michael Dukakis to disconnect its toll-free
nationwide telephone number, an aide said Monday.
   Dukakis fell victim to an unidentified person who placed
classified advertisements in more than a half dozen big-city daily
newspapers. The ads purported to be recruiting electricians and
helpers, but each one listed the 800 telephone number used by
Dukakis' national campaign headquarters in Boston.
   ``It's a lame joke at the expense of people who are out of work
and looking for a job,'' campaign spokesman Steve Akey said. ``We
received numerous calls.''
   Akey added that the campaign reluctantly canceled the number
last week and has no plans to request a new 800 number which, he
said, would be equally vulnerable to sabotage.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Delaware GOP Starts Convention Delegate Process</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
