<HEAD>Top Democrats: Dukakis, Jackson Can't Win South Carolina</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Democratic presidential ticket headed by
Massachussets Gov. Michael Dukakis or native son Jesse Jackson has
little chance of winning in South Carolina, top state Democrats
believe.
   ``To carry South Carolina, we'd need a conservative Southern
Democrat on the ticket,'' said U.S. Rep. Robin Tallon of Florence.
``We haven't been successful except once, in the past five
elections, so I don't see us doing much worse.''
   State House Speaker Bob Sheehan, D-Kershaw, said a ticket with
Jackson or Dukakis ``will not do very well with the general public
in the state'' because neither ticket would be ``nearly as centrist
or conservative as South Carolina is.''
   Sen. Ernest F. Hollings said he will support the Democratic
ticket regardless of who is on it, but wasn't enthusiastic about
current prospects.
   ``I'm not gung ho for anybody who's against our position in
Central America, and I'm not going to work hard for anybody who
believes in Cuba and Castro,'' Hollings said.
   Hollings said he is uncomfortable with Dukakis' views as well as
Jackson's. ``I've got a problem with both of them,'' he said.
