<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Arabs,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Comments Stir Ire Among Some Arab-Americans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab-American supporters of Jesse Jackson
splintered bitterly Monday over the Democratic presidential
hopeful's latest comments on the Middle East, with one group asking
why he had chosen to ``abandon your principles.''
   ``Your comments in New York have the appearance of tailoring
your positions on critical issues to suit the narrow political
views of powerful special interest groups,'' said Abdeen Jabara,
president of the American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee, in a
letter to Jackson.
   But James Zogby, executive director of the Arab-American
Institute, said suggestions that Jackson has shifted are ``grossly
exaggerating'' what happened.
   ``One can't erase a nine-year commitment to Palestinian rights
and to peace and justice for both Israelis and Palestinians in just
one day,'' Zogby said in a statement issued by his office.
``Arab-Americans in New York and across the nation are strongly
committed to Jackson's campaign.''
   The institute also released a statement from Edward Said, a
Columbia University professor. Said is a member of the Palestine
National Council _ often called the political wing of the PLO _ and
met with Secretary of State George Shultz in a controversial
Washington session last month.
   ``I feel that Rev. Jackson remains the only presidential
candidate responsive to Arab and Palestinian concerns. He has never
backed away from defending the rights of the Palestinian people,
whom he described this morning as `sovereign,''' Said said.
   Jackson has long been outspoken about a need to meet the
Palestinians' needs in any Middle East peace agreement. And
Arab-Americans have provided money and votes to his 1984 and 1988
campaigns.
   On Sunday, Jackson seemed to distance himself from the Palestine
Liberation Organization and he said that, as president, he would
not sit down with PLO leader Yasser Arafat.
   ``We must not equate Arafat and the PLO with a sovereign people,
the Palestinian people,'' he said.
   Asked on Monday to expand that stand, Jackson said:
   ``It would not be a good approach to start at the table with the
most extreme elements. That's a formula for catastrophe.''
   Jabara said in his letter that Jackson is pandering to Jewish
voters in the April 19 New York primary.
   ``On behalf of tens of thousands of Arab-Americans, I wish to
express my sadness that you felt the need to abandon your
principles in your campaign for public office,'' Jabara wrote.
``Virtually every Arab-American looked to you as the one symbol of
strength in a field of political candidates who are notorious for
their unwillingness to stand up to the pro-Israel lobby.''
   In particular, Jabara said the PLO is the spokesman for the
Palestinians.
   ``You know full well that virtually all Palestinians regard the
PLO as their sole legitimate representative,'' he said. ``Your
attempts to distinguish the PLO from the Palestinian people will
not improve your position with Jewish voters in New York, but will,
sadly, raise questions among your traditional supporters as to your
willingess to stand firm on principle.''
</TEXT>
