<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Spice Imports,110</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spice Imports Rose 12 Percent Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spice imports totaled about $439 million last
year, up 12 percent from 1986, the Agriculture Department said
Monday.
   The rise was due mainly to larger imports of vanilla beans,
white pepper, nutmeg and mace, cassia, cumin, anise, capsicum
peppers, laurel and thyme, the department's Foreign Agricultural
Service reported. Higher prices of many of the items also were a
factor.
   ``Saffron prices have soared in recent months, reflecting a
short Spanish crop,'' the report said.
   Also, it added, cesium contamination from the Soviet Union's
nuclear mishap at Chernobyl two years ago ``has kept supplies tight
and prices firm for several Mediterranean-area herbs such as
oregano, laurel, rosemary and sage.''
</TEXT>
