<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1906EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Glance     04-11 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Glance,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The anticipated drought in the West this summer will curtail
industries and recreation throughout the region. Here is a brief
summary:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FARMING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Water districts will cut farm water allotments.
   Ranchers are trucking water to cattle, selling stock and
appealing for federal grain subsidies as pastures and water holes
dry up.
   Wheat farmers are bracing for low yields.
   Irrigation water will be in short supply for the orchards,
hopyards, vineyards and livestock on the eastern slopes of the
Cascades in Washington state.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>UTILITIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Bonneville Power Administration stopped selling power to
California last fall to make up for a drop in electricity produced
by the hydroelectric dams on the Columbia River.
   The Northwest Power Planning Council anticipates power rate
increases if it has to buy power from Canada or generate
electricity from coal plants to make up for less electricity from
the hydroelectric dams.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FORESTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The region's forests, already heavily scarred by fires last
summer, are bracing for fire season. Last summer, officials limited
logging in Oregon forests where the fire danger was high, so timber
companies have been stockpiling logs through the winter and spring,
pushing up prices in the process.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FISHING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A bacterial disease called furunculosis could kill thousands of
spring chinook salmon on their spawning run up southern Oregon's
Rogue River.
   Low water flows mean higher water temperatures, which promote
the growth of the bacteria. Low water also makes it tougher for the
fish to swim up rapids and falls, bottling them up in crowded pools
where the bacteria is more readily spread.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
