<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Over South, Snow In Ozarks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell from the lower Mississippi Valley to the southern
Atlantic states on Monday, and cold rain fell over Arkansas and
northern Mississippi, with some snow in higher elevations of
western Arkansas.
   Thunderstorms broke out around Georgia. Thunderstorms produced
golfball-size hail at Peachtree City, just south of Atlanta.
Quarter-size hail piled up 3 inches deep at Forsyth, in central
Georgia.
   Smaller hail was reported at a number of locations in eastern
Alabama and Georgia and northwestern South Carolina.
   Savannah, Ga., got 0.71 of an inch of rain in one hour during an
afternoon thunderstorm.
   Temperatures were only in the 40s when scattered rain fell in
Arkansas, northern Louisiana and northern Mississippi. Jackson,
Miss., reported a temperature of just 45 degrees at 3 p.m. EDT.
   The higher elevations of western Arkansas got more snow, with 3
inches on the ground on the top of Rich Mountain, at an elevation
of 2,800 feet.
   A freeze warning was posted overnight for the Hill Country of
south-central Texas.
   Elsewhere, light snow also was reported at Eastport, Maine,
during the afternoon.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 38
degrees at Hyannis, Mass., to 94 at Thermal, Calif. The low for the
day was 7 degrees above zero at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Tuesday, showers and a few thunderstorms were forecast from
Mississippi and Tennessee across the central and southern
Appalachians to the Carolinas and Georgia.
   Highs in the 40s or 50s were predicted in New England; in the
50s in parts of Mississippi, the southern Appalachians, the middle
Atlantic states and the Great Lakes region; in the 80s in
southwestern Texas and interior California; in the 80s and 90s in
the desert Southwest; and in the 60s or 70s across most of the
nation.
</TEXT>
