<2ND_LINE>AM-Hinckley,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Hinckley To Be Questioned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Monday ordered presidential
assailant John W. Hinckley Jr. to be questioned in a deposition
prior to a civil trial arising from the 1981 shooting of President
Reagan.
   U.S. District Judge John Garrett Penn approved a motion by
lawyers representing White House press secretary James S. Brady and
two other people wounded in the March 30, 1981, shooting to
question Hinckley before the case goes to trial later this month.
   The trial of the multimillion-dollar lawsuits brought by Brady,
retired Washington policeman Thomas K. Delahanty and Secret Service
agent Timothy J. McCarthy is scheduled to begin April 26 before
Penn.
   Hinckley, who was confined to St. Elisabeths mental hospital
here following his 1982 acquittal by reason of insanity of
attempted murder charges, has asked to attend the trial, which
could last several days.
   Penn said at a hearing that he has made arrangements with the
U.S. Marshals Service for Hinckley to be present.
   Brady, who was shot in the head, was left permanently crippled.
Delahanty, who was shot in the back, was forced to retire from the
police force because of his medical disability.
   McCarthy was hospitalized for several weeks after a bullet was
surgically removed from his abdomen.
   The defense claims that Hinckley cannot be held liable for
damages because he was insane at the time of the shooting.
</TEXT>
