<HEAD>Prime Minister Arrives for Talks with U.S. Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew of Singapore on
Monday began a five-day visit to Washington that will include talks
with President Reagan and U.S. editors critical of Singapore's
press restrictions.
   The State Department described Lee's Washington stay as a
private visit, but officials of both countries said the 63-old
leader would meet Secretary of State George Shultz Tuesday and
lunch Wednesday with Reagan at the White House.
   On Thursday, Lee is scheduled to address both the American
Society of Newspaper Editors and the Asia Society.
   ASNE leaders in recent years have criticized Singapore's
restrictions on the circulation of foreign publications, ordered on
grounds that their articles amount to interference in domestic
politics. Publications hit with restrictions at various times have
included the Asian Wall Street Journal, Time Magazine and the Far
Eastern Economic Review.
   The Singapore Foreign Ministry said in January press freedom in
Singapore should not be expected to meet the ``free and
unrestricted'' standards of United States.
   Meetings were also scheduled with members of Congress.
   House Foreign Affairs Committee Chairman Rep. Dante Fascell,
D-Fla., joined 50 other lawmakers in a joint letter last year
protesting the Lee government's use of preventive arrest without
trial of people suspected of subversion.
   Trade was another likely issue in Lee's talks. Singapore, a
newly-industrialized and affluent country with a growing trade
surplus with America, is facing loss of U.S. duty concessions
intended to promote development in poor countries.
</TEXT>
