<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MountTrial     04-11 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mount Trial,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scholar Plans Appeal of Conviction on Transport of Stolen
Documents</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT summary line.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scholar will appeal his conviction Monday for
transporting stolen historic documents that belonged to the
National Archives and Library of Congress, including letters from
Abraham Lincoln and Winston Churchill, his attorney said.
   Charles Merrill Mount, 59, a Brooklyn native who sports the
accent and manners of a British gentleman, was convicted of
interstate transportation of stolen goods.
   He is scheduled to be sentenced in U.S. District Court May 23
and faces up to 10 years in prison and a $500,000 fine. He was
released on $50,000 bail pending sentencing.
   Charles McGinty, Mount's public defender, said he will appeal on
grounds that the court should have paid transportation costs for
two Irish men Mount wanted as defense witnesses. Mount, whose
$18,400 in savings was seized by the government following the
arrest, claimed his status as indigent required prosecutors to pay
to bring witnesses to Boston.
   Mount, a respected art historian and former Guggenheim
Foundation fellow, claimed he owned the documents for years and
showed some of them to the two Irish men in the 1960s in Dublin.
   ``This was not a trial. It was only a hearing of government
allegations,'' Mount said after the verdict. ``A trial is when both
sides present their case. It did not happen here. ... The
government wanted a conviction and they got a conviction.''
   The jury deliberated four hours Friday and met for another 2{
hours Monday before returning the verdicts.
   Mount was accused of selling letters by artist James McNeill
Whistler, Winston Churchill and author Henry James, allegedly
belonging to the Library of Congress, to a Boston bookshop for
about $20,000 in July.
   He was arrested by FBI agents in August at the bookshop while
trying to sell letters and papers signed by Abraham Lincoln and
Civil War generals that allegedly were taken from the National
Archives.
   The government did not charge Mount with stealing the documents.
   Mount's only defense witness during the three-week trial was a
Nebraska woman who said she met Mount in an Ireland hotel in 1961
and saw some documents. She paid her own fare to Boston.
   Mount also has been indicted by a Washington grand jury on
charges of possession of federal property, but McGinty said he
would question whether Mount should face those charges following
his conviction on the transportation charges.
   Frank L. McNamara Jr., U.S. attorney in Boston, said he did not
know if federal prosecutors in Washington would pursue the
possession charges. Mount's court-appointed Washington counsel,
James Lyons, did not return phone calls.
   Mount, who changed his name from Stanley Merrill Suchow in the
1950s, said he will return to his room in a Washington boarding
house.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
