<DOCNO> AP880411-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1917EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Honduras     04-11 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Withdraws Troops From Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government withdrew thousands
of soldiers from the streets of the capital Monday and businesses
reopened for the first time after violent anti-U.S. demonstrations
last week.
   Restrictions imposed on two cities under a temporary state of
emergency remained in effect, but the government said the emergency
might be lifted later this week if no further trouble was reported.
   Protesters attacked and burned the U.S. Consulate Thursday night
after a Honduran man suspected of drug trafficking was arrested and
flown to the United States. Five Hondurans were killed in the
violence. The Honduran Constitution prohibits the extradition of
Honduran citizens.
   The state of emergency imposed Friday gave authorities the power
to ban public demonstrations and restrict freedom of movement in
the capital of Tegucigalpa and San Pedro Sula, 125 miles to the
north. The cities are the largest in Honduras.
   Many businesses closed Friday as students filled the street for
an anti-American demonstration. They remained shut Saturday as
thousands of police and soldiers patrolled the tense capital.
   Major Manuel Antonio Urbina, chief police spokesman, said
authorities had detained at least 70 people believed involved in
the attack on the embassy facilities.
   Military sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
number of people arrested in connection with demonstrations and
looting could climb to 300 in Tegucigalpa and San Pedro Sula.
   Thursday night's violence began during a student-led
demonstration against the April 5 arrest of Juan Ramon Matta.
   Honduran officials took Matta from his Tegucigalpa home in a
pre-dawn raid and hustled him onto a plane to the Dominican
Republic without a passport.
   Dominican Republic officials later put Matta on a New York-bound
flight and he was arrested aboard the jetliner by U.S. marshals,
according to U.S. law enforcement officials.
   Matta, held at a maximum-security federal prison in Marion,
Ill., was wanted by U.S. officials for questioning in the 1985
slaying in Mexico of a U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agent,
Enrique Camarena Salazar. He is also wanted on drug charges in the
United States.
   Honduran legislators criticized the incident and the Foreign
Ministry launched an investigation.
   The violent demonstration was unusual in Honduras, one of the
United States' closest allies in Central America.
   About 4,000 soldiers and police, many in tanks and trucks,
patrolled Tegucigalpa and San Pedro Sula on Saturday and Sunday.
   Presidential spokesman Lisandro Quesada said Monday that
President Jose Azcona Hoyo received repeated death threats in
anonymous telephone calls over the weekend.
   Monsignor Hector Enrique Santos, archbishop of Tegucigalpa, said
in an interview that the demonstrations showed ``barbaric
instincts'' and dealt a ``blow against the democratic continuity of
Honduras because they tend to undermine human coexistence.''
   Jaime Rosenthal Oliva, one of the nation's three vice
presidents, said the violence occurred because the government
violated the constitution in permitting Matta's extradition.
   ``I admire the U.S. fight to eliminate drug trafficking but I
consider that that nation has sufficient resources to accuse any
drug trafficker who lives here so that he can be judged in Honduras
after legal evidence is presented,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
