<DOCNO> AP880411-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1945EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PortExcavation     04-11 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Port Excavation,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas A&M Archaeologists Find Child's Skeleton at Submerged
Jamaican Ruins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLLEGE STATION, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas A&M University nautical
archaeologists excavating the submerged half of Jamaica's Port
Royal found remains of a child killed as he tried to flee during an
earthquake nearly 300 years ago, the university said Monday.
   The partial skeleton of the child, probably no older than 6, was
the first found in such a complete state during seven seasons of
digging in the sunken city, said project leader Don Hamilton.
   Port Royal, once home to English buccaneers and to a young naval
officer named Horatio Nelson, boasted a well-to-do population of
about 8,000 at the time of the quake.
   But on June 7, 1692, tremors over a period of roughly 30 minutes
dropped blocks of the city into the bay, killing 2,000 residents.
   Nearly 300 years later, Texas A&M researchers will resume their
archival work on items recovered so far, the university said. The
project will be featured May 2 in the PBS series, ``Underwater
Discoveries.''
   Among other finds from the latest round of excavations is what
appears to be part of the living quarters of well-to-do merchants.
Remains of a window complete with its slender lead frame have been
recovered where the front of a two-story house smashed to the
street during one of the tremors, Hamilton said.
   From what is probably the kitchen have come brass cooking pots,
sieves, pewter bowls, a woman's gold ring, candlesticks and
porcelain dishes. The almost-intact remains of a cricket were found
in an unbroken wine bottle excavated where mud had trapped the
insect.
   Port Royal, across the bay from modern-day Kingston, once was
rivaled only by Boston as a center of British commerce in the
Americas. Residents and visitors apparently liked tobacco because a
fourth of the nearly 5,000 artifacts recovered have been pipes or
parts of pipes.
   The port never regained its former importance because
earthquakes, fires and hurricanes blocked attempts to rebuild,
Hamilton said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880411-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1946EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Trade-Candidates     04-11 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade-Candidates,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Contenders Voice Support For Notice Of Plant Closings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contenders urged
Congress to stand firm against administration pressure and retain
in its sweeping trade bill a provision requiring employers to give
notice of plant closings.
   ``I offer my strong encouragement to your efforts in resisting
any further weakening of these already quite modest provisions,''
Jesse Jackson said in a letter to Senate Finance Committee Chairman
Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas.
   ``I urge you and other conferees to insist that mandatory
advance plant notification be included in the final version,'' said
Sen. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn., in a letter to Bentsen. Both
messages were dated Friday and released Monday by the office of
Rep. William D. Ford, D-Mich.
   The Reagan administration has been pushing Congress to drop the
plant closings provision.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis already had called for
retaining the provision, which would require companies with more
than 100 employees to give 60 days' notice before a plant closing
or large-scale layoff.
   ``I am aware that the administration has refused to accept any
form of advance notice provision and has threatened a veto of the
trade bill if the conference committee's provision passed,''
Dukakis said in a March 30 letter to Bentsen. ``I hope that the
threat is only that _ a threat that would not be carried out if the
situation actually presents itself.''
   ``Regardless of the president's intentions, I urge you to work
for retention of the plant closing provision in the trade bill,''
Dukakis said.
   The plant closings provision is one facet of a sweeping bill
that contains measures ranging from approval for the administration
to sign trade deals with other countries to repeal of the windfall
profits tax on oil companies.
   At the heart of the bill are provisions that restructure the way
in which the United States retaliates against violations of
international trade rules. Lawmakers say they are designed to open
foreign markets to U.S. exports.
   The measure has been approved in large part by a House-Senate
conference committee, although a few finishing touches remain to be
attended to.
   Any congressional move to drop provisions that might yield a
veto most likely would have to start with Bentsen under powers that
have been granted him by Senate conferees.
   Bentsen, as vice chairman of the conference committee, took the
lead in dropping a number of stringent provisions opposed earlier
by the Reagan administration.
   The administration has been describing the plant-closings
provision as one that would be disastrously expensive for industry.
While the measure contains no money provisions, some business
groups have suggested it would be a first step toward substantial
costs later.
   The candidates jumped into the debate amid new signals from the
administation that a veto could await the 1,000-page trade bill if
it arrives at the president's desk with the plant-closings
provision intact.
   Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III said in an interview on
NBC-TV's ``Today'' show that he would meet with congressional
leaders early this week to discuss what lawmakers must do to win
presidential approval of the legislation.
   ``At the very least it will take removal of some provisions that
are now in that bill,'' Baker said. ``Such, for instance, as a
provision requiring that any business in the United States give
prior notice of layoffs or a desire to close a facility.''
   He stopped short, however, of saying that a veto would
automatically result from trade sanctions in the bill against
Japan's Toshiba electronics company because of a sale by a
subsidiary of submarine-silencing equipment to the Soviet Union.
   ``That is something that we don't like,'' Baker said. ``There
are a number of things in the bill that we do like. There are a
number of things in the bill that we need. I don't think you can
take each and every item in there and say this for sure will
trigger a veto. I think you can say that about the plant-closing
provision.''
   ``My own personal view is that the president will veto the bill
if that plant closing provision stays in there,'' he added.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, said he hoped to bring the
final version of the trade bill to the House floor for a vote next
week.
   He said that before that happens there may be a few changes in
the measure and that he is not ``set in concrete'' on how the
provisions are drawn.
</TEXT>
