<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Robertson-IRS 1stLd-Writethru a0664 04-11 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson-IRS, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0664,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRS Wants Books From Robertson Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf to UPDATE with hearing continued</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate Pat
Robertson's campaign organization said Monday it already has
submitted 1986 financial records the Internal Revenue Service is
going to court to obtain.
   ``If there is a hearing, we will attend to show that we have
complied with the order,'' said Barbara Gattullo, a representative
for Americans for Robertson. She said the material was turned over
last week.
   James F. Patterson, treasurer of the organization, said it has
been ordered to court before U.S. District Judge J. Calvitt Clarke
to show why the IRS should not be given records needed to verify
the accuracy of the group's 1986 tax filing. The hearing was
originally set for Tuesday but was continued until April 28.
   Court documents show that the IRS first requested the financial
information in December 1987. The IRS also asked for copies of
fund-raising letters sent out and ``records of any transactions
with The Freedom Council or Christian Broadcasting Network.''
   Robertson, a former television evangelist, founded the
non-profit CBN and was its president until last October when he
announced his candidacy. He turned over the operation of the cable
network to his son Tim Robertson.
   The Freedom Council was established in 1981 with seed money from
CBN. According to former council officials, nearly $3 million was
pumped into the organization from CBN in 1985, the year Robertsn
began establishing his grass-roots campaign organization.
   Many credit the Freedom Council, also a tax-exempt, charitable
organization, with mobilizing Robertson's cadre of volunteers,
mostly political first-timers drawn mainly from charismatic or
fundamentalist churches. Robertson used these volunteers to pack
local GOP meetings and caucuses to gain control of the party at the
local level in several states.
   Under federal tax laws, tax-exempt entities cannot raise money
for, or support, political candidates.
   The stated purpose of the council, which closed its operation in
October 1986, was to educate Christians on how to get involved in
politics. However, critics have charged that the group was a front
for Robertson's then-unofficial political campaign.
   The IRS currently is probing the tax-exempt status of CBN over
the same general issue.
   If the money was used for Robertson's campaign, then the
tax-exempt status of CBN would be in jeopardy. If, as CBN and
Freedom Council officials have said, the money was used to educate
Christians as to how to become involved in the political process,
then it would be legitimate donation.
   Americans For Robertson, the campaign organization, filed for
organization with the Federal Election Commission in July 1986.
   During 1986, Bob Slosser, president of CBN University, served as
president of the Freedom Council after retired Gen. Jerry Curry
resigned from the post in the spring. When Americans for Robertson,
the campaign organization, was organized in July 1986, Marc Nuttle
was named acting director. At the same time, he was also a paid
consultant for the Freedom Council.
   Nuttle became Robertson's campaign manager until last month when
he was assigned other duties as part of Robertson's scaling back of
his campaign. Though he remains the lone official challenger of
Vice President George Bush, Robertson admits he has no chance for
the nomination.
   He has laid off most of his national staff and restricted his
campaigning to occasional appearances in states that select
delegates to the national convention by caucus.
</TEXT>
