<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0696 04-11 0840</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0696,0862</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Deports Eight Palestinians, Orders 12 Others Expelled</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with eight Arabs wounded. Picks
up 7th graf pvs ``The deaths ...; SUBS penultimate graf ``Settlers
and...'' with one graf to CORRECT first name to Geulah, sted
Beulah.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel expelled eight Palestinians from the
occupied lands Monday, accusing them of inciting the four months of
violence there, and it issued deportation orders against 12 others.
   In the West Bank, meanwhile, Israeli troops shot and killed two
Arabs after a group of Palestinians threw stones and bottles at a
patrol, the army said. Hospital officials said eight Arabs were
wounded.
   Among the 12 receiving deportation orders were six Palestinians
from a West Bank village where an Israeli settler girl and two
Arabs were killed in a clash last week.
   Palestinian leaders contended the purpose of the expulsions was
to appease right-wing politicians and Jewish settlers angered by an
army report that said Tirza Porat, 15, was killed by a bullet from
another settler's gun.
   But Israel television quoted a top military official as saying
the deportations were intended as a warning to Palestinians.
   In the West Bank village of Rai near Nablus, troops shot and
killed two Arabs after a patrol was pelted with rocks and bottles,
the army said.
   Arab doctors said three other Palestinians, including an
11-year-old girl and a 14-year-old boy, were wounded in Rai.
Hospital officials said four others were wounded in Nablus and one
in Jenin, another village near Nablus.
   The deaths brought to 143 the number of Arabs killed since riots
began Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel captured
from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war. Two Israelis,
Ms. Porat and a soldier, have also died.
   The army said Monday that 4,800 Palestinians have been arrested
since the riots began. Five hundred of them have been convicted,
3,400 are awaiting trial and 900 are being held in administrative
detention, which allows imprisonment without trial for six months.
   Arab residents of the occupied territories followed Palestine
Liberation Organization orders to close stores and stay home from
jobs in Israel on Monday. Underground leaflets called for a ``day
of firebombs'' April 21.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said:
``We strongly oppose deportations from the occupied territories,''
which he described as ``counterproductive. ... They only further
inflame passions.''
   Redman said the practice violates international human rights
agreements to which Israel is a signatory. The Geneva Convention
bars expulsion of civilians in time of war, but Israeli officials
say the convention applies only to mass expulsions.
   Army helicopters flew the eight deportees to Israel's
self-proclaimed security zone in southern Lebanon. The army offered
them a medical examination and gave each $50 before soldiers led
them to two taxis heading for Syrian-controlled territory.
   Israel television showed some of the men carrying their
belongings in plastic bags. When the taxis sped off, one of the
Palestinians flashed a victory sign.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said on Israel radio: ``We are not
expelling residents. We are only expelling agitators, preachers (of
violence) and extremists. The past has proven that expulsions are
one of the most effective deterrents.''
   Palestinian leaders said the expulsions would feed bitterness.
``The more the government uses drastic measures, the more people
become determined, even though they don't have the power to
overthrow the authorities,'' said Rashad al Shawwa, a former Gaza
City mayor deposed by Israel.
   Monday's deportation was the second in four months of riots. The
expulsion of four Palestinians on Jan. 13 provoked an international
outcry. More than 1,000 Arabs have been expelled from the
territories since 1967.
   Expulsion orders against five of those expelled Monday were
issued three months ago. The most prominent deportee is Abed al
Aziz Uda Rafia, 33, of Gaza City, described by the army as chief
ideologue of a Moslem fundamentalist group pledged to destroy
Israel and create a Palestinian homeland through war.
   Elias Freij, a Christian Palestinian who is mayor of Bethlehem,
called the deportations ``a revenge for Beita,'' the village where
Arabs attacked 16 teen-age hikers and two armed guards from Elo
Moreh, a Jewish settlement.
   ``It was done to appease the settlers,'' Freij said.
   Uri Ariel, head of the West Bank settlements council, said
Monday's action was ``too little too late'' and demanded more
expulsions.
   The Beita clash Wednesday has provoked debate along party lines
since army investigators said Miss Porat apparently was struck by a
bullet from the gun of Romem Al Dubi, one of the two guards
accompanying the teen-agers.
   Settlers and right-wing legislators said the army report was
one-sided. Geulah Cohen of the right-wing party Tehiya said Lt.
Gen. Dan Shomron, the army chief of staff, ``jumped to conclusions
and, acting as a judge, pointed an accusing finger at the
settlers.''
   Peres, who leads the center-left Labor Party, said to the
critics: ``This is very serious, the attempt to involve the army in
political matters.''
</TEXT>
