<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Texaco,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco Confirms It Is Negotiating To Sell Deutsche Texaco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. oil giant Texaco Inc. said
Monday it is negotiating to sell its West German subsidiary
Deutsche Texaco AG as part of a restructuring.
   Texaco officials confirmed news reports and industry rumors that
its Hamburg-based unit is up for sale. But the officials refused to
name prospective buyers or give details of the negotiations.
   ``We can't disclose any details, especially the names of the
companies interested in the takeover, while negotiations with
interested parties are going on,'' Texaco said in a statement.
   Texaco officials Friday told Deutsche Texaco's supervisory board
the parent company planned to sell its 99.1 percent share of the
German subsidiary as part of a restructuring to lead it out of
Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings.
   Industry analysts said the German company would be an attractive
acquisition because of its large gasoline marketing network,
substantial cash reserves and oil and gas assets.
   Deutsche Texaco has 1,903 gasoline stations in West Germany.
   Company officials declined to say whether the company is
profitable but said the company will release its 1987 figure next
month.
   Texaco said in its 1987 annual report it hopes to raise at least
$3 billion through the sale of assets. The sale of Deutsche Texaco
could net about $1.7 billion, officials said.
</TEXT>
