<DOCNO> AP880411-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 2057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TestBan     04-11 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Test Ban,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Hail Limited Test Ban Treaty to Mark 25th Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and American officials marked the 25th
anniversary of the Limited Test Ban Treaty Monday by hailing it as
a historic pact that laid the groundwork for subsequent nuclear
arms agreements.
   Officials gathered at the John F. Kennedy Library and Museum to
reminisce about the events surrounding its signing.
   Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin praised President Kennedy, who
oversaw the U.S. side of negotiations, saying the treaty ``would
not have been attained without a fresh and sober look'' at
superpower rivalry by ``that dynamic leader.''
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, brother of the late president, called
the treaty a ``watershed event in Soviet-American relations ... the
first major arms control agreement involving the superpowers.''
   The treaty, signed July 25, 1963, after 10 days of negotiations
in Moscow involving Soviet, U.S., and British representatives,
banned testing of nuclear weapons in the atmosphere, in outer space
and under water.
   Other testing bans have been signed since, but the Test Ban
Treaty remains the only one ratified by both superpowers.
   Former Soviet and U.S. participants in the negotiations agreed
at a news conference that the treaty gave rise to a series of other
nuclear arms pacts between the superpowers, including last year's
accord to eliminate intermediate-range nuclear weapons.
   McGeorge Bundy, special assistant for national security affairs
from 1961 to 1966, told reporters the signing ``brought a prospect
of further and larger agreements,'' and praised Kennedy for
ignoring U.S. perceptions that the Soviets were further advanced in
testing.
   Alexei Roshchkin, a disarmament expert in the Soviet foreign
ministry at the time of the signing, concurred.
   ``This was a first step in post-war history ... a first step in
the field of disarmamanent,'' he said.
   Theodore Sorensen, special counsel to the president from 1961 to
1963 and part of a small group of advisers that guided the talks
from Washington by telephone, said ``there was a great sense of joy
and relief when word was received'' at the White House that the
treaty had been signed.
   ``But backslapping was not the Kennedy way,'' Sorensen said.
``On the contrary, he immediately began to worry about Senate
ratification,'' which came in the fall. Intense lobbying by the
president left only 11 Democrats and eight Republicans opposed.
   Soviet officials recalled the jubilation of their leader, Nikita
Khrushchev, as described by former Kennedy aide Arthur M.
Schlesinger Jr. in his book, ``A Thousand Days.''
   As Khrushchev and U.S. Undersecretary of State Averell Harriman
strode through a Kremlin park, ``a huge crowd collected behind
them,'' Schlesinger wrote.
   According to the book, Khrushchev turned and asked the crowd:
```We've just signed a test-ban treaty. I'm going to take him to
dinner. Do you think he's earned his dinner?' The people applauded
and applauded.''
   The signing and subsequent ratification followed 336 nuclear
explosions in the atmosphere by the United States, Britain and the
Soviet Union over 13 years.
   The agreement also was important as a tangible sign of emerging
detente after the Cuban missile crisis of October 1962 brought the
world to the brink of nuclear war.
   France and China, the only other nations that openly engaged in
nuclear weapons test programs, have not agreed to the test ban. But
all French nuclear explosions have been underground since 1974, and
China exploded its last atmospheric device in 1980.
   Disagreement on verification measures has held up joint
ratification of the 1974 Threshold Test Ban Treaty and the 1976
Peaceful Nuclear Explosions Treaty limiting test explosions to 150
kilotons. A kiloton equals the explosive force of 1,000 tons of TNT.
   U.S. and Soviet negotiators began a second round of talks on
ratifying those two treaties in February, and participants Monday
invoked the Limited Test Ban treaty as an example that agreement is
possible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880411-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 2058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Gulf     04-11 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Envoy, UN Chief Begin Talks on UN Peace Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Iraqi envoy said Monday there is
no point in continuing talks on ending the Persian Gulf war until
Iran accepts a Security Council peace plan.
   ``We do not want to enter into another round of futile
discussions and arguments and wrangling,'' Wisam Alzahawi, a senior
deputy foreign minister, told reporters after a meeting with U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   Nearly nine months have passed since the Security Council passed
a resolution demanding an immediate cease-fire and troop withdrawal
as the first steps toward a negotiated end to the 7{-year-old
Iran-Iraq war.
   Iraq endorsed the resolution almost immediately; Iran has yet to
do so.
   The United States wants the council to impose an arms embargo on
Iran for not accepting the resolution but has failed to muster the
support of the Soviet Union.
   Alzahawi said he told Perez de Cuellar that Iraq is ready ``to
sit and negotiate with the Iranians under the auspices of the
secretary-general once the Security Council obtains Iran's
unequivocal, clear-cut official acceptance of the resolution.''
   Iraq says it accepts a cease-fire and troop withdrawal as the
first steps in a settlement of the war. Iran wants the United
Nations to condemn Iraq as the aggressor in the war before it pulls
out any troops.
   Alzawahi said Iraq is ``not entering into any details of
implementation at this stage before we have a clear-cut acceptance
from Iran.''
   Iran's deputy foreign minister, Mohammed Larijani, held talks
with Perez de Cuellar last week. Larijani dismissed Iran's position
on the resolution as irrelevant and instead urged the Security
Council to condemn Iraq for using chemical weapons.
   Iran's U.N. representative, Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati, repeated
this request at a news conference Monday, saying the council should
ban the export to Iraq of chemicals used to make the deadly weapons.
   Alzahawi dodged questions from reporters about Iraq's use of
chemical warfare and accused Iran of using the weapons. He said
Iraq would ``observe the rules of international combat'' if Iran
did.
   Alzahawi also denied that he and Perez de Cuellar has discussed
the issue of chemical weapons on Monday. The U.N. chief has sent
teams to Tehran and Baghdad to investigate charges that such
weapons were being used.
   Iran has charged that Iraq dropped cyanide and mustard gas bombs
on three Kurdish towns in Iraq in March, killing 5,000 Kurds.
</TEXT>
