<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Taylor     04-11 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Taylor,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Early Airplane Designer Dead at 89</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   C.G. Taylor, a self-taught aircraft
designer whose Taylor Cub evolved into the overwhelmingly
successful Piper Cub of the 1930s and 1940s, has died in Houston,
his daughter said Monday.
   Taylor, 89, had suffered from Parkinson's disease for more than
a year, and died March 29, said Carol Taylor Sharp.
   In partnership with William Piper, Taylor designed and sold the
Taylor Cub, a lightweight two-passenger airplane at Bradford, Pa.
in the early 1930s.
   After several years in production, Piper bought Taylor's
interest in the aircraft and began manufacturing it under the Piper
Cub label.
   The Piper Aircraft Co. went on to build more than 20,000 of the
simple, yellow airplanes _ initially for about $700 apiece.
   Taylor designed another single-engine aircraft in 1936, the
Taylorcraft, which was also highly successful.
   Born in Rochester, N.Y., Taylor is survived by five children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
