<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Kling     04-11 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Kling,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Television Comedy Writer-Producer Dies of Lung Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Woody Kling, a two-time Emmy winner who spent
40 years writing TV comedy for shows ranging from Milton Berle's
``Texaco Star Theater'' to the ``Cabbage Patch Kids,'' has died of
lung cancer at 62.
   Kling, who died early Sunday at UCLA Medical Center, began his
career in the 1940s with Buddy Arnold, writing sketches and jokes
for Berle's comedy show, the ``Texaco Star Theater.'' Kling also
co-wrote the opening jingle, ``Oh, we're the men of Texaco, we work
from Maine to Mexico.''
   Berle, ``Mr. Television,'' called Kling's work on the show a big
help to his own career.
   ``He was really a darling man,'' said Berle. ``He was always
charming and kind. He was very sharp. I thought he was a brilliant
man.''
   Kling, who lived in Los Angeles, also co-wrote and helped
produce the Jackie Gleason and Carol Burnett variety shows, and
wrote for Will Rogers, Jack Paar and Red Buttons.
   He was nominated for five Emmys, winning in 1972 and 1973 for
scripts for ``The Carol Burnett Show.''
   Kling was a co-executive producer on Norman Lear's television
series ``All in the Family.''
   He created and produced the cartoons ``Casper, the Friendly
Ghost'' and ``Beatles'' as well as the ``Cabbage Patch Kids
Christmas Special.''
   In addition to his wife of 21 years, Mary, he is survived by a
son, Anthony.
</TEXT>
