<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     04-11 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report 12 rebels Killed in Gun Battles, Four Commit Suicide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian and Sri Lankan troops killed 12
Tamil rebels in two gun battles and in a separate incident four
Tamils committed suicide by swallowing cyanide to avoid capture,
officials reported Monday.
   Eight rebels were killed Sunday when Sri Lankan soldiers raided
a jungle hideout in the Anuradhapura district about 100 miles
northeast of Colombo.
   A Sri Lankan military official said the hideout was used by
guerrillas of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam who were blamed
for the massacre last week of 14 Sinhalese villagers. He said the
camp was 10 miles northeast of Merigaswela where the villagers'
mutilated bodies were found Friday.
   The troops captured three Soviet-designed automatic rifles, a
submachine gun and a shotgun, the official said, speaking on
condition of anonymity. He did not report any army casualties.
   Tamil rebels have been fighting for four years for a separate
nation. Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's population of 16 million people and they claim they are
discriminated against by the Buddhist Sinhalese, who are the
majority.
   An Indian diplomat in Colombo said that on Saturday, four Tamil
Tigers killed themselves by biting cyanide capsules as they were
about to be captured by Indian troops in Batticaloa, 140 miles east
of Colombo.
   Many Tamil guerrillas carry cyanide capusules, and according to
official and unofficial reports at least 200 have committed suicide
since Tamil militants began their separatist war.
   The Indian diplomat, who spoke with the condition he not be
identified, also said Indian troops killed four Tamil rebels in a
gunfight Saturday at Vavuniya, 135 miles northeast of Colombo. He
said one Indian soldier was wounded.
   More than 50,000 Indian soldiers are in Sri Lanka to disarm the
Tamil rebels under an agreement signed July 29 by the Indian and
Sri Lankan governments.
   India is predominantly Hindu and has tried to arrange a peace
settlement in Sri Lanka. The Tamil Tigers, the largest rebel group,
have rejected demands that they lay down their arms and are
battling both Sri Lankan and Indian forces.
</TEXT>
