<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0712 04-11 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0712,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Blames Arab Leaders For West Bank Violence</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 8th graf pvs, He later, with Dukakis'
cousin Olympia Dukakis winning Academy Award</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis said Monday that Arab
leaders, by refusing to negotiate with Israel, are ``responsible
for the turmoil and the violence'' in the West Bank.
   Addressing Jewish leaders, Dukakis said the government of
Israel, as well as the ``generation of young Palestinians'' in the
region, do not bear the responsbility for recent violence there.
   ``Just as Camp David stands as an example of what can be
accomplished when leaders choose peace, the recent events in the
West Bank and Gaza show what happens when Arab leaders are
unwilling to walk in the footsteps of President Sadat,'' the late
Egyptian leader, Dukakis said.
   Dukakis made the comments in an address to the Conference of
Presidents of major American Jewish Organizations, an umbrella
group of leaders of 44 of the largest national Jewish organizations.
   With the race for the Democratic presidential nomination
focusing on New York's primary April 19, rival Albert Gore Jr.
spoke to the group earlier and strongly sided with Israel on the
violence in the occupied territories.
   The third Democratic candidate, Jesse Jackson, has declined an
invitation to address the group citing scheduling problems,
organization spokesman Richard Cohen said.
   Dukakis, the governor of Massachusetts, spent much of the day at
the State House in Boston before flying to New York.
   He later visited a New York restaurant, and planned to attend a
private reception and stop at a rally on Staten Island. He also was
attending an Academy Awards reception.
   Dukakis' cousin Olympia, made a pitch for him as she accepted
her Academy Award for best supporting actress on Monday night in
Los Angeles. ``OK, Michael, let's go!'' she said, waving her Oscar
statuette. Ms. Dukakis won for her role in the comedy
``Moonstruck.''
   Earlier, addressing the Jewish leaders, Dukakis said ``it is
critically important that the world understand who is responsible
for the turmoil and the violence'' of recent weeks between
Palestinians and Israelis.
   ``It is not the generation of young Palestinians who have grown
up in uncertainty, and who have been taught by their elders to
hate,' he said.
   ``It is not a government in Jerusalem that struggles to maintain
order while seeking an opportunity to negotiate with responsible
Arab leaders about the future of the territories,'' Dukakis said.
   ``It is, regretably, Arab leaders themselves who have time and
again rejected the chance to sit down with Israel and negotiate a
permanent peace in the Middle East,'' he said.
   Dukakis cited ``principles'' for policy in the Middle East _
that real progress toward peace will not be made until Arab leaders
``are willing to negotiate directly,'' and until they accept
Israel's right to exist ``within borders that are secure and
defensible.''
   Dukakis cited his own remarks of 11 years ago, saying, ``Israel
needs room to breathe, and a return to the 1967 borders is out of
the question.''
   He later told reporters ``there will have to be some exchange of
land for peace'' but short of a return to Israel's prior borders.
   He said the Palestine Liberation Organization cannot be a Middle
East negotiator ``until it renounces terrorism in word and deed,''
until it accepts UN resolutions 242 and 338, and until it renounces
its own statement that peace ``can only come at the price of
Israel's right to exist.''
   Dukakis said ``I welcome'' Secretary of State George Shultz's
peace initiative while not agreeing ``with evey aspect.''
   Taking questions from the Jewish leaders, Dukakis was asked if
he supports establishment of a Palestinian state. He said that
should be a matter of negotiations between Israel and neighboring
countries.
   He was also asked about the future of Jerusalem and said it too
``has too be subject to negotiation.'' He later told reporters,
``I'm for a united Jerusalem'' under Israeli control.
   Dukakis was asked why he hasn't drawn more distinctions with
Jackson, with one questioner describing Jackson as ``an
anti-Semite.''
   Dukakis said, ``We have differences in the Middle East.'' He
later told reporters, ``I'm not going to characterize any of the
people in this race.''
   He said the next president ``should insist'' that the Soviets
``let Jews and other minorities leave if they wish and let them
worship freely.''
</TEXT>
