<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 2149EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LehderTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0616 04-11 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0616,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Driver Testifies About Lehder Extradition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs after 8th graf ``When their'' to UPDATE with
afternoon testimony. Picks up 9th graf pvs ``When members.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal agent testified Monday in
the cocaine-smuggling trial of Carlos Lehder Rivas that the
investigation began in 1977 when he started following large
expenditures of cash by a member of a Jacksonville gang.
   Soon into the investigation, Ed Ward was identified as the head
of the smuggling organizaton, Drug Enforcement Administration agent
Doug Driver testified.
   Ward, now a convicted drug smuggler, was the key prosecution
witness against Lehder and testified he was the pilot for most of
the cocaine flights listed in the indictment against Lehder.
   Lehder, 38, and co-defendant Jack Carlton Reed, 57, are on trial
on charges they conspired to smuggle some 3.3 tons of cocaine into
the United States from Colombia via the Bahamian island of Norman's
Cay from 1978 to 1980.
   Testimony began Nov. 16.
   In November 1978, Driver, Starratt and a DEA pilot flew to
Norman's Cay to investigate Ward's assets on the island.
   ``We were more or less posing as smugglers ourselves,'' Driver
said, adding that he and the other agent took photographs at Ward's
house and dock, but noticed they were being watched.
   When their plane began to take off, they saw a van on the runway
carrying a man with an automatic weapon, Driver testified.
   Under cross-examination, Driver could not recall what weapons
Bahamian police carried when he visited the island last year.
   ``There is a difference in seeing a weapon in the hands of a
police officer and seeing a weapon in the hands of a thug,'' Driver
told defense attorney Ed Shohat.
   Shohat objected to much of Driver's testimony, claiming it was
hearsay. Driver has been allowed to sit through the testimony of
all witnesses in the trial.
   When members of Ward's smuggling group were indicted in 1981,
Lehder was listed as one of the co-defendants.
   Driver testified that federal officials spent four days in
Bogota meeting with the attorney general of Colombia in 1983 to
seek Lehder's extration to the United States. On the trip were U.S.
Attorney Robert Merkle, Assistant U.S. Attorney Ernst Mueller and
another DEA agent, Bobby Starratt.
   As a result of that visit, an extradition order was signed in
May 1984. Lehder was not arrested until Feb. 4, 1987.
   Driver also testified about the arrest in Haiti of Ward's
smuggling group, and said that on their flight back to Jacksonville
about a DC-3 the group began singing ``Homeward Bound'' and
commercial jingles.
   The jury also was shown a videotape taken last April on a visit
to Norman's Cay by Merkle, Mueller and Driver that showed the
island had become nearly deserted.
   Introduced into evidence Monday were address and telephone books
confiscated in a raid on Reed's house in February 1987.
   The books contained phone numbers for Lehder in Colombia, plus
the names of others identified in the trial.
   Lehder is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a
continuing criminal enterprise. A separate Miami indictment accuses
him of being one of the leaders of the Medellin cartel, which
officials say is responsible for about 80 percent of the cocaine
shipments into the United States.
   Reed, of San Pedro, Calif., is charged with only being a member
of the smuggling conspiracy.
</TEXT>
