<DOCNO> AP880411-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 2156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Oscars-Scene     04-11 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oscars-Scene,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Oscars, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thousands Of Movie Buffs Flock To The Shrine</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood's reigning royalty turned out
Monday evening in basic black and white with a few dashes of color
as elegance replaced glitz for the 60th annual Academy Awards _
except for Cher.
   The star of ``Moonstruck,'' who arrived fashionably late,
knocked the scream meter off the scale when she stepped from her
limousine outside the Shrine Auditorium in an almost-not-there
diaphanous gown, only partly covered by a dark black cape.
   But Cher was one of the exceptions to the rule.
   Actress Liza Minnelli typified this year's style with a bright
red cape draped over a long crepe black dress, while Marlee Matlin
exemplified the few bright exceptions, wearing a strapless,
knee-length purple dress with a large bow hanging from her side.
   Perennial Edie Williams wore a bikini top over a pale blue mini
skirt and sported a puppy on one shoulder, but the rest of the
turnout at the cavernous Shrine Auditorium exercised good taste and
classic styling.
   Fifteen minutes before showtime, actresses Meryl Streep and
Glenn Close, nine months pregnant and aided by a cane, were seen
marching quickly up Jefferson Boulevard to the theater in an effort
to make it to the Academy Awards on time.
   Protesters on Jefferson Boulevard included Bible-thumping
Christians carrying signs reading ``Movie Idolaters Repent,''
``Fear God'' and ``Repent or Perish.''
   Guardian Angel leader Curtis Sliwa and his self-declared band of
red-bereted crimebusters chanted alongside the Christians and
marched around mock caskets in protest of Friday's release of the
realistic police gang movie ``Colors.''
   Los Angeles police are in the midst of a declared war against
gangs, and Sliwa said the motion picture will incite more violence.
``It shouldn't be released now at the height of the storm,'' he
said.
   Many Oscar guests in limousines and passenger cars gave Sliwa
and his troops thumbs up signs of approval as they passed.
   Fans in the bleachers were whipped up by Oscar greeter and
columnist Army Archerd who conducted an impromptu fan poll. The
best picture winner on the applause meter was ``Moonstruck.''
   In the middle of the bleachers were seven Glenn Close
lookalikes, with frizzy blonde hair and wearing ``Fatal
Attraction'' T-shirts.
</TEXT>
