<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 2215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hijack-Security     04-11 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijack-Security,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hijackers of Kuwaiti Jet May Have Smuggled Weapons Through Service
Ramp</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The weapons aboard a hijacked Kuwaiti airliner
may have been smuggled aboard in Bangkok through the ramp area used
by caterers and cleaning crews, an International Air Transport
Association official said Monday.
   ``On the basis of discussions we've had so far, the probability
is weapons were placed on board the aircraft through the coercion
or collusion of staff on the ramp,'' said Rodney Wallis, head of
security for the association.
   Caterers, engineers, cleaners and loaders all have access to the
ramp area where the cabin of the Kuwait Airways Boeing 747 was
serviced and cleaned before it left Bangkok on Tuesday, he said.
   Thai authorities have not completed their investigation, he
added.
   There are believed to be at least five Arab hijackers on board
the jumbo jet, which was commandeered Tuesday on its way to Kuwait
and has been sitting on the tarmac in Larnaca, Cyprus, since Friday.
   The hijackers have killed two passengers and threatened to kill
the remaining passengers if authorities do not fulfill their demand
that the plane be refueled. About 45 hostages are being held.
   Wallis said he thought the weapons were placed on board through
the ramp area because it is highly unlikely five people could take
guns and grenades through security gates at Bangkok airport.
   The International Air Transport Association is a Montreal-based
international association of commercial airlines.
   ``The initial reaction of the Thais was, `it couldn't have
happened here,''' Wallis added. ``But the most logical place for it
to have happened was while it was on the ground in Thailand; it was
on the ground there for a considerable period.''
   Paul Sheppard, head of the security section of the International
Civil Aviation Organization, said the operation was obviously well
planned and the weapons could have been smuggled aboard any number
of ways.
   Security ``is like a great spider web over the whole world, and
there's no way of plugging up every single little gap,'' said
Sheppard. ``The chain of security is only as strong as its weakest
link.''
   The plane was bound for Kuwait from Bangkok on April 5 when it
was seized by the hijackers, who demanded the release of
pro-Iranian terrorists imprisoned in Kuwait.
   The jumbo jet was forced to land in northeastern Iran, where 57
people were released. The aircraft then left Iran and landed in
Larnaca on Friday after being refused permission to land in Lebanon
and Syria.
   The Montreal-based International Civil Aviation Organization is
a United Nations agency that sets international standards and
regulations for safe air transportation.
</TEXT>
