<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Sikhs     04-11 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Radicals Rule Out Talks, Except on Independence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Sikh extremist groups on Monday ruled
out peace talks with the government unless they focus on the
radicals' demand for an independent nation.
   Also Monday, police reported five more people killed in the
6-year-old guerrilla war for a Sikh homeland in the northern state
of Punjab. Authorities have blamed Sikh extremists for killing
nearly 700 people, mostly Hindus and moderate Sikhs, since the
start of the year.
   The five-member Panthic Committee and its 11-member Council of
Khalistan, a subgroup, said Monday that anyone who negotiated with
the government and did not demand Sikh independence would be killed.
   ``No one will be allowed to negotiate with New Delhi for less
than Khalistan,'' the Panthic Committee said, using the name Sikh
extremists have given to their would-be nation.
   ``The struggle for Khalistan is being fought in an organized
manner, and whosoever comes between the Sikhs and Khalistan will be
taken care of,'' the group announced in a statement at the Golden
Temple in Amritsar, the holiest shrine for Sikhs.
   Jagar Singh, a spokesman for the groups, read their statements.
Members of both the Panthic Committee, formed in 1986, and the
Council of Khalistan, created in October, generally operate
underground. Many of them are wanted on sedition and murder charges
by the government.
   The Panthic Committee claims it is the official voice of the
Sikh separatists, and has rejected the authority of traditional
Sikh institutions.
   The Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, claim they are discriminated
against by India's majority Hindus. Sikhs make up less than 2
percent of India's 800 million people but constitute a majority in
Punjab.
   Indian government officials have repeatedly said they are
willing to discuss grievances of the Sikh community but ruled out
any discussion of independence.
   The militants' statements came a day after Jasbir Singh Rode,
chief priest at the Golden Temple, told the United News of India
that he was willing to explore negotiations with the government.
But he said militants ``do not seem interested in talks with the
government at present.''
   The separatists' statements appeared aimed at undercutting Rode,
who has called for a gathering of Sikh faithful on Wednesday in
southern Punjab.
   The Council of Khalistan's statement reiterated an assertion by
several militant groups that the radicals were not responsible for
the recent surge in attacks on Sikh families.
   The statement blamed the attacks on ``the black cat commando
force,'' a special unit created to guard Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi. It said the slayings of Sikh moderates were aimed at
discrediting the militant movement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
