<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0708 04-11 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers Demonstrate Against Government</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 5th graf pvs, ``Pinepple face ... to
UPDATE with meeting between government and U.S. executives. Picks
up 6th graf pvs, ``If we ...; minor editing to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of teachers demonstrated
Monday against Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega as
Panama slid further toward chaos in the seventh week of an economic
and political crisis.
   American business executives tried to figure out how they were
affected by new U.S. sanctions that could cost Panama millions of
dollars.
   The sanctions prohibit U.S. businesses from making payments,
including taxes, to the Panamanian government. Panama is virtually
bankrupt because of a run on its banks, the freezing of Panamanian
deposits in U.S. banks and a variety of American sanctions aimed at
forcing Noriega to resign.
   Protesting teachers, who along with 100,000 other public
employees have not been paid fully in more than a month, gathered
in front of the Ministry of Education and shouted anti-Noriega
slogans for several hours before dispersing without incident.
   ``Pineapple face, you must go,'' they cried in a mocking
reference to Noriega's jowly, pockmarked face.
   Commerce and Industries Minister Mario Rognoni said Monday after
a meeting with more than 30 representatives of American companies
that Panama planned to be flexible with firms affected by the U.S.
sanctions.
   However, he said if the companies do not pay utility bills
because of the U.S. executive order, their services would be cut.
   ``It is a delicate situation for which we are looking for a way
to help the American companies continue operating in Panama,'' he
said.
   Fred Denton, executive director of the American Chamber of
Commerce in Panama City, said he had received numerous calls from
representatives of U.S. firms asking how the tax sanctions would be
applied.
   ``If we take this to the letter of the law, I wouldn't be able
to buy a Panamanian postage stamp,'' Denton said. ``We're in a
complete state of confusion.''
   President Reagan on Friday invoked the sweeping economic
sanctions law against Panama to force the ouster of Noriega, the
commander of the 15,000-member Defense Forces and the power behind
the civilian government.
   The Treasury Department in Washington was expected to issue
guidelines this week covering the sanctions imposed under the 1977
International Emergency Economic Powers Act.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater defended
the steps as an attempt to deny Noriega ``money that could be used
to perpetuate his stay in power.''
   Noriega repeated his claim that the U.S. actions are an attempt
by Washington to renege on the treaty that will turn over full
control of the Panama Canal to his country at the turn of the
century.
   ``They want to rewrite history, cancel the treaties by imposing
a government controlled by them and reversing the social
achievements made since 1968,'' he told the Paris newspaper Le
Monde in an interview published Monday.
   Asked if his departure from the country would end the crisis and
alleviate the suffering of Panamanians, Noriega said: ``If the
people are suffering, it is because of the United States, not me.''
   Panama's crisis began when Noriega had the National Legislature
depose President Eric Arturo Delvalle on Feb. 26, the day after
Delvalle tried to fire the general. The United States still
considers Delvalle the legal head of state.
   Noriega is under federal indictment in the United States on drug
trafficking charges, which he denies.
   In Caracas, Venezuela, a Panamanian opposition leader forced
into exile said Panama will start running out of basic foodstuffs
in days and such a shortage could lead to the ``final push'' to
remove Noriega.
   Carlos Gonzalez de la Lastra arrived in Caracas Sunday night
from Panama City after 11 days in prison. He was imprisoned after
leading a protest march and said authorities told him he could
either remain in jail or go into exile.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Gonzalez urged Latin
American nations to abandon their opposition to U.S. economic
pressures designed to remove Noriega.
   ``We have been successful in that in ten months we have taken
away all Noriega's support without shedding blood. What he needs
now is a final push, and this could be when the economic situation
grows sharply worse in the next few weeks, basically for a lack of
food,'' he said.
</TEXT>
