<HEAD>Medical Critic Dead at 61</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 2nd to add reference to column.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Robert Mendelsohn, an author, teacher
and critic of the medical establishment, is dead at age 61.
   Mendelsohn, who died April 5 at his home in Evanston after a
brief illness, wrote the books ``Confessions of a Medical
Heretic,'' published in 1979, and ``How to Raise a Healthy Child In
Spite of Your Doctor,'' published in 1984.
   Mendelsohn also wrote a syndicated newspaper column, `The
People's Doctor.''
   ``He was probably the nation's most vocal critic of organized
medicine,'' said Jay Hathaway, executive director of the Bradley
Method of Natural Childbirth, a California-based group on whose
advisory board Mendelsohn served.
   ``He served as a kind of catalyst for many different
organizations'' that question medical orthodoxy, Hathaway said.
``My favorite quote of his is, `You should kick the hospital habit
at birth.'''
   Mendelsohn was a professor and instructor of pediatrics at the
University of Illinois and Northwestern University. He also taught
at Loyola University medical school.
   He was a former director of development at Chicago's Michael
Reese Hospital and a former national director of Project Head
Start's medical consultation service.
   Mendelsohn is survived by his wife, two daughters and six
grandchildren, his mother and two brothers.
</TEXT>
