<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 2258EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Terrorists     04-11 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Terrorists,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Reportedly May Reduce Sentences of Jewish Terrorists</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Chaim Herzog may further reduce the
sentences of three leaders of a Jewish terror group that operated
for four years in the occupied territories, Israel radio reported
Monday.
   Herzog's spokesman, Ami Gluska, said in a written statement that
``all such reports are baseless.''
   The radio said the president is considering reducing the
sentences of Menachem Livni, Shaul Nir and Uzi Sharbaf, Jewish
settlers who staged a gun and grenade attack at the Hebron Islamic
College that killed three Palestinians and wounded 33 in August
1983.
   They were sentenced to life in prison in July 1985 but Herzog
reduced their punishment last year to 24 years each. Several
right-wing political leaders have appealed to Herzog to pardon the
men.
   The radio said the president was considering a further reduction
of their terms in honor of Israel's 40th anniversary.
   The three settlers were among 25 arrested in 1984 and charged
with planning and conducting six attacks against Arabs in the
territories captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East War.
   On April 1, Herzog ordered the freedom of two other people
convicted of taking part in the group's activities. Gluska called
the move part of ``a general trend to reduce sentences in the
framework of the 40th year of the state.''
   One of those freed was New York-born Ira Rappaport, who was
serving a two-year sentence for helping to plant a bomb in the car
of then-Nablus Mayor Bassam Shaka in 1980. Shaka lost his legs in
the attack.
</TEXT>
