<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 2302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Unrest     04-11 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Unrest,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Killed In Unrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three black men were fatally
shot and the fourth was stabbed to death in separate attacks near
the southeastern coastal city of Durban, police said Monday.
   The killings in the Hammersdale area outside Durban were
announced in the Monday morning police report which covers
incidents during the previous 24 hours. The report gave no
additional details on the killings.
   At least 16 people were injured by guns, knives and fighting
when rioting broke out Sunday at an overcrowded black music
festival in Durban, police said.
   Police said they fired shots in an attempt to control the crowd
at Kings Park rugby stadium, which seats 50,000. Approximately
120,000 people attended the festival, which began at midday and
lasted about six hours despite the scattered violence.
   Black unrest has declined sharply in South Africa in the past
year.
   The only area reporting regular flare-ups in recent months has
been the southeastern city of Pietermaritzburg, where about 500
people have died in black factional feuding since the beginning of
1987.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
