<HEAD>Suspect in Double Murder Arrested in Manhattan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 31-year-old man accused in a double murder in
Pennsylvania slightly injured three New York City police officers
who stopped him in a pickup truck that had been reported stolen,
authorities said Monday.
   Arthur Faulkner of Philadelphia tried to flee then used a
folding knife against pursuing officers in an attempt to fend off
arrest Sunday night, police spokesman Sgt. Ed Burns said.
   Faulkner was charged with auto theft, resisting arrest and
criminal possession of a deadly weapon, Burns said. The three
officers were treated and released at a local hospital.
   Faulkner is wanted on a murder warrant in Pennsylvania in the
April 1 stabbing deaths of Clarice J. Dorner, 30, and Annaliese H.
Killoran, 22, at an archaeological workshop outside Philadelphia.
   Faulkner, a laborer at the site, is also accused of stabbing and
wounding the supervisor of the archaeological study, Glenn W.
Sheehan, 39, and Sheehan's pregnant wife, Anne M. Jensen, 31.
</TEXT>
