<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 2338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iraq-PoisonGas     04-11 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Poison Gas,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fifteen Iraqi Soldiers Flown to London, Vienna for Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq flew 15 Iraqi soldiers to England, Austria
and West Germany on Monday for treatment of wounds it said the men
suffered from Iranian chemical weapons during fighting last month.
   The soldiers were sent to European hospitals two weeks after
Iran flew about two dozen civilians to medical facilities in
Western Europe and New York. The Tehran government said they were
victims of Iraqi poison gas attacks in a March 16-17 battle over
Halabja and two other Kurdish town that had been capturd by the
Iranians.
   Iran has repeatedly accused Iraq of using chemical weapons in
the war that began September 1980.
   Iraqi officials denied their country was sending wounded to
Europe to counter the Iranian claims.
   ``We bring the proof now that our soldiers have been hit'' with
chemical weapons, Iraqi Embassy spokesman Abdul N. Isa told The
Associated Press in London. Iraq has said 88 of its soldiers were
wounded in an Iranian poison gas attack in the Halabja fighting.
   Iran has repeatedly denied its forces have used chemical
warfare, which is outlawed by international conventions.
   Five Iraqi soldiers arrived at London's London's Heathrow
Airport on a chartered Saudi Arabian jet for treatment at Brompton
Hospital, a private clinic in west London.
   Four doctors accompanied the injured. The soldiers, on
stretchers, were wrapped tightly in blankets and only their faces,
some burned, were visible.
   Iraqi Ambassador Mohammed Sadiq al-Mashat was at the airport to
meet them.
   Ten Iraqi soldiers were flown to Vienna aboard a special Saudi
Arabian flight.
   Five were admitted to Vienna's General Hospital and officials
said the five others were flown on to West Germany for treatment.
   The Austria Press Agency said the men taken to the Vienna
hospital were not in critical condition.
   They were met at by Iraqi Ambassador Wahdi Al-Qaraguli who said
the cost of their treatement would be paid for by his government.
   Twelve days ago, the British Foreign Office indicated it
believed Iraq had used poison gas in the fighting at Halabja and
filed a protest with the Iraqi ambassador.
   Iran has said 5,000 people were killed and 5,000 injured by
Iraqi chemical weapons in the fighting for the Kurdish towns.
</TEXT>
