<DOCNO> AP880411-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 2345EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0682 04-11 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0682,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Moves Farther From Arafat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 4 grafs after 16th graf pvs, bgng: Later, an xxx to
UPDATE with labor rally</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, referring to Yasser Arafat as one
of the ``most extreme elements'' in the Israeli-Palestinian
conflict, called Monday on Jewish and Arab Americans to start
Middle East peace talks in the United States.
   ``Talks can, in fact, begin right here in this country,''
Jackson said.
   His proposal came as the New York presidential primary campaign
entered its final week.
   Nearly one quarter of the Democratic electorate on April 19 will
be Jewish and for many of those voters, the future of Israel is a
critical issue.
   Jackson appeared to be reaching out to Jewish voters on Sunday
when he declared that as president he would not meet with Arafat,
whom he has been criticized for meeting several years ago.
   At a breakfast meeting on Monday, he also ridiculed suggestions
that he would come under greater scrutiny as a result of the
electoral successes that have placed him only a handful of
delegates behind Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts in the
Democratic race.
   Running third in the three-candidate race was Sen. Albert Gore
Jr. of Tennessee.
   Jackson, the former civil rights activist, said there had been
suggestions that the news media and the other candidates would get
tough with him.
   ``Well, get tough,'' he said. ``Who else has a budget for
fighting the drug crisis?
   ``Who else has a budget deficit plan?
   ``Who else has significant foreign policy experience?''
   And then he said, ``I look forward to tougher days.''
   Jackson was asked about Arafat and he said, ``It would not be a
good approach to start at the table with the most extreme elements
_ that's a formula for catastrophe.''
   Instead, he said, ``In this city some of your top Palestinian
leaders in the world live. Some of your top Jewish-American and
pro-Israeli leaders live. We should begin to talk here, to implore
both sides to a higher level of security.''
   He brushed aside questions about whether he would meet with the
Council of Presidents of Major Jewish Organizations, a group
Dukakis spoke to on Monday. He said he also was addressing concerns
of Haitians living in New York, of people from the Caribbean, as
well as of Italian and Irish Americans.
   Later, an aide said Jackson had no room on his schedule to meet
with the Jewish group.
   Monday evening, labor leaders and the rank and file turned out
in force at a labor rally in support of Jackson's candidacy.
   The candidate was interrupted repeatedly with shouts of ``Win,
Jesse, Win!'' _ an updated version of the ``Run, Jesse, Run!''
slogan chanted during his unsuccessful first run for president in
1984.
   Jackson told about 5,000 supporters at the Jacob K. Javits
Convention Center that blue-collar workers ``will have a friend in
the White House'' if he becomes president.
   Jackson reminded the crowd, which represented a wide
cross-section of the labor movement, that he has stood with them
many times on picket lines, and asked them to stand with him now by
supporting his candidacy.
   Jackson also campaigned north of the city, addressing a rally at
Rockland Community College and greeting workers at a General Motors
plant in North Tarrytown.
   At the college he urged students to ``seize that leadership. ...
Young America must lead.''
   At the GM plant he sounded his familiar theme of battling
economic violence and told the workers, ``We built our campaign at
the plant gate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
