<NOTE>$adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, April 21</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Today is Thursday, April 21, the 112th day of 1988. There are
254 days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On April 21, 1836, an army of Texans led by Sam Houston defeated
the Mexicans at San Jacinto, assuring the independence of Texas.
   On this date:
   In 753 B.C., according to legend, Rome was founded.
   In 1649, the Maryland Toleration Act, which provided for freedom
of worship for all Christians, was passed by the Maryland Assembly.
   In 1789, John Adams was sworn in as the first vice president of
the United States.
   In 1816, author Charlotte Bronte, who wrote ``Jane Eyre,'' was
born in Thornton, England.
   In 1910, author Samuel Langhorne Clemens, better known as Mark
Twain, died in Redding, Conn.
   In 1918, Baron Manfred von Richthofen _ the German ace known as
the ``Red Baron'' _ was killed in action during World War I.
   In 1940, the quiz show that asked the ``$64 question,'' ``Take
It or Leave It,'' premiered on CBS radio.
   In 1967, Svetlana Alliluyeva, daughter of Soviet leader Josef
Stalin, rrived in New York.
   In 1972, Apollo 16 astronauts John W. Young and Charles M. Duke
explored the surface of the moon.
   In 1975, South Vietnamese President Nguyen Van Thieu resigned
after 10 years in office.
   In 1976, full-scale testing of the swine flu vaccine began in
Washington.
   In 1977, the musical play ``Annie,'' based on the ``Little
Orphan Annie'' comic strip, opened on Broadway with Andrea McArdle
in the title role. (The show closed Jan. 2, 1983, after 2,377
performances.)
   In 1986, the United States, Britain and France vetoed a U.N.
Security Council resolution condemning the U.S. air raid on Libya.
   Ten years ago: Former first lady Betty Ford, undergoing
treatment at Long Beach Memorial Naval Hospital in California,
disclosed in a statement that she was addicted to alcohol as well
as a drug she had been taking for arthritis.
   Five years ago: Yielding to a massive letter-writing campaign
promoted by the banking industry, the U.S. Senate voted 91-5 to
repeal President Reagan's plan for withholding taxes from interest
and dividends.
   One year ago: The Senate panel investigating the Iran-Contra
affair voted to grant limited immunity to President Reagan's former
national security adviser, Rear Adm. John M. Poindexter.
   Today's Birthdays: Former California Gov. Edmund G. ``Pat''
Brown is 83. Actor Anthony Quinn is 73. Britain's Queen Elizabeth
II is 62. Actress-comedian-writer Elaine May is 56. Actor Charles
Grodin is 53. Actress Patti LuPone is 39. Actor Tony Danza is 37.
   Thought for Today: ``All say, `How hard it is to die' -- a
strange complaint to come from the mouths of people who have had to
live.'' -- Mark Twain (1835-1910).
</TEXT>
