<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Taiwan-Oldsters Adv18   04-11 0807</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Oldsters, Adv 18,0829</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs April 18 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Taiwan's Geriatric Parliament Set For Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the geriatric world of Taiwan's
Parliament, lawmakers have been dying this year at the rate of two
a month, and the Young China Party has a representative who is 74.
   The Legislative Yuan, the highest of the three lawmaking
branches of Parliament, is populated by scores of octagenarians and
nonagenarians elected in 1948 on the Chinese mainland. Many are
hospitalized today and cannot attend sessions, including
97-year-old Chao Chu-hsu, the senior member.
   Six members died in the first three months of 1988, lowering to
306 the number of mainland-elected lawmakers still in the 884-seat
body at the end of March.
   The aging lawmakers were part of the Chiang Kai-shek's
Nationalist mainland government, which was forced to flee to Taiwan
a year later by the victory of Mao Tse-Tung's Communists in the
civil war. Chiang died in 1975 at the age of 87, and Mao died in
1976 at 83.
   The Nationalist leaders on Taiwan still claim to be the rightful
rulers of all China and have frozen the lawmakers elected in 1948
into office until the government can return to the mainland to hold
new elections. Starting in 1969, however, Taiwanese were allowed
seats in the legislature.
   But with native Taiwanese seeking a greater say in today's
government and the mainland-elected lawmakers becoming increasingly
feeble, the Nationalists are facing calls to take the gray out of
the Legislative Yuan.
   ``Over the past 40 years the (Nationalist Party) has never paid
enough attention to the voice of the people,'' said Chu Kao-cheng,
a lawmaker from the opposition Democratic Progressive Party. ``The
whole constitutional structure is distorted and destroyed.''
   In February, the Nationalist Party, or Kuomintang, proposed
voluntary retirement for the remaining mainland-elected lawmakers
and an increase in the number of seats open for election on Taiwan,
which now stands at 73. The proposal also would apply to the
934-seat National Assembly, the branch that meets every six years
to choose Taiwan's president. The other legislative branch is the
Control Yuan, which serves as a watchdog.
   The opposition party has denounced the Nationalist plan,
however, arguing that all seats, including those of the
mainlanders, should be open for election.
   In the meantime, Chu and 11 other opposition party members
elected in 1986 are making life miserable for the aging lawmakers.
Most of the mainland-elected members belong to the Nationalist
Party but some belong to smaller groups, including 74-year-old Liu
Tzu-peng of the Young China Party.
   Democratic Progressive Party lawmakers constantly refer to the
elderly members as ``old thieves.'' They also get into fights with
the Nationalists, rip apart furniture and generally cause chaos
whenever possible during Legislative Yuan sessions.
   The 33-year-old Chu's exploits in this have earned him the
nickname ``Rambo'' in the local media.
   On April 7, Chu stormed the Legislative Yuan podium to stop a
vote on the budget. He wound up in a wild melee with several
Nationalists that resulted in a decision to provide the Legislative
Yuan's aging president and vice president with bodyguards.
   The mass-circulation United Daily News said that among those who
punched and kicked Chu during the scuffle were several elderly
Nationalist lawmakers who ``had suppressed their displeasure for
too long.''
   Opposition lawmakers recently have taken to the streets to
protest the ``10,000-year Parliament'' and in March led a group of
more than 1,000 people to a walled suburban compound where many of
the aging Nationalists live. At least 16 people were reported
injured when demonstrators clashed with the security forces.
   Opposition party members also have publicized the telephone
numbers of mainland-elected representatives and have urged people
to call them to demand they retire.
   Nationalist lawmaker Chang Hung-hsueh, 72, said he receives one
or two calls late each night. Some callers curse while others
remain silent, he said. He added that he receives paper money
traditionally offered to the dead with his name on it.
   ``This is shameful (and) mean, but it does not bother me,''
Chang said in a recent interview. He said he always replies to the
callers with a polite: ``Thank you. I am still alive.''
   Chang believes that holding elections in Taiwan for the entire
Legislative Yuan would be unconstitutional on grounds that it would
become a local lawmaking body. His belief is shared by other
mainland-elected representatives.
   But reform of the parliamentary system was firmly pushed by
President Chiang Ching-kuo, Chiang Kai-shek's son who died at the
age of 77 in January, as part of his sweeping policy to introduce
democratic change to the island.
   His successor, President Lee Teng-hui, is a firm supporter of
the voluntary retirement package and final details are expected to
be announced in coming months.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs April 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
