<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv17,0433</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Today is Sunday, April 17, the 108th day of 1988. There are 258
days left in the year.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
      Today's Highlight in History:
   On April 17, 1961, about 1,500 CIA-trained Cuban exiles launched
the disastrous Bay of Pigs invasion of Cuba in an attempt to
overthrow the government of Fidel Castro. The invasion failed, and
the survivors were captured.
   On this date:
   In 1492, a contract was signed between Christopher Columbus and
Spain to seek a westward ocean passage to Asia.
   In 1521, Martin Luther went before the Diet of Worms to face
charges stemming from his religious writings.
   In 1524, Giovanni da Verrazano discovered New York harbor.
   In 1790, Benjamin Franklin died in Philadelphia at the age of 84.
   In 1861, the Virginia State Convention voted to secede from the
Union.
   In 1941, Yugoslavia surrendered to Germany in World War II.
   In 1964, Jerrie Mock of Columbus, Ohio, became the first woman
to complete a solo airplane flight around the world.
   In 1969, Sirhan Sirhan was convicted of assassinating Sen.
Robert F. Kennedy.
   In 1969, Czechoslovakia's Communist Party chairman Alexander
Dubcek was deposed.
   In 1975, Phnom Penh fell to Communist insurgents, ending
Cambodia's 5-year war.
   In 1984, gunfire erupted from the Libyan embassy in London at a
group of anti-Gadhafi demonstrators. The shots killed a
policewoman, Yvonne Fletcher, and wounded eleven others.
   In 1986, the bodies of American librarian Peter Kilburn and two
Britons were found near Beirut. The three hostages had been slain
apparently in retaliation for the U.S. raid on Libya.
   Ten years ago: Bill Rodgers won his second Boston Marathon,
completing the 26-mile course in 2:10:13. Gayle Barron of Atlanta
was the first woman across the finish line in 2:44:52.
   Five years ago: In Warsaw, Poland, police routed 1,000
Solidarity supporters participating in an unofficial ceremony
marking the 40th anniversary of the Warsaw ghetto uprising.
   One year ago: President Reagan slapped $300 million in punitive
duties on imported Japanese computers, television sets and power
tools, in retaliation for Japan's alleged violation of a computer
chip trade agreement.
   Today's Birthdays: CBS News correspondent Harry Reasoner is 65.
Movie and theatrical director Lindsay Anderson is 65. Rock promoter
Don Kirshner is 54.
   Thought for Today: ``The history of the world is the record of a
man in quest of his daily bread and butter.'' -- Hendrik Willem van
Loon, Dutch-born American journalist (1882-1944).
   End Adv
</TEXT>
</DOC>
