<1ST_LINE>a i AM-IrishHostage Adv15   04-11 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish Hostage, Adv 15,0810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>adv15</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, April 15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Family Awaits for Word of Irishman Missing Two Years in Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two years after Brian Keenan
disappeared in Beirut, his mother and two sisters say they too have
become hostages to unknown kidnappers.
   ``If they could only let us know whether he's alive or dead _
even if he's dead, it would be better than hoping all the time,''
said his younger sister, Elaine Spence.
   Despite petitions and appeals to the Lebanese people and the
Iranian and Syrian governments, no group has claimed responsibility
for the disappearance of the 37-year-old teacher, who is a citizen
of the Irish republic to the south even though he was born and
lived in Northern Ireland.
   Keenan rushed out of his apartment April 11, 1986, late for an 8
a.m. lecture at the American University in Beirut where he had
taught for four months.
   His mistake, the family believes, was to forget his Irish
passport.
   They believe he was kidnapped by people who may have thought he
was American or British, rather than a citizen of a small neutral
country.
   Ireland's only involvement in the Middle East is through aid
groups and its contingent in the United Nations peacekeeping force
in Lebanon.
   Immediately after Keenan disappeared, the Irish government in
Dublin issued photographs of his passport and repeatedly broadcast
that he was an Irish citizen, raising the family's hopes that he
might be released quickly.
   But two years later, Keenan remains the only Irishman among the
22 foreigners missing in Lebanon.
   His family is resigned to an indefinite wait for his return.
   ``We still feel he's alive and we're not going to give up
hope,'' said his older sister, Brenda Gillham. ``We never thought
it would last as long as this, but we're going to keep on fighting
until we see him released.''
   Ireland's ambassador to Iraq, Patrick McCabe, who is also
accredited as the envoy to Lebanon, was quoted in Dublin's Sunday
Press newspaper April 3 as saying: ``People we have talked to do
not think Mr. Keenan is dead.'' He added, the newspaper reported,
that hostages could be held for years without their captors making
contact, and ``that gives us some hope.''
   The only reported sighting of Keenan came from a French hostage,
Camille Sontag, 85, who was freed in November 1986. He said one of
the five Westerners held with him in an underground prison in south
Beirut by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems slipped him a piece of paper
on which was written: ``I am Irish. Please tell my family.''
   Keenan's sisters and his 65-year-old mother, Minnie, were
encouraged by Sontag's message, but disheartened this past March
when Nabih Berri, leader of the Lebanese Amal militia, said that
because he had heard nothing about Keenan, he feared him dead.
   A photograph of Keenan and a scrapbook of news clippings about
all the hostages in Lebanon have a special place in Mrs. Gillham's
tidy living room in a state-subsidized development in east Belfast.
   ``It's not only the hostage himself that's held, his family's
held hostage as well,'' she said. ``In our own home, you're afraid
to go out in case the phone rings. If you go out for a night out,
you feel guilty, the fact that you might be trying to enjoy
yourselves and Brian's sitting in a cell somewhere.''
   Belfast-born Keenan had lived in the turmoil of sectarian strife
that has gripped Northern Ireland for nearly 20 years.
   A Protestant, he chose to become a citizen of predominantly
Roman Catholic Ireland rather than of Britain, which governs the
province. Everyone born in Northern Ireland has the option of
becoming a citizen of either.
   In addition to teaching, Keenan was a community worker for the
Belfast City Council.
   ``He has many Protestant and Catholic friends,'' said Mrs.
Gillham. ``He tried to build communication on both sides. He loved
his country.''
   Mrs. Spence said the family did not want his kidnapping to
become a political issue.
   In December, two senior officials from Sinn Fein, the legal
political wing of the outlawed Irish Republican Army, went to
Beirut without the family's knowledge to try to win Keenan's
freedom.
   Mrs. Gillham said it was the similarities between Northern
Ireland and Lebanon that attracted her bearded, easy-going brother
to Beirut.
   ``When he told me he was going, I said to him, `Are you sure you
know what you're doing? It's like going from the frying pan into
the fire.'
   ``But as Brian said, there's a war there. There's a war here at
home and life has to go on.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, April 15</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880411-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Germany-Spies Adv18   04-11 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Spies, Adv 18,0755</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>West Germany Says Communist Spies Still Flocking In</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even though East-West relations have
thawed, communist espionage is on the rise in West Germany and
probably is aimed more at high-tech industrial secrets than
military or political ones, officials say.
   West Germany has been infested with communist spies since its
creation in 1949 in the ashes of World War II. The spying has
ranged from East German truck drivers rolling through the
countryside to moles in the highest of government offices.
   Among the most important spies caught were Guenter Guillaume,
who wrecked Chancellor Willy Brandt's government in 1974; Margret
Hoeke, who was a secretary to five presidents; and Manfred Rotsch,
who delivered top-secret NATO documents to the Soviets.
   But just last month, West German federal police arrested 11
people suspected of working for the KGB, the Soviet intelligence
agency, and are investigating others.
   ``The large number of arrests confirms that instead of
refraining from activating agents in a time of detente, the East
bloc is intensifying its espionage activities,'' Interior Minister
Friedrich Zimmermann told reporters after the March sweep.
   Hans-Gert Lange, spokesman for the Office for the Protection of
the Constitution, West Germany's counter-espionage agency, said
warmer East-West relations increase the opportunities for spying.
   ``The thaw has increased interest in obtaining information, and
also improved conditions for espionage,'' Lange said in an
interview at his Cologne office.
   Lange added that because some communist countries have loosened
emigration restrictions, a danger increases that agents have been
planted among the refugees.
   ``Emigration plays an important role in espionage in the Federal
Republic (West Germany), as has been shown by the arrest of the
suspected KGB agents,'' Lange said.
   Among the 11 suspects arrested in March were four Soviet emigres.
   With communist research lagging behind the West in many areas,
Soviet bloc agents have intensified their efforts to obtain secrets
from private companies in science and high-tech fields, Lange said.
   ``The interest in political secrets is still great, but for
technological and scientific matters it has grown considerably,''
Lange said.
   Security officials estimate that as many as 3,000 spies are at
work in West Germany, most of them from East Germany. Between 30
and 50 suspected spies are arrested each year, the
counter-intelligence office says.
   Secretaries and other government employees in Bonn, the nation's
capital, are among those who have been caught.
   Also, security officials have long suspected that East German
truckers driving through West Germany report on military movements
and gather other information for the East German secret service.
   But a spy can come from anywhere.
   West Germany automatically grants citizenship to all ethnic
German refugees from the East bloc, making the task of isolating
communist agents extremely difficult.
   In addition, West Germany and East Germany have improved
relations over the past few years, resulting in more contacts
between the two sides and greater chances for espionage.
   East German authorities have allowed the resettling of its
citizens to West Germany to increase dramatically, reaching a high
of 30,000 in 1984, compared to just 7,000 the year before,
according to federal statistics.
   Past spy scandals have damaged the nation's image among other
NATO allies.
   West Germany arrested 16 communist agents in 1976 after cracking
East German infiltration methods. But it turned out that two of the
spies, Lothar-Erwin Lutze and his wife Renate, had been passing
NATO documents to East Germany since the 1960s. West German Defense
Minister Georg Leber resigned over that scandal.
   In 1974, Guenter Guillaume, a close aide to Chancellor Brandt,
was exposed as an East German agent, and Brandt resigned.
   Guillaume began serving a 13-year jail sentence in 1975 _ the
longest ever given by a West German court to a convicted spy _ but
he was released six years later in an exchange of agents with East
Germany.
   In 1985, the Constititution Protection Office itself was rocked
by the defection to East Germany of Hans-Joachim Tiedge, who headed
an agency group responsible for catching East German spies.
   Security officials believe many of the communist agents in West
Germany now can do only minor damage.
   ``But one must be careful when one uses the term `small fish',''
said Lange. ``A small fish can always become a bigger one.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
