<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1355EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-APN--SchoolReforms Adv24-1stAdd   04-11 0776</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--School Reforms, Adv 24-1st Add,0794</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv24</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 24</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: Bennett said.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bell takes no comfort from the education rhetoric he has heard
from the presidential candidates, including promises from both
George Bush and Michael Dukakis that they will be ``the education
president.''
   ``We should be asking the presidential candidates: `If elected,
what do you plan to do to lead the nation into a truly great
education system and to transform America into a learning
society?'''
   Even before it was published, ``The Thirteenth Man'' made
headlines with Bell's claim that he heard ``mid-level right-wing
staffers in the White House and at OMB'' make racist jokes and
ethnic slurs. Bell has never named names.
   The book recounts Bell's bitter, often losing struggles within
the administration on budget, personnel and policy with people whom
he regarded as conservative ideologues.
   Conservatives regarded Bell as a mole of the education
establishment in the Reagan Cabinet, a big-spending liberal who had
testified in 1978 in favor of creating the Education Department.
   If they needed any evidence to support those views, Bell
provides it in abundance in ``The Thirteenth Man.''
   ``Those who accused me of being part of the educational
establishment were right,'' said Bell, who had served two previous
stints in Washington, one as U.S. commissioner of education in the
Ford administration, between school posts in Utah.
   Bell calls for $25 billion in new federal, state and local
spending on the Chapter 1 remedial program for disadvantaged
students, Head Start, the pre-school program for poor children, and
the Job Corps.
   He said the country should attack the problems of illiteracy and
dropouts with ``a national movement of the magnitude of the
Marshall Plan that helped rebuild the war-ravaged nations of Europe
at the end of World War II.''
   But, he says, ``money by itself is not the answer. We cannot
ignore the other part of education, and that's the home and
family.''
   Bell's own life story is testimony to the power of both
education and the family.
   Bell grew up in poverty in Lava Hot Springs, Idaho. His father
died in an accident in 1929 when Bell was 8. His mother, Alta
Martin Bell, raised nine kids in the Depression on virtually no
money.
   When he graduated from high school as valedictorian he wore a
suit that, without his knowledge, Mrs. Bell had bought with money
donated by his teachers. He headed off to the college with the
lowest tuition in the state, Albion State Normal School. It charged
$11.50 per semester.
   ``My life at Albion opened richnesses beyond anything I ever
imagined,'' he recalls. ``I was ignorant of our own history and of
the great literature of the Western world. I knew nothing of the
Federalist Papers, the works of Tolstoy, or the rudiments of
economics. This all came to me courtesy of the taxpayers who
founded and supported a state normal school to prepare teachers to
teach their children and grandchildren.''
   It also came courtesy of President Franklin D. Roosevelt's New
Deal and the Congress, which supported the part-time National Youth
Administration job that paid him $17 a month _ enough to cover his
$4 rent and leave $13 for food, which his mother supplemented by
mailing four loaves of bread every Wednesday.
   His experiences at Albion, now defunct, made it all the harder
for Bell to support Reagan cuts in student aid, cuts he now says
were ``absolutely wrong.''
   Bell said that when he left Washington to return to Salt Lake
City, ``I had a nagging feeling of betrayal..I felt frustration at
not having been able to secure an enduring commitment to the cause
of education at the highest federal level.''
   On the positive side, he says, ``we are educating 60 to 70
percent of the youth of America better than in previous decades.''
College-entrance test scores have stopped sliding, states have
raised high school graduation requirements dramatically and
installed competency tests for both students and entry-level
teachers, and ``at least 30 states have taken steps to build career
ladders for teachers that reward distinguished teaching
performance.''
   But, he says, then there are the bottom 30 percent to 40 percent
of students for whom the push for school reform ``didn't do a darn
thing.''
   ``In my mind,'' he adds, ``nothing could have assured Ronald
Reagan's place in history more than his enduring commitment to the
school reform movement that he supported so effectively for 18
months, only to abandon it after the election.''
   ``Failure to educate millions of our people adequately will move
us toward disaster if we do not alter course,'' he warns.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 24</NOTE>
