<DOCNO> AP880411-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-FrenchElection Adv17-2Takes   04-11 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-French Election, Adv 17-2 Takes,0749</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>French Election: `What Will Change, Whoever Wins?'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LE FORNET, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the crumbling manor he shares with
his sheep, Adolphe Bonnevie frowns into his field glasses at a
France caught between star wars and Louis XIV. He is not cheered by
the presidential campaign around him.
   ``What will change, whoever wins?'' he asked, expressing a
common view of the likely re-election of Francois Mitterrand.
``What changed in the last seven years? More unemployment, the same
problems.''
   In Paris, lawyer Alain Spilliaert made a similar point:
   ``People believed in ideologies in 1981. They elected Mitterrand
as a Socialist, to bring about change. Now they see their problems
are beyond ideology. They'll vote for a person, not a party.''
   Across France, people echo Bonnevie's concerns over jobs,
technological competition, agriculture, education and urban
problems. Few are willing to express more than guarded optimism.
   Unemployment is 10.5 percent. Last year's trade deficit of $5.5
billion was 60 times higher than in 1986. Economic growth of 2
percent lags far behind Britain's.
   But more, Frenchmen see an erosion of culture and a breaking
down of the fabled art of living that once set France apart. Old
roots are dying, and new growth is too sparse.
   Around villages like Le Fornet, tucked away in a back corner of
the French Alps, the ``crisis'' takes tangible shape.
   Bonnevie, an aging farmer, owns most of the village, old stone
buildings, cobblestones and a patchwork of fields. He sits in the
sun and trains his binoculars on passersby. Most are in ski clothes.
   Le Fornet is three miles from Val d'Isere, which in preparing
for the 1992 Winter Olympics, has hurtled itself into the space age.
   A sleek train rockets skiers straight through the mountain, to
the top of La Daille. Val d'Isere's relaxed little main plaza has
vanished below a gigantic hotel-mall.
   The last remnants of the past, a stone home built in 1642, a
generation before Louis XIV, the Sun King, are hardly visible amid
a forest of garish signs.
   ``This is a ski factory,'' grumbles Jean-Francois Lamy, who sold
his Squaw Valley Hotel and is moving to Geneva. ``They have lost
all the flavor, the old way of life, and they'll never get it
back.''
   In Albertville, headquarters of 1992 Winter Olympics, old
regulars still shuffle into the Cafe des 4 Vallees and wait,
without a word, for Marcel to bring their ``petit blanc,'' their
glass of wine.
   But the cafe, redone in plastic and formica, no longer serves
France's hallowed melted ham and cheese sandwich, the croque
monsieur. Now there is a goopy microwaved substitute called
Love-Croquy, sold along with ``les Love Double Cheeseburger.''
   On Easter Sunday, the baker lady was selling brioches at Au
Peche Mignon.
   ``Mitterrand, someone else, what's the difference?'' she said,
with a merry laugh. ``I'm still working every weekend.''
   Down the mountain in Lyon, the heart of old-style France, a
conflict of ages is evident in the modern new neighborhood called
Part Dieu, which translates roughly to ``God's Little Acre.''
   Futuristic trains cut the old time in half, to two hours, from
Paris to Lyon's high-tech Part Dieu Station. But the Hertz
car-rental office closes four hours for Sunday lunch.
   The huge Mr. Chef cafeteria advertises, ``Open 11 a.m. to 9
p.m., even Sundays,'' but it closes for lunch, at 2:30 p.m.
   Campaign posters cover every flat surface of Part Dieu, but few
people questioned in the street say they think any of the
candidates can make headway against underlying problems.
   Most pictures show the jovial face of Raymond Barre, Lyon's
favorite son, who warns that any serious economic recovery will
take at least two years of job retraining.
   His rival conservative for the chance to run against Mitterrand
in the May 8 runoff is Premier Jacques Chirac, who argues roughly
the same thing with a flashier style.
   Posters also tout arch-conservative Jean-Marie Le Pen, who
argues foreign cultural pollution is taking France from the French.
As a dark horse, his ads call him: ``L'Outsider.''
   ``It makes no difference,'' said Andre Duranson, a Lyon driver
who prefers sports to politics. ``All of them want the same
thing.'' He patted his wallet pocket. ``They clean up, and then
they go.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
