<DOCNO> AP880411-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-FrenchElection Adv17-1stAdd   04-11 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-French Election, Adv 17-1st Add,0589</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LE FORNET: they go.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A malaise was reflected in l'Express magazine. A poll indicated
54 percent of a sample of the nation's elite thought France was in
decline.
   The country is finding it costly to retain the grandeur of
Charles de Gaulle's defiant defense and foreign policies.
   France is quietly moving closer to the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization. Recently, 1,000 U.S. Marines from the 6th Fleet came
ashore for a two-week exercise, the first on French soil since 1966.
   Economically, France is to blend into a unified European system
by 1992.
   ``Our motherland is France, but our future is Europe,''
Mitterrand put it.
   Less easily defined signs indicate a concern that traditional
French values and tastes are at risk.
   Le Pen's main plank is to send home immigrants, fueling racism
among those who worry that 2 million people of North African
extraction will curdle the melting pot.
   Ironically, Le Pen's far-right National Front has taken votes
from the Communist Party, replacing the old left as the place for
disgruntled workers to register their protest.
   Even dyed-in-the-wool Communist supporters expect their
candidate to poll less than 7 percent, half of their 1981 showing
and less than a third of their high-water mark after World War II.
   More generally, middle class French parents worry that youths
are growing up selfish, without depth or respect for traditions.
Few see campaign programs that might counter the trend.
   For a large number, it is a cultural vacuum, especially on
television.
   The two private channels licensed last year, amid great hoopla,
show only 24.5 percent original French programing. One offering is
Sexy Clips, in which nude couples stress togetherness in ways
outlawed in some American states.
   On ``La Roue de la Fortune,'' a perky Frenchwoman turns letters
for contestants who spin a giant wheel to decipher a blanked out
message. In French, the show's name means, ``The Wheel of Fortune.''
   There is also, ``Le Juste Prix'' _ ``The Price is Right.'' Both
French productions are licensed by the shows they copy.
   At 8 a.m., viewers choose among Daffy Duck, Andy Panda and Dan
Rather. The pay channel, Canal Plus, retransmits the CBS Evening
News in English at that time, and it is fast gaining popularity.
   Some Frenchmen worry that much of France is falling into foreign
hands.
   Foreigners bought up $1 billion worth of French real estate last
year, a fifth of the market.
   Japanese investors built an office complex at Montparnasse where
once Ernest Hemingway could barely afford a cup of coffee.
   Most important, people are caught in the middle as the country
meshes with the modern world, but old ways foul the gears.
   Mitterrand has made it clear that in a second term, he would set
aside Socialist dogma in favor of letting France find its own pace.
   He told an interviewer: ``The country is headed toward a
free-market economy, and so let's play it to the hilt. Let us have
no half measures.''
   But now there is ``OPA,'' an acronym, meaning corporate
takeover, that is a new French fad word.
   When Schneider S.A., a diversified holding company, tried to
take over the industrial automation group Telemecanique Electrique,
however, workers blocked it by marching in the streets _ the way
Frenchmen have done since the Revolution that broke the Sun King's
line.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880411-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--FilmReviews Adv00   04-11 1027</1ST_LINE>
