<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Beetlejuice''; ``The Seventh Sign''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Beetlejuice''
   
   Sometimes a devilishly dynamic performance lifts a movie out of
the ordinary. That happened last year with Jack Nicholson's satanic
furioso in ``The Witches of Eastwick.'' Now comes Michael Keaton in
the title role of ``Beetlejuice.''
   Keaton outroars a banshee. His head rotates with a velocity of
which Linda Blair never dreamed. He is so unspeakably, devotedly
evil that he becomes almost lovable. It's a great comic performance
that redeems the obvious crowd-grabbing strategy behind
``Beetlejuice.''
   Curiously, the movie begins much the same as ``The Witches of
Eastwick.'' The camera hovers over a picture-postcard New England
village and travels through the immaculate streets and freshly
painted buildings to focus on a hilltop house that looks a bit huge
for its surroundings.
   The occupants are a pair of cheerful yuppies, Alec Baldwin and
Geena Davis, whose main occupation appears to be puttering around
the mammoth house. Their work is interrupted when they drive into
town for supplies. On the return they swerve on a covered bridge,
land in the river and drown.
   Rather confusedly, they return to the house as ghosts slightly
less sophisticated than Cary Grant and Constance Bennett in
``Topper.'' Their lives continue much the the same, though
invisibly, until the house is sold to a New York developer, Jeffrey
Jones. He moves in with his death-obsessed daughter, Winona Ryder,
and his second wife, Catherine O'Hara, who is hellbent to transform
the house into a chic monstrosity.
   Alarmed by what is happening to their house, the yuppies seek
help from the after-life bureaucracy, a useless exercise. Finally,
they enlist the infamous Keaton who rises from his grave to
perpetrate his monstrous deeds.
   Director Tim Burton (``Pee-Wee's Big Adventure'') is a former
Disney animator, and his film has the kinetic energy of a cartoon.
There is also a synthetic plot, credited to Michael McDowell and
Warren Skaaren, which affords little of the logic needed for a
convincing fantasy.
   Unrecognizable in his weirdo makeup, Keaton behaves
outrageously; it's a marvelous characterization. Also helpful are
Jeffrey Jones (``Ferris Beuller's Day Off''), Catherine O'Hara
(``SCTV'') and Winona Ryder as the invaders.
   ``Beetlejuice'' was produced by Michael Bender, Larry Wilson and
Richard Hashimoto. The Warner Bros. release is rated PG, mostly for
its scare quotient. Running time: 92 minutes.
   _ By Bob Thomas, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Seventh Sign''
   
   An intense man walks purposely through the sands of a beach in
Haiti. He stares ponderously at the sea, breaks a small, round
token and tosses it and a piece of parchment into the water. Almost
immediately, sea life washes up _ dead.
   This purportedly foretells the coming of the apocalypse _ the
ultimate destruction of evil and triumph of good. It is the first
of seven signs, and in the Carl Schultz movie, ``The Seventh
Sign,'' only one woman can stop it.
   The woman is Demi Moore.
   Demi Moore? Demi Moore of the Brat Pack? Demi Moore who is also
Mrs. Bruce (``Moonlighting'') Willis? Demi Moore who is about as
compelling on screen as Gumby? What in the name of Boris Karloff is
she doing in a ``serious'' occult thriller?
   However, Moore's tepid performance in the Tri-Star Pictures
release is only one problem with this meandering and misguided
movie.
   One by one, the signs happen: A village is frozen in the middle
of the Negev desert; a river runs with blood; hail the size of a
baseball falls in Southern California; there's an unexpected
eclipse in which the moon becomes red. Interestingly enough, no one
in the news media, science or government takes any notice.
   The stranger (Jurgen Prochnow) rents a room from Russell and
Abby Quinn, who are played by Michael Biehn, who limps through his
role, and Moore.
   Abby, who is seven months pregnant, discovers more tokens and
parchments in his room and takes one of the pages to a rabbi for
translation. But she offends him and instead gets assistance from
the scholar's brash young neighbor, Avi (Manny Jacobs), who not
only tells her that she's up to her agnostic chin in the apocalypse
but also becomes her sidekick.
   Meanwhile, hot on the heels of the Quinn's boarder is a priest
named Lucci (Peter Friedman) who is investigating the strange signs
for the Vatican. Is he good or evil? If you can sit through another
20 minutes of the movie, you'll find out.
   While Abby tries to figure out how to stop the apocalypse, her
lawyer husband tries to save his client, Jimmy, from the gas
chamber.
   John Taylor, a 20-year-old who has Down's Syndrome, gives an
excellent and sensitive performance as the tormented Jimmy, who
killed his mother and father in God's name because they were
brother and sister _ incest was against the way of God.
   Abby has constant flashbacks to another time in history: little
flickers of a centurion; a tortured man of goodness; a woman
holding a water vessel. It's easy to figure out who is who and what
is what, especially since the movie was released during the
Easter-Passover season.
   What's not easy to figure out is why the filmmakers didn't pay
more attention to organization and sense in their production, and
plug in the many holes that make ``The Seventh Sign'' the eighth
wonder of muddled movies.
   The Interscope Communications Production, with a script by W.W.
Wicket and George Kaplan, is saved only by the lovely and dramatic
photography of Juan Ruiz Anchia and Stephen Marsh's sets. The movie
is rated R for strong adult themes and some nudity.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
