<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Fatal Attraction,'' that slice and dice lust
thriller starring Glenn Close and Michael Douglas, is finally being
released as a video from Paramount Home Video.
   The Academy Award-nominated movie _ for best picture, director,
actress and screenplay adapation _ was the film industry's biggest
moneymaker last year, selling $150 million worth of tickets in the
United States and Canada. With its themes of adultery, terror and
mental instability, it still draws lines at some movie theaters.
   If you missed this one on the big screen, you can buy it for the
small screen beginning June 1 (VHS@Beta, $89.95, Rated R).
   Paramount also is releasing a dubbed, English-language version
of the Oscar-nominated ``My Life as a Dog'' on April 20. The
subtitled original of the Swedish language movie by Lasse
Hallstrom, concerning a Swedish boy learning about life and death
in the 1950s, will be released on May 18 (VHS@Beta, $79.95).
   Out this week from MCA Video is one of the best contemporary
rock films ever made, ``Chuck Berry: Hail! Hail! Rock 'n' Roll''
(VHS, $79.95, Rated PG). When the tribute to the legendary Chuck
Berry premiered at last year's New York Film Festival, critics and
audiences cheered.
   Also on the market this month: ``Date With an Angel'' (HBO
Video, VHS, $89.99, Rated PG); ``Deadly Illusion'' (RCA-Columbia
Pictures Home Video, VHS@Beta, $79.95, Rated R); ``Flowers in the
Attic'' (New World Video, VHS, $89.95, Rated PG-13); and
``Dancers'' (Warner Home Video, $89.95, Rated PG).
   Videos reviewed this week:
   
   ``Dancers''
   
   When this Herbert Ross movie starring Mikhail Baryshnikov first
came out in October 1987, it pirouetted right off the screen after
a thrashing by critics.
   ``Dancers'' is not the greatest ballet movie ever made _ it will
never fill those red shoes. It was directed by Herbert Ross, who
also did ``The Turning Point,'' but falls short of his earlier
effort.
   Still, the movie seems to find a comfortable niche on the home
screen: Somehow, it's more believable and engaging.
   The plot revolves around Anton Sergeyev (Baryshnikov), the
world's star male dancer. He's also a ladykiller who's in Italy to
film a production of ``Giselle.'' There are sexual innuendoes and
flirtations and some excellent performances by the American Ballet
Theater.
   Leslie Browne, who starred with Baryshnikov in ``The Turning
Point, appears as Anton's ex-lover. The ABT's Alessandra Ferri also
co-stars.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Deadly Illusion''
   
   Get a giant cauldron, drop in Billy Dee Williams, Vanity and
Morgan Fairchild and what do you get? A soupy, unappetizing mess
called ``Deadly Illusion.''
   Williams plays a private detective with the improbable name of
Hamberger. His repeating line throughout the movie is, ``Please, no
jokes about the name.'' Vanity, whose leather and lingerie cover
her lousy acting, plays his girlfriend and assistant. Fairchild,
who has a brief, lusty romp with Williams, is the villain who sets
up Hamberger for murder.
   Hamberger, ever so friendly with the local police, is given 48
hours to prove his innocence (sound familiar?) and find the real
killer.
   Forget the action, forget the thrills: There aren't any. Nor is
there any slick dialogue in this movie written by Larry Cohen, who
co-directed with William Tannen.
   With two directors you'd think they'd be able to keep their
geography straight. Not these guys. They have Williams racing
through Rockefeller Center in midtown Manhattan. He looks over his
shoulder, turns a corner and in a blink is downtown in the Wall
Street area in the same chase scene. Not even the best marathon
runner could accomplish that.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
