<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0500</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out $5.3 billion more in
installment debt than they paid off in February for the third
consecutive strong monthly gain, the government said in a report
providing further evidence that consumers have not stopped spending.
   The Federal Reserve said Friday consumer debt increased at an
annual rate of 10.3 percent in February, down slightly from the
12.2 percent rate of growth in January. In that month, installment
debt had risen by $6.24 billion following a December increase of
$4.3 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tate & Lyle PLC, a major British sugar refiner and
distributor, made a $1.33 billion cash tender offer for Staley
Continental Inc., the second largest refiner of corn sweeteners in
the United States.
   Tate & Lyle, which already owns nearly 5 percent of Staley's
stock, said Friday it was offering $32 a share for all the
remaining common stock.
   Staley Continental, which is based in Rolling Meadows, Ill.,
said Sunday its board would review the bid and make a
recommendation to shareholders by April 21.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OIL CITY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group led by a New York-based
investment banking firm offered $695 million to buy Quaker State
Corp., the motor oil refining company.
   Ardshiel Inc. said Friday it was offering $26.50 per share for
the Oil City-based company, which refines and sells Quaker State
motor oil, owns Quaker State Minit-Lube Inc. drive-in automobile
lubrication centers, and manufactures truck lighting systems and
automobile brake lights.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group led by New York communications investor
Robert F.X. Sillerman agreed to buy Metropolitan Broadcasting
Holding Co., which owns seven radio stations and the Texas State
Radio Network.
   Sillerman said Friday his group will pay about $40 million to
the owners of the privately-held broadcasting concern and will
assume about $260 million in debt.
   The sale is subject to approval by the Federal Communications
Commission.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average retail price of gasoline rose by
more than a penny in the past two weeks, bringing the price roughly
even with where it was a year ago, according to an industry survey.
   The price increase for all grades of gasoline was 1.18 cents a
gallon, pushing the average price to 96.14 cents, according to the
Lundberg Survey of gasoline prices from stations around the United
States. The survey was released Sunday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government ruled that Japanese-made
forklift trucks are being exported to this country at ``less than
fair value,'' a major step toward ordering steep anti-dumping
duties on the vehicles.
   U.S. customs will be instructed to collect anti-dumping duties
ranging from 14 to nearly 57 percent, if the U.S. International
Trade Commission determines in the next 45 days that the Japanese
imports threaten material injury to domestic industry, a Commerce
Department announcement said Friday.
</TEXT>
