<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter
threatened retaliation after Japan blocked a U.S. request for
creation of an international panel to resolve a dispute over beef
and citrus imports.
   Yeutter also urged Japanese industrialists to use their
political clout to block the protectionist measures for which
Japan's farmers are lobbying.
   The Japanese move came Friday in Geneva at a session of GATT,
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than six months after the global market
collapse, Japanese stock prices have surged above pre-crash levels,
thanks to market resilience and renewed confidence in the country's
healthy economy.
   ``People have realized the Tokyo market has certain strengths,''
Simon Smithson at the Kleinwort Benson investment firm, said Friday.
   The Nikkei Average of 225 selected issues, which shed a modest
20.33 points last Friday, gained 175.98 points, or 0.65 percent
today, finishing the first day of the week at 26,924.87.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students from nearly 30 of the nation's
top business schools have expressed confidence about their career
outlooks and say the panic that pervaded campuses after the
stock-market crash has eased significantly.
   But some of the delegates at an annual conference of graduate
business students at Northwestern University said Friday Wall
Street investment banking has lost much of the allure it held
before the Oct. 19 market collapse.
   Many said they intend to pursue high-pay consulting jobs instead.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp., moving to
earn more money on its intellectual property, said it will raise
the ceiling on its patent license fees to 5 percent from the
current 1 percent.
   The decision, announced Friday, is likely to put pressure on the
profit margins of companies that require licenses to make products
compatible with those of IBM, the world's largest computer company.
   IBM holds 9,000 U.S. patents and more than 23,000 counterpart
patents worldwide.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reaping the benefits of tax reform,
President Reagan and his wife Nancy made more money and paid less
taxes last year than in 1986.
   The Reagans' tax liability for 1987 was $86,638, 25.1 percent of
their $345,359 gross income, it was disclosed Friday. In 1986,
their tax bill had been $92,460 on a total income of $336,640, or
27.5 percent.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rang up its fourth straight gain Friday with a
strong advance that carried the Dow Jones industrial average to a
new high since the October crash. The index of 30 industrial stocks
climbed 28.02 points to 2,090.19, bringing its gain for the week to
102.13 points.
   The dollar drifted lower while gold prices rose.
   Bond prices rebounded.
   Cattle futures advanced sharply, reflecting expectations of
improved beef demand.
</TEXT>
