<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PorkAds     04-11 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pork Ads,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pork Ads To Appear On All Star Game Telecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pork producers have bought six 30-second
television commercials for baseball's 1988 All Star Game on July
12, as part of a $1.36 million campaign to promote pork products
during a time of the year when sales traditionally are slow.
   The National Pork Board announced last week it had allocated the
funds for the summer promotion campaign, continuing last year's
theme of ``Pork _ the Other White Meat.''
   The June-August campaign will center on the All Star Game
sponsorship and will include the June distribution of sales
promotion kits to about 5,000 food stores that feature pork as a
part of summer activities.
   Barry Pfouts, director of the consumer product marketing group
of the National Pork Producers Council, said building the entire
summer consumer ad campaign around an event with such wide interest
would help reach a larger number of consumers and use promotion
funds contributed by pork producers more efficiently.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
