<DOCNO> AP880411-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 0734EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Smoking-Airlines     04-11 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Smoking-Airlines,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Smoking Group To Ask Airline Stockholders For Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARREN MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national anti-smoking group says it plans
to ask shareholders of major airlines to do what it says the
federal government has not done: enact a total ban on smoking
during all domestic flights.
   Ahron Leichtman, president of Citizens Against Tobacco Smoke,
said in a weekend interview the group will attempt to arrange
shareholder votes at major U.S. airlines over the issue.
   Leichtman said the new federal law that will ban smoking on
domestic airline flights of two hours or less beginning April 23 is
a good first step but contains loopholes.
   Because Congress used a time limit rather than mileage, airline
flights scheduled for just under two hours could escape compliance,
he said. Flight time can be altered by the rate of climb, flight
altitude, the type of aircraft being used, headwinds and the
schedule of the airports involved, Leichtman said.
   The federal ban on smoking during short-term flights will expire
in two years if Congress takes no further action, but Leichtman
doesn't expect that to happen. Nevertheless, his Cincinnati-based
group does not want to wait for two years to get further action.
   Leichmtan said the group planned to take the issue to the annual
stockholders' meetings of every major airline. In addition to
seeking a total smoking ban, the group wants airline executives to
designate 50 percent of all flights over two hours as smoke free.
   The group chose Minneapolis to announce its new strategy because
Northwest Airlines, based in the suburb of Eden Prairie, already
has banned smoking on nearly all of its domestic flights, Leichtman
said.
   He said the group planned to go to Miami, Dallas, Chicago,
Atlanta and tentatively Kansas City, where other major carriers are
based to raise questions about the health, safety, economic and
legal issues raised by passenger smoking on aircraft, he said.
   ``We are going to attempt to prove to the National
Transportation Safety Board that increased carbon monoxide levels
caused by smoking in airplanes puts a flight attendant at risk by
reducing the ability to think clearly,'' Leichtman said.
   He suggested that smokers be provided with nicotine gum or
nicotine pills if they could not otherwise physically handle
smoke-free flights.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880411-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 0739EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     04-11 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Advances In Europe, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in early European trading today as
investors positioned themselves for this week's meeting of finance
ministers from the major industrialized nations and the latest set
of U.S. trade figures.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   Dealers said they were expecting ministers from the seven major
industrialized nations to reaffirm their strong opposition to a
further decline of the dollar at their meeting in Washington
Wednesday.
   The meeting, in conjunction with the semi-annual meeting of the
International Monetary Fund and World Bank, wasn't likely to
generate any market-moving news, dealers said, but a reaffirmation
of a stable-dollar policy may still help the dollar.
   The market is also in a bullish mood because traders are
speculating on a narrower U.S. trade deficit for February _ between
$11 billion and $12 billion _ when figures are released on
Thursday, dealers said. January's deficit was $12.44 billion.
   ``In the long run, the dollar is heading upward, and this is
already influencing its medium-term trend,'' said Michael Schnirel,
foreign exchange dealer at Irving Trust Company in Frankfurt.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.53 yen to a closing 125.71 yen. Later, in
London, it rose to 126.42 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.6790 West German marks, up from 1.6725; 1.3916
Swiss francs, up from 1.3825; 5.7050 French francs, up from 5.6715;
1.88465 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8790; 1,246.80 Italian lire, up
from 1,241.75; and 1.2420 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2478
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.87 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.8755 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $450.40 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $450.15, both down from late Friday's bid of
$451.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $449.80, up from $449.50 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 84 cents to close at a bid
$451.95. Silver was quoted in London this morning at a bid price of
$6.43 a troy ounce, down from Friday's $6.48.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880411-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 0742EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     04-11 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Tokyo Stocks Hit New Closing High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo stock market indicator surged to a new
closing high today, while the U.S. dollar gained ground in trading
against the Japanese yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Average of 225 selected
issues, which shed a modest 20.33 points last Friday, gained 175.98
points, or 0.65 percent, finishing the first day of the week at
26,924.87.
   The Nikkei's close today surpassed the previous high set last
Thursday when it closed at 26,768.22. Monday's close was 278.44
points above its pre-crash best level of 26,646,43, set the week
before the worldwide stock market crash last October.
   ``Boosted by the last week's advance on Wall Street, the Nikkei
average went up to less than two points short of touching the
27,000-point level,'' said Fumihiko Morimoto of First Boston.
   The index reached 26,998.36 points, the highest ever, at one
time during the morning trade. Investors spread their buying
through most sectors amid bullish sentiment, traders said. The
dollar's stability dispelled whatever doubts investors may have had
about Tokyo stocks, they said.
   In the afternoon, however, Morimoto said concerns that the
market was rising too high prompted profit-taking, and the selling
eased prices a little.
   Advancing issues outpaced decliners 531 to 351, while 173 issues
were unchanged.
   Popular issues were electricals and precision machineries.
Constructions and housing stocks also rose. Insurances and
securities were firm. Volume of the first section trade was an
estimated 900 million shares, down from 1.5 billion shares last
Friday.
   In the foreign exchange trading, the dollar closed at 125.71
yen, up 0.53 yen from its close of 125.18 yen last week. It had
opened the day at 125.80 and traded between 125.68-125.83 yen.
   ``Trading was quiet and the dollar moved very little,'' said Ken
Iiya of the Bank of Tokyo.
   He said most participants watched from the sidelines, waiting
for results of the scheduled meeting in Washington this week of
monetary authorities from the seven major industrialized nations
and the announcement of U.S. trade figures for February.
