<DOCNO> AP880411-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-KansasCitySouthern     04-11 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kansas City Southern,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Confident $244 Million Antitrust Judgment Will Be
Overturned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kansas City Southern Industries Inc.
says an antitrust judgment of at least $244.2 million against the
company conflicts with a Supreme Court decision and likely will be
overturned.
   Landon H. Rowland, president and chief executive officer of
Kansas City Southern, said Saturday the jury award announced Friday
in South Dakota was ``a distressing result which was not expected,
in a matter which has been in progress for years.''
   In the case in federal court in Sioux Falls, S.D., a jury agreed
with the state of South Dakota's contention that the company's
railroad subsidiary, Kansas City Southern Lines, had conspired with
other railroads to block a coal slurry pipeline proposed by Energy
Transportation Systems Inc.
   The jury awarded South Dakota $200 million in antitrust damages,
which the company said would be tripled to $600 million under
federal law. But the jury also provided an alternative award of
$200 million for interference with contractual relations and $44.2
million in punitive and other damages.
   At the end of 1987 Kansas City Southern reported a net worth of
$361 million. The company has a workforce of about 2,500 in Kansas
City.
   Rowland cited a victory in a related case to bolster his
contention that the South Dakota judgment would be overturned on
appeal.
   Kansas City Southern successfully sued in 1982 to block the
federal government from providing water to the slurry pipeline
project. Energy Transportation Systems appealed, but higher courts
upheld the decision, including the Supreme Court in February.
   ``In view of the unanimous decision of the Supreme Court in the
ETSI case,'' Rowland said, ``we expect our position to be
vindicated.''
   The slurry pipeline was proposed to carry a mixture of
pulverized coal and water between Wyoming and several southern
states.
   South Dakota had a contract to supply the pipeline with water
from the Missouri River for 50 years, which would have brought $9
million a year in revenue to the state.
   The suit contended Kansas City Southern and others violated
federal antitrust laws in delaying the 1,400-mile, $3.8 billion
pipeline, which would have crossed railroad tracks. Attorneys for
the state produced a document that said Kansas City Southern was
designated to be the lead railroad to fight the project and the
water sale.
   Kansas City Southern argued that it opposed the pipeline, but
that there was no conspiracy. The company also contended that the
project was financially doomed regardless of South Dakota's water
contracts.
   The jury verdict came amid Kansas City Southern's quest to
acquire control of the Southern Pacific railroad. Kansas City
Southern has asked the Interstate Commerce Commission to reject a
competing offer from Rio Grande Industries Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
