<1ST_LINE>d f BC-EEC-Research     04-11 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Research,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Launches $2 Billion Hi-Tech Research Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Research ministers of the European Economic
Community on Monday agreed to spend about $2 billion over the next
five years on research in information technology.
   The plan, called ESPRIT II, is designed to help European
companies to compete against the United States and Japan.
   An EEC official said the program, which involves 5,500
researchers from 12 EEC countries, represents about one-third of
all European basic research in information technology.
   The official said ESPRIT research has led to numerous
technological achievements, including the development of T800, the
most powerful chip on the market.
   He said the current phase, which is to begin in late summer,
will continue to center on microelectronics and information
processing.
   Under EEC rules, the Community contributes 50 percent to the
cost of each project, with the rest coming from the member states.
   For the first time since 1984, when ESPRIT was launchhed, the
Community will allow non-member countries, mainly from Scandinavia,
to participate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
