<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Soviet-US-Trade     04-11 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Soviet-US-Trade,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commerce Secretary Heads U.S. Trade Delegation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Commerce Secretary William Verity and a
delegation of American businessmen arrived in Moscow on Monday for
superpower trade talks in advance of next month's summit here.
   Verity told reporters at Sheremetyevo Airport that Washington
``supports the expansion of peaceful, mutually beneficial trade and
economic relations'' with the Soviet Union an that he hoped this
week's meetings would produce new trade agreements.
   About 400 U.S. businessmen plan to take part in the 10th session
of the Joint Commercial Commission, formed in 1973 to bring trade
agencies of the two governments together.
   The trade meetings, which open Tuesday, come six weeks before
President Reagan travels to Moscow for his fourth summit with
Communist Party chief Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Gorbachev and Reagan called during their December meeting in
Washington for joint exploration of trade expansion prospects
during the next commission meeting.
   U.S. sales to the Soviet Union totaled $1.5 billion in 1987, or
only about 0.5 percent of all exports, and two thirds of the
business was in grain sales.
   The volume of U.S.-Soviet trade was three times larger in 1979,
before then-President Jimmy Carter imposed trade sanctions after
the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan.
   Verity said before leaving Washington that he did not expect
major breakthroughs during this month's commission meeting, but
that he hoped the talks would create ``a new climate'' in
superpower trade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
