<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed today on
the Chicago Board of Trade as dealers awaited two potentially
influential Agriculture Department reports.
   Wheat was slightly higher, corn was mostly lower and soybeans
were mixed in early trading.
   This afternoon's USDA supply and demand report was to contain
the government's grain usage estimates and projections for
stockpiles that will be carried over into the next marketing year.
   The USDA's world production report was to include the
government's new estimate for the Brazilian soybean crop, which has
suffered from dry conditions and is now being harvested.
   ``These reports will be coming out after the close and that is
causing some hesitancy here on the part of many traders,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 2\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.18 a bushel; corn was { cent
lower to \ cent higher with May at $2.08{ a bushel; oats were {
cent to 1{ cents higher with May at $1.67\ a bushel; soybeans were
1 cent lower to 1{ cents higher with May at $6.79{ a bushel.
   Livestock futures were higher but frozen pork bellies were lower
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent to .45 cent higher with April at 75.05
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .55 cent higher with
April at 80.52 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent to .40 cent higher
with April at 45.50 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
unchanged to .50 cent lower with May at 54.37 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher on Friday.
</TEXT>
