<HEAD>Quaker State Wants To Remain Independent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OIL CITY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Quaker State Corp. said Monday that it
wants to remain independent after receiving an unsolicited $675
million takeover bid from a group led by Ardshiel Inc., a New York
investment banking firm.
   ``My strong view is that is in the best interests of Quaker
State to remain independent,'' said Chairman Quentin E. Wood in a
statemen.
   The motor oil refining company made no other comment about the
proposal, submitted Friday by Ardshiel, other than to say it did
not contain definitive financing.
   Ardshiel said it was offering $26.50 per share for the Oil
City-based company, which sells Quaker State motor oil, owns Quaker
State Minit-Lube Inc. drive-in automobile lubrication centers, and
manufactures truck lighting systems and automobile brake lights.
   Ardshiel said it currently owns 3.3 percent interest in the
company. It did not disclose the identities of other investors.
   Dennis McCormick, Ardshiel's senior managing director, said
Ardshiel wanted to continue Quaker State's core businesses.
   Quaker State employs 6,300 people, including about 450 at its
headquarters and research centers in Oil City, a Venango County
community of 13,500. It also has refineries in Farmers Vally,
McKean County, and in Newell, W.Va.
</TEXT>
