<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1223EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-USG-DesertPartners     04-11 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-USG-Desert Partners,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Desert Partners Alters Bid For USG</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Desert Partners LP on Monday increased the
number of USG Corp. shares it is seeking to acquire in its $2.18
billion hostile takeover attempt.
   Under terms of an amended tender offer, Desert Partners said it
would pay $42 a share for 39 million USG shares, or 85 percent of
the building materials company, up from the 21.5 million shares it
initially sought for the same price.
   Remaining shares would be exchanged for securities and notes
valued at $42 a share. With 51.8 million USG shares outstanding,
the offer is valued at about $2.18 billion.
   Desert Partners, which owned a 9.9 percent stake in USG when it
launched the tender offer, said that about 12.6 million shares had
been tendered as of last Friday.
   The latest offer, made possible by additional financing
commitments, would not be subject to Delaware anti-takeover laws,
Desert Partners said in a statement. The offer is set to expire at
midnight EDT April 22.
   USG repeatedly has opposed Desert Partners' overtures and has
urged its stockholders to reject a slate of board candidates
recommended by the Texas group. Six of USG's 15 board seats are up
for election at the May 11 annual meeting.
   Last month, Chicago-based USG, a leading producer of gypsum
wallboard and other building materials, said it was considering
defensive strategies that might include the sale of a major block
of USG stock to a third party to block an unfriendly takeover.
   Separately, Desert Partners said it has received commitments for
$1 billion of the $1.4 billion needed for the offer, including $500
million each from Wells Fargo Bank and Chase Manhattan Bank. An
additional $300 million in subordinated debt will come from
subsidiaries of the Australia'd Elders IXL, which would receive
warrants to purchase up to 22 percent of the company surviving a
merger.
   Desert Partners, a limited partnership led by Texas oilmen Jack
E. Brown and Cyril Wagner Jr., said its offer is conditioned in
part upon the redemption of USG's poison pill. The partnership has
a lawsuit pending in Chicago seeking the elimination of USG's
poison pill rights.
</TEXT>
