<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Farmers-Batus     04-11 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Farmers-Batus,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers May Be Willing to Consider Batus Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Group Inc. said Monday it was willing
to discuss a takeover by Batus Inc. if Batus follows through on a
suggestion it may raise its $4.5 billion bid.
   Batus, the U.S. subsidiary of the British conglomerate B.A.T.
Industries, termed the letter ``an encouraging development'' and
said it welcomed the chance for negotiation.
   Farmers, the nation's third-largest home and auto insurer and
seventh-biggest property and casualty insurer, opened the door to
talks in a letter from Leo E. Denlea Jr., chairman and chief
executive officer.
   ``I am requesting hereby that you advise us without delay of any
higher offer you are prepared to make,'' Denlea wrote.
   Denlea offered to share confidential information disclosed to
other potential suitors if Batus agrees to confidentiality
guidelines. He set a Tuesday deadline for Batus' response.
   On March 3, Louisville, Ky.-based Batus launched an unsolicited
$63-a-share offer for the Los Angeles-based insurer. In a letter
Thursday, Batus Chairman Patrick Sheehey said the company would
consider increasing its offer if Farmers management would agree to
negotiate.
   The issue is complicated by a dispute between Batus and
insurance regulators in Kansas, one of nine states in which Farmers
owns insurance companies.
   A hearing is set for April 20 on a Kansas Insurance Department's
order that Batus stop soliciting proxies in support of a resolution
that would require Farmers directors to reconsider their earlier
refusal to negotiate.
   Kansas law requires regulatory approval of any change of control
of an insurer, and defines control partly as holding ``proxies
representing 10 percent or more of the voting securities.''
   ``We feel that we'll meet all the statutory requirements,''
Batus spokesman Wilson Wyatt said Monday.
   B.A.T., a tobacco, retailing and paper-goods conglomerate, has
been seeking a foothold in the U.S. financial services market for
some time.
</TEXT>
