<HEAD>Shearson Defends Role In Koppers Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. today defended its
role in the hostile takeover attempt of Koppers Co., and denounced
the ``bizarre allegation'' that Shearson, rather than a group led
by Beazer PLC, was trying to acquire Koppers.
   ``From an American Express Co. viewpoint, not only do we think
this to be a Shearson transaction and activity in the normal course
of its business, but we also view the uproar by some allies of
Koppers as ill-informed, provcative and ill-advised,'' Harry L.
Freeman, executive vice president of parent company American
Express, told the Senate Banking Committee.
   He said it was ill-informed because of the ``continued erroneous
assertion that that somehow Shearson, rather than Beazer, is trying
to acquire Koppers, which is simply not true and strikes the
management of American Express Co. as a bizarre allegation.''
   Freeman said it was unfair to characterize Shearson Lehman as
having taken an equity position in the takeover attempt. He said
Shearon Lehman was providing advice and bridge financing for the
transaction, both ``normal functions'' for U.S. investment banks.
   But Charles R. Pullin, chairman and chief executive officer of
Koppers, a Pittsburgh construction materials concern, said
Shearson@American Express ``has dominated and actively guided every
aspect of the planning and execution of the Koppers takeover
attempt since its secret initiation one year ago.''
   Beazer's unsolicited cash tenderpoffer of $45 a share on March 3
has since been sweetened to $60 per share.
   Brian C. Beazer, chairman and chief executive officer of the
British materials and construction firm that bears his name, told
the Senate panel, ``I am not a corporate raider.''
   Beazer said his firm was ``not the sort of organization that
seeks to put people out of work, far from it.''
   Commenting on Kopper's refusal to try to negotiate a merger
agreement, Beazer said, ``It appears to me that you can never know
anything aboet an opposing side until you at least can hear their
view.''
</TEXT>
