<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0023,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose sharply in thin trading Monday,
bolstered by positive weekend news from the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries and by a healthy rise in the U.S.
dollar.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 30.8
points, or 1.7 percent, higher at 1,810.5, its best level for the
day.
   Volume, however, was light at 405.4 million shares, down from
508.5 million on Friday.
   Share prices opened strongly, helped by recent rises in New York
and Tokyo.
   In addition, shares, especially in the oil sector, were helped
by news that representatives of OPEC and non-OPEC producers were to
meet to discuss ways to bolster the price of crude oil.
   Britain is the world's fifth-largest oil producer.
   The dollar's rise, and consequent fall in the value of the
pound, gave a lift to international stocks, and dealers said U.S.
buyers were seen in the market taking advantage of the more
favorable exchange rates.
   Dealers said stocks surged to their best levels late in the day
after the 100-share index held above the psychologically
significant level of 1,800 points for most of the session.
   ``The momentum of having broken through 1800 has carried us
on,'' a dealer said.
</TEXT>
