<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1448EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Manville-Storage     04-11 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Manville-Storage,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manville Opens Storage Center for Asbestos-Related Documents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pile of documents involving years of
asbestos-related suits against Manville Corp. has grown so large,
it needs its own warehouse.
   The company announced Monday that it began operation of a
storage plant for the paperwork _ 16 million documents in all.
   The warehouse operation in Englewood is available to those
involved in resolving asbestos health claims against the company.
It was established in cooperation with the Manville Personal Injury
Settlement Trust, the committees representing asbestos health
claimants and other interested parties.
   The trust was established under the Manville bankruptcy plan of
reorganization to settle asbestos health claims against the company.
   The former asbestos maker filed for protection from its
creditors under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws on Aug. 26,
1982. The bankruptcy court for the Southern District of New York
confirmed the company's plan of reorganization on Dec. 22, 1986.
   The company sought bankruptcy protection because of thousands of
lawsuits pending by victims of asbestos, which causes asbestosis,
an often-fatal lung disease. The victims are seeking billions of
dollars, and future claims are expected to develop.
   Experts testified that the claims totaled more than the
company's entire worth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
