<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Robins     04-11 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robins,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unsuccessful Buyer of Dalkon Shield Maker Seeks $34 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A.H. Robins Co. told a federal judge Monday
his decision to set $2.475 billion in compensation for Dalkon
Shield victims helped kill a pending buyout of the pharmaceutical
company.
   But a lawyer for Rorer Group Inc., which planned to acquire
Robins, told U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr. the judge's
ruling did not automatically destroy Robins' pact with Rorer.
   Merhige and U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Blackwell N. Shelley listened
to arguments on whether Robins should pay a $25 million
``break-up'' fee to Rorer plus $9 million in expenses associated
with the failed merger.
   The Rorer-Robins pact, negotiated last November, included the
$25 million fee to Rorer if the deal fell through. Its key
provision called for paying $1.75 billion to women who suffered
injuries from using the Dalkon Shield intrauterine device, which
Robins sold in the early 1970s.
   A month after the agreement was reached, Merhige determined that
$2.475 billion was needed for Dalkon Shield compensation.
   Dennis Drebsky, an attorney for Robins, said the agreement with
Rorer ``for all intents and purposes was a dead letter'' after the
higher compensation figure was established.
   ``They were Siamese twins, and when one of the twins died the
other went with it,'' Drebsky said of the Rorer merger and its
$1.75 billion compensation proposal.
   But Arthur L. Liman, the attorney for the Rorer Group, said his
company had the sole right to withdraw from the agreement when the
higher figure was set. Robins had no such right, he said.
   Also, Liman said Robins officials continued to negotiate with
Rorer executives after Merhige's decision as if the two firms could
adjust the terms of their deal to accomodate the larger
compensation.
   ``Robins knew the agreement was not dead,'' he said. ``It was
clinging to it'' in case talks with two other potential buyers, the
American Home Products Corp. of New York and the Paris-based Sanofi
SA, a major European pharmaceutical manufacturer, fell through.
   Robins accepted an American Home Products offer in late January.
   The judges did not rule immediately on Rorer's request for the
break-up fee, but Merhige said the Fort Washington, Pa. company
would not receive all the $9 million in expenses.
   Merhige interrupted arguments on the dispute for about two hours
Monday to allow the attorneys to try to work out a settlement, but
no deal was struck.
   Robins, the Richmond-based maker of the Robitussin series of
cough medicines and other pharmaceuticals, has been in federal
bankruptcy court under Chapter 11 protection from creditors since
August 1985.
   The chief issue in the company's reorganization has been
payments to some 195,000 women with injury claims because of the
IUD.
   Robins' merger with American Home Products and the Dalkon Shield
compensation package will be voted on by creditors after ballots
are mailed out April 25. Votes are due back July 11, and Merhige
has set July 18 for a hearing on confirmation of the reorganization
plan.
</TEXT>
