<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Goodyear     04-11 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Goodyear,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mercer Sees More Restructuring, More Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co.
told shareholders Monday that a top priority this year will be
eliminating about $3.6 billion in debt incurred in fending off Sir
James Goldsmith's 1986 takeover attempt.
   Robert E. Mercer also said he expected 1988 earnings to surpass
the $770.5 million earned last year, which included $257 million
from discontinued operations.
   At the shareholders' meeting, Mercer said that reducing debt
caused by Goodyear's anti-takeover stock buyback plan would require
several measures, including possibly divesting its interest in a
joint pipeline.
   Mercer said a recent court ruling permitting the final segment
of the All American Pipeline in Texas should enhance the sale
prospects.
   The pipeline is a project of Celeron Oil and Gas, a former
Goodyear subsidiary until it was sold last year as Goodyear
concentrated on its core tire business.
   ``Continuing advances in cost control, and keeping capital
expenditures as close to depreciation levels as is competitively
practical, should allow us to make some contribution to the debt
reduction this year from operating income,'' Mercer added. ``In our
assessment of the remainder of 1988, the global tire market looks
promising.''
   Meanwhile, Executive Vice President Stanley J. Mihelick
confirmed that Goodyear is considering building a new tire plant in
Canada.
   A 550-acre site in Napanee, Ontario, about 25 miles west of
Kingston, Ontario, could be home for a radial tire plant, subject
to working out details with Canadian authorities, he said.
   The Ontario government has approved a $32 million loan to assist
in establishing the plant.
   During the weekend, the United Rubber Workers union targeted
Goodyear for negotiations toward a three-year labor contract that
labor leaders say will set the tone for negotiations with the rest
of the industry.
   A 12-member advisory committee on Saturday unanimously chose
Goodyear over companies such as Firestone Tire & Rubber Co. as the
pattern-setting company, according to a news release from Milan
Stone, URW's international president.
</TEXT>
