<HEAD>Soybean Futures Close Higher; Grains Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures closed as much as 5 cents a
bushel higher Monday on the belief that a late-season dry spell had
seriously damaged the Brazilian soybean crop. Grain futures were
mixed to slightly higher.
   Trading activity was light ahead of two U.S. Department of
Agriculture reports on grain supply and demand and foreign crop
production.
   The world production report was expected to show a reduction of
0.5 million metric tons in the USDA's estimate of the Brazilian
soybean crop, which is now being harvested, said Jerry Gidel, an
analyst in Chicago with G.H. Miller & Co. The agency had previously
pegged the Brazilian harvest at 18.5 million tons.
   ``The market followed through here a little on the deterioration
of the Brazilian crop,'' Gidel said.
   Wheat futures closed mostly higher while corn was narrowly mixed.
   At the close, wheat was \ cent lower to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.17{ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
lower to } cent higher with May at $2.07} a bushel; oats were
unchanged to 1{ cents higher with May at $1.67} a bushel; soybeans
were 1 cent to 5 cents higher with May at $6.83 a bushel.
