<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ChineseBillboards Bjt   04-11 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chinese Billboards, Bjt,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nixon Relative Helps Swing Billboard Deal in China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Nixon opened China to Americans in the
early 1970s. Now his son-in-law is opening China to more and better
advertising billboards.
   China's eagerness to put up more billboards is a sign of
progress in the Communist nation, Edward Cox said Monday in
announcing a deal between China and Patrick Media Group Inc. of
Scranton, Pa.
   ``If you're going to have a market-oriented economy, the most
important thing is free passing of information, and advertising is
a big part of that,'' Cox said in an interview.
   Cox, a finance lawyer and the husband of Patricia Nixon Cox,
acted as a go-between on behalf of Patrick Media, which bills
itself as the world's largest outdoor advertising company.
   Patrick Media will give the Chinese advice on such matters as
standardizing the sizes of billboards, upgrading its paint and
attracting business from non-Chinese advertisers.
   ``An initiative like this, like sports or arts, transcends
advertising or business. It goes to the germ of our being,'' said
Gerard P. Joyce, the company's 36-year-old president and chief
executive.
   With more than 1 billion consumers and only about 7,000
billboards, China is ``a little more naked'' than the United
States, Joyce said, meaning that each advertising message has more
impact.
   China hopes to increase its number of billboards to 10,000
within five years, said Zhao Guihong, general manager of the China
National United Advertising Corp., which is responsible for almost
all Chinese advertising billboards.
   Zhao is leading a group of Chinese advertising officials in a
nine-day, six-city tour of Patrick Media's U.S. operations. Others
on the tour include regional officials from Shanghai, Nanjing,
Beijing and Chengdu.
   Outdoor advertising accounts for about 25 percent of advertising
expenditures in China, compared to less than 2 percent in the
United States, Patrick Media said. One reason is that Chinese
characters can be understood by all literate Chinese regardless of
the language or dialect they speak.
   Cox said he approached Zhao's group last year on behalf of
Patrick Media. He said the contact was a sidelight to the main
purpose of his visit, which was to visit China as an emissary for
former President Nixon, who wanted to ascertain whether economic
reforms were continuing.
   Cox said large-character posters are protected by the Chinese
constitution. ``It used to be a political message,'' he said. ``Now
the message is an advertising message.''
   Joyce declined to say how Patrick Media would be paid for its
services. He said the matter was still under negotiation. Patrick
Media will act as exclusive adviser to the Chinese on all outdoor
advertising joint venture operations.
   Joyce founded Patrick Media at age 18 and remains its majority
shareholder. The company swelled from a three-market operation into
a $200 million-a-year giantwhen he engineered the $710 million
acquisition of the assets of Foster and Kleiser from Metromedia
Inc. in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
