<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1618EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Trade     04-11 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Trade,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Trade Deficit Declines From 1987 Level, Widens From March
Figure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's trade surplus continued to decline from
year-earlier levels in March, although it widened from February's
surplus, the Finance Ministry announced Monday.
   The surplus totaled $7.458 billion, down from $8.050 billion in
March 1987, bu up from $5.238 billion the previous month.
   After seasonal adjustment, the surplus came to $6.552 billion,
up from $6.479 billion in the previous month.
   Japan registered a trade surplus of $3.4 billion with the United
States, down from $3.77 billion a year earlier.
   Finance Ministry officials characterized the figures as
encouraging because of the year-to-year decline.
   The continuing shrinkage in the latest report was attributed to
the high yen, which has slowed the growth of exports while boosting
the yen's purchasing power and the value of imports flowing into
the country.
   Imports surged much faster than exports, rising 35 percent to
$15.21 billion from $11.26 billion a year earlier.
   Exports grew by a comparatively muted 17.4 percent to $22.67
billion from $19.31 billion a year earlier.
   Seasonally adjusted imports in the month dipped 3.9 percent to
$14.76 billion from $15.36 billion in February, while adjusted
exports inched down 2.4 percent to $21.31 billion from $21.84
billion.
   Exports to the United States rose 15.8 percent to $7.17 billion,
while American imports rose 55.8 percent to $3.77 billion.
   Motor vehicle imports from the United States soared 112.7
percent from a year earlier to $20.01 million. Food imports rose
47.1 percent to $805.1 million, while textile imports surged 87.8
percent to $78.6 million.
   Japan's exports of passenger vehicles to the United States rose
56 percent to $1.29 billion. Overall electrical machinery exports
were up 11.4 percent to $1.57 billion, although television set
exports fell 23 percent to $27.38 million.
</TEXT>
