<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Banks     04-11 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Banks,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Posts 84 Percent Profit Jump in 1st-Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp. said Monday its first-quarter
profit jumped 83 percent as tax benefits combined with strong
growth in interest income and other gains more than offset a rise
in costs.
   The company, which is fighting a hostile takeover bid from Bank
of New York Co., said its profit rose to $52.4 million, or $2.71 a
share, in the first quarter compared with $28.6 million, or $1.51 a
share, a year earlier.
   Chairman Joseph A. Rice said the results included $12.3 million
in tax benefits related to the loan-loss provisions that the
company took in 1987 in anticipation of problems in collecting some
Third World loans.
   Net interest income rose 12 percent to $146.9 million from
$131.2 million a year earlier as the difference between what the
bank paid in interest to obtain funds and what it received on its
money widened in the banking company's favor.
   In the quarter, Irving took a provision for credit losses of
$19.6 million in 1988 compared with $21.8 million in 1987. That
left its loan loss allowance at $696.5 million, or 4.38 percent of
loans, compared with $224.8 million, or 1.62 percent of loans, a
year earlier.
   Noninterest income increased 16 percent to $119 million from
$102.6 million a year earlier, including a 24 percent rise in trust
income. Securities trading generated revenue of $6.3 million in
contrast with a loss of $2.8 million a year earlier.
   Noninterest expenses rose 11 percent to $179 million, including
a 10 percent rise in salary and employee benefits.
   Irving said earlier this month that it expects to earn $234
million in all of 1988 in contrast to a loss of $193.2 million a
year earlier.
   It is trying to convince its shareholders to reject Bank of New
York's $1.08 billion tender offer of cash and securities for all of
Irving's stock.
   Bank of New York is offering 1.575 shares of its own stock and
$15 a share in cash for each of the 18.4 million shares of Irving
stock that it doesn't already own.
   But Irving has argued that its advisers rate the offer as
inadequate.
</TEXT>
