<2ND_LINE>AM-FERC Resignation,0135</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FERC Loses Member</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   C. Michael Naeve will leave the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission to rejoin his old law firm on April 30, the
commission announced Monday.
   Naeve, who had announced his intention to resign in February,
submitted his letter of resignation to President Reagan on April 6,
the commission said.
   One of the two Democrats on the five-member panel regulating
interstate oil and natural gas pipelines and wholesale electricity
sales, Naeve is rejoining the firm of Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher
and Flom, which he left to take a four-year appointment to the
commission in 1985.
   His departure will leave the commission with two holdover
members, Chairman Martha Hesse and Charles Stalon, and two members
whose terms expire in October, Charles Trabandt and Anthony Sousa.
</TEXT>
