<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1750EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Boeing-Defects     04-11 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boeing-Defects,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing Plans News Conference on Reports of Defects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. declined Monday to comment on reports
that four major airlines had reported defects in the aerospace
company's 747 and 767 widebody jets.
   The problems reportedly ranged from wrong parts to incorrectly
installed firefighting systems.
   T. Craig Martin, a spokesman for Boeing's commercial airplane
division, deflected questions about the reports, saying the company
planned to hold a news conference Tuesday to discuss the matter.
   The newspaper accounts said Boeing had received complaints of
defects from American Airlines, Japan Air Lines, All Nippon Airways
and British Airways.
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer said Monday that All Nippon, a
Japanese domestic carrier, disclosed it told Boeing of several
instances of poor workmanship in 747 and 767 airliners, mostly on
newly delivered planes.
   The problems included a wing flap disintegrating in flight on
the first day of service, smoke from a misassembled power unit that
caused an emergency landing, and problems in a fire extinguisher
system, All Nippon said.
   Dean Thornton, head of Boeing Commercial Airplanes, was quoted
by the newspaper as saying a jetliner ``is a big complicated piece
of machinery.''
   The complaints were ``isolated instances that shouldn't
happen,'' he said. ``We're gonna bust our butt to make sure they
don't happen again.''
   Yoshiyuki Funatsu, All Nippon executive vice president, told the
Post-Intelligencer that problems with defects had been increasing
recently at Boeing. He said that while many had been minor, some
had safety ramifications, although none of the defects had caused
accidents.
   Bob Baker, American Airlines' senior vice president for
operations, told the newspaper the company's maintenance crews had
found faulty fire-suppression systems in the cargo holds of three
767-200s. The system pipes fire-fighting chemicals to the forward
and aft compartments of the cargo hold.
   ``The pipes were misrouted,'' Baker said. ``If you light them
off for the forward belly system they go off in the rear.''
   Baker said that after being informed of the problem by American,
Boeing found one faulty system on its production line and All
Nippon and Japan Air Lines found several in their planes.
   Last week, it was reported that Japan Air Lines President Susumu
Yamaji had complained of manufacturing mistakes in a March 30
letter to Boeing Chairman Frank Shrontz. Besides the fire
extinguisher system, the airline complained about engine
temperature sensors being installed in reverse order in a 747,
which would cause temperature gauges to register for the wrong
engines.
   In its Saturday editions, the Seattle Times published excerpts
from a letter from D.K. Craig, British Airways' chief engineer for
technical and quality services, to Phil Condit, executive vice
president of Boeing Commercial Airplanes.
   Craig said British Airways inspectors at Boeing's plant found
problems in their jets ranging from missing fasteners to wrong or
missing parts. One missing part caused the floor of a jet to bow so
much that a main deck cargo power drive unit would not work, the
Times said.
   ``My quality inspectors can only properly inspect a very small
proportion of each aircraft,'' Craig wrote. ``They should never
ever come across ... missing fasteners, missing parts, cracks,
bodged rivets, fasterners fitted the wrong way round. Yet we find
instances of some of these on every aircraft.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
