<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Chrysler-Kenosha Bjt   04-11 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chrysler-Kenosha, Bjt,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to fix typo in slug</HEAD>
<HEAD>Study Says Chrysler Plant Closing To Cost Taxpayers $209 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp.'s planned closing of its
Kenosha auto plant would cost $209 million in welfare and
unemployment benefits, along with lost taxes, for the first two
years after the shutdown, a union-commissioned study concluded
Monday.
   The analysis by the Midwest Center for Labor Research in Chicago
estimated that the plant's closing would cost federal, state and
local governments a total of $38,000 for each unemployed Chrysler
worker.
   Chrysler announced in January it plans to end auto production at
Kenosha by Sept. 30, resulting in the layoffs of 5,500 workers.
Chrysler took over the plant last year as part of its purchase of
American Motors Corp.
   ``Of about the two dozen studies that we've done, that's the
highest figure we've ever come up with,'' Greg LeRoy, MCLR research
director, told a news conference at the United Auto Workers Local
72 headquarters.
   LeRoy said the study, which was commissioned by the union local,
was based on a previous MCLR study in 1985 but used more
comprehensive welfare and employment figures from the state,
Kenosha and Racine counties and the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics.
   It estimated that the plant's closing would result in $62.4
million in unemployment compensation, $54.5 million in lost federal
income tax revenue, $26 million in lost Social Security tax
revenue, $21.4 million in welfare expenditures and $17 million in
lost state sales and excise tax revenue.
   Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson has threatened to sue Chrysler,
claiming the Detroit-based automaker broke a promise to keep the
plant open for five years.
   Chrysler officials have said they may have been overly
optimistic when negotiating with the state for improvements and job
training funds, but have repeatedly denied making any such promise.
   The study indicated that 53.1 percent of the Kenosha workers
would still be unemployed two years after the plant's closing.
   In addition, the study estimated that 9,796 other workers in the
state would be dislocated by the shutdown. Most of those jobs would
be in companies that supply Chrysler as well as people in retail,
service and other jobs supported by the buying power of Chrysler
workers.
   ``In an economy like this, the absorbtion rate just isn't there.
If jobs aren't there, people aren't going to get re-employed,''
LeRoy said.
   He said the figures for Kenosha were higher than those in other
communities hit by large plant shutdowns because of several
different factors in the southeastern Wisconsin economy and in the
status of unionized Chrysler workers. Among the differences he
cited:
   _Kenosha has an above average unemployment rate which has
remained above the national average for several years.
   _The area is strongly dependent on employment at the plant. More
than one-third of the area's total jobs would be lost with the
shutdown.
   _Chrysler workers make above average salaries and wages,
$29,120, and have benefits that many other potential employers in
Kenosha do not have.
   _Unionized workers in general have a harder time finding new
employment.
   LeRoy said the study also estimated that Chrysler workers would
experience a loss in living standards within the first two years.
With welfare and compensation benefits and new employment, the
worker's average income in the second year would still decline by
77.5 percent, he said.
   Local 72 negotiator Rudy Kuzel said the union commissioned the
study as a public service. ``Some people in the public perceive
this as a problem for the workers in the plant and don't realize
it's going to cost them a lot of money also,'' he said.
   Kuzel said the study would be sent to state and local officials
to aid in negotiations with Chrysler.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880411-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1910EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AT&T-Unix     04-11 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AT&T-Unix,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T Makes Unix Software Easier To Use</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AT&T on Monday announced changes to make it
easier for customers to use computers based on its Unix operating
system.
   The new Open Look feature of Unix software will allow users to
manipulate the computer with graphic symbols instead of written
commands, American Telephone & Telegraph Co. said.
   The changes represent another step toward acceptance of Unix in
the business world. Until recently, Unix was seen as mainly for
science and engineering.
   Open Look was designed for AT&T by Sun Microsystems Inc., the
burgeoning maker of engineering workstations based in Mountain
View, Calif.
   Sun's design is based on original work, contributions from AT&T
and technology licensed from Xerox Corp., which originated many of
the ideas for graphic screen symbols, the companies said.
   The Open Look screen somewhat resembles that of Apple Computer
Inc.'s Macintosh. Apple, famed for the ease of use of its
computers, has been fighting to protect its turf and recently sued
Microsoft Corp. and Hewlett-Packard Co. over a software copyright
issue.
   Apple spokeswoman Brooke Cohan said the company had no comment
on the AT&T announcement.
   Unix is a base layer of software in a computer that serves as a
traffic cop for its internal operations. Open Look is a ``user
interface,'' which determines the look and feel of a computer to
someone sitting at the keyboard.
   A wide range of companies endorsed Open Look, including software
makers such as Lotus Development Corp., Ashton-Tate Corp. and
Oracle Corp.; computer makers such as Unisys Corp., Amdahl Corp.
and NCR Corp., and chip makers such as Motorola Inc. and National
Semiconductor Corp.
   AT&T will circulate specifications of Open Look for comment
starting this summer and will make the available in the year's
third quarter. Software that is written to use Open Look will be
available mainly in 1989 and after.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
