<HEAD>French Industrial Group Makes Offer For Vinyl Siding Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French industrial group said Monday it
began a $75.9 million tender offer for Wolverine Technologies Inc.,
a maker of vinyl siding and windows for the home remodeling
industry.
   The $23-a-share bid by SG Acquisition Corp., a subsidiary of
Compagnie de Saint-Gobain, topped a March 16 offer of $18.50 a
share by Ply-Gem Industries Inc.
   Wolverine had agreed to be acquired by Ply-Gen, but the company
said its board would consider Saint-Gobain's bid.
   The Saint-Gobain offer extends through May 6 and is conditional
on at least 2.1 million of Wolverine's 3.3 million outstanding
shares being tendered, said Toney File, a Saint-Gobain spokesman in
New York.
   Saint-Gobain manufactures industrial products including flat
glass, insulation, containers, fiber reinforcement, industrial
ceramics, pipe and machinery, and includes a contracting and
services unit.
   It has more than 300 plants and 140,000 employees in 17
countries.
