<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1927EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Grolier-Hachette     04-11 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grolier-Hachette,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grolier Agrees To $448 Million Acquisition By French Publisher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grolier Inc.'s board of directors on Monday
unanimously accepted a $448.6 million cash takeover offer from
French media giant Hachette SA.
   Under the definitive merger agreement announced on Sunday,
Hachette, France's biggest publisher and the second-largest in
Europe, would pay $24.25 cash per share for the roughly 95 percent
of Grolier's 19.5 million common shares it does not already own.
   Grolier also granted Hachette the option to acquire about 18.5
percent of its outstanding common stock for $24.25 per share under
certain conditions. Such ``lockup options'' commonly are used to
discourage competing bidders.
   The definitive agreement marks the second time Hachette has
sweetened its offer for Grolier. The French company initially
offered $21 a share for Grolier on March 13, later sweetening the
bid to $24 a share after Grolier rejected the initial offer as
inadequate.
   Hachette, which has indicated it chiefly was interested in
Grolier's encyclopedia publishing business, said Friday it had
agreed to sell Grolier's Childcraft Education Corp. to Walt Disney
Co. for $52 million if its takeover bid succeeded. Childcraft
markets educational toys by direct mail.
   Spokesman Amory Hall said that agreement would remain in force
under the definitive merger proposal.
   Grolier is an international publisher of encyclopedias,
reference and educational books,juvenile books and furniture, trade
publications and yearbooks. Grolier also owns Mystic Color Labs, a
mail-order film processor.
   The company has about 7,200 employees.
   Grolier posted a profit of $22.1 million on revenue of $424.2
million in its 1987 fiscal year, up from net income of $12.5
million on revenue of $350.6 million the previous year.
   The 162-year-old Hachette, which reported sales of more than $3
billion in 1987, has operations i book and magazine publishing and
distribution, radio broadcasting, movie and television production
and outdoor advertising.
   Hachette publishes magazines such as Elle, Paris Match and a new
French edition of Fortune, and owns Curtis Circulation Co., which
it describes as the second largest national magazine distributor in
the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880411-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1927EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-DowJones     04-11 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Dow Jones,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts 55 Percent Rise in 1st-Qtr Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Jones & Co. Inc. said its first-quarter
profit climbed 55.3 percent from a year ago as its revenue rose
37.5 percent and the company reported a huge gain on the sale of a
book publishing subsidiary.
   Dow Jones, the publisher of the Wall Street Journal and
Barron's, said its profit amounted to $103.6 million, or $1.08 a
share, in the three months ended March 31 compared with $66.7
million, or 69 cents a share, a year ago.
   First-quarter revenue rose to $392.5 million from $285.6 million
a year earlier.
   The latest results included an after-tax gain of $64.5 million
from the previously reported sale of the book publisher Richard D.
Irwin Inc. for $135 million. First-quarter results in 1987 included
an after-tax gain of $29.4 million, or 30 cents a share, from the
sale of the company's 18.9 percent interest in the South China
Morning Post Ltd.
   Excluding those gains for each period, earnings were up 4.8
percent to $39.2 million in the latest quarter compared with $37.4
million a year earlier.
   Operating income for the quarter rose 54.2 percent to $91.1
million from $59.1 million in 1987.
   The company said the increase in operating income reflected
contributions from Telerate Inc., the electronic financial
information service that is 56 percent owned by Dow Jones, and the
continued growth of Dow Jones' community newspapers.
   Operating income in the business publications segment fell 22.7
percent to $32.6 million as revenue slipped 4.6 percent in the
quarter, partly reflecting lower levels of financial advertising in
the wake of the October stock market crash.
   Operating income from the information services segment which
includes Telerate results more than fourfold to $54.3 million as
revenue more than tripled.
   Ottaway Newspapers Inc., the community services segment, said
its operating income rose 3.7 percent to $8.5 million as revenue
rose 11.5 percent.
</TEXT>
