<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 2057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BankAmerica-Defense     04-11 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BankAmerica-Defense,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BankAmerica Adopts Takeover Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BankAmerica Corp., which bitterly fought
off one hostile takeover bid two years ago and could become a
target again, adopted a takeover defense plan on Monday.
   BankAmerica's board of directors said the preferred share
purchase rights plan was intended to protect shareholders ``in the
event of partial tender offers, squeeze-outs, and other abusive
tactics to gain control of BankAmerica without paying all
stockholders a premium.''
   The plan would make a hostile takeover prohibitively expensive
by allowing BankAmerica common shareholders to acquire a new issue
of preferred stock in the event a party acquired 20 percent of the
company's common shares or launched a tender offer to acquire 20
percent or more.
   BankAmerica is the nation's third-largest bank holding company,
following No. 1 Citicorp and Chase Manhattan Corp., both of New
York.
   A.W. Clausen, BankAmerica's chairman, said the plan was not in
reaction to any specific buyout proposal. He noted that hundreds of
other companies had adopted similar plans.
   BankAmerica stock closed down 12{ cents to $11 a share Monday on
the New York Stock Exchange.
   First Interstate Corp., based in Los Angeles, waged a lengthy
and bitter hostile bid for BankAmerica beginning in 1986, but gave
up its chase last year in the face of a major BankAmerica
restructuring that the suitor said diminished the value of its
target.
   ``I don't know why they took this action at this point, except
that maybe the time to do it is when you don't need to,'' Dan B.
Williams of San Francisco-based Sutro & Co. Inc., said of
BankAmerica. ``Maybe they just want to be prepared.''
   Nevertheless, Williams added, if the company did not have
further major problems with its troubled Third World debt portfolio
it might be able to produce a string of profitable performances
that could make it an attractive target.
   Separately, Bank of America announced the formation of three
regional capital markets operations to serve Europe, the Americas
and Asia. Each will be responsible for trading, merchant banking
and investment banking activities in its respective region.
   ``We're reorganizing our operation from product-oriented to
geography-oriented,'' said bank spokesman Jim Mitchell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
