<DOCNO> AP880411-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 2135EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Wheeling-Pittsburgh     04-11 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wheeling-Pittsburgh,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steelmaker Allowed To Sell Most Of Idled Monessen Mill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp. can sell most
of its idled mill in Monessen to Sharon Steel Corp., a federal
bankruptcy judge ruled Monday.
   The $18.1 million deal, approved by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Warren
Bentz in Erie, is unusual because both companies are reorganizing
under federal bankruptcy laws.
   The deal does not include a $120 million rail mill that is to be
sold in three months by the federal agency that financed and later
foreclosed on it.
   Sharon's offer, which edged out four other bids, was for
Monessen's coke ovens, raw steelmaking facilities and continuous
bloom caster, a piece of equipment that produces semi-finished
products.
   Sharon has until May 15 to complete the purchase, but has
reserved the right to back out of the deal if the Environmental
Protection Agency and Judge Hubert Teitelbaum refuse to grant
temporary relief from pollution control standards imposed on coke
operations at the Westmoreland County mill.
   Attorneys for Wheeling-Pittsburgh and its creditors said Sharon
Steel's offer was best, partly because the steelmaker would provide
a ready market for the coke. They also said Wheeling-Pittsburgh
would be better able to press any financial claims against another
company that was reorganizing under Chapter 11 of the federal
bankruptcy law than against one that was not.
   Walter Sieckman, Sharon Steel's chief executive, said his
company's plans to reopen the coke ovens will bring back about 150
jobs. The ovens were idled in June 1986 but kept partially fired to
prevent their brick linings from deteriorating.
   A restart of the operations also would enable Sharon Steel to
recall about 90 to 100 of its own workers who were laid off last
week when a shortfall of coke _ a necessary ingredient in
steelmaking _ caused the company to temporarily idle one of its two
blast furnaces.
   Sharon Steel purchases coke on the open market, but has been
unable to fill its requirements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
